  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data science team needs a foundation model deployment on Amazon Bedrock that guarantees consistent, low-latency inference throughput for a production workload with predictable traffic. Which Bedrock feature addresses this need?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A prompt engineer is trying to improve a foundation model's accuracy on a multi-step math problem by instructing the model to explicitly describe each reasoning step before providing the final answer. Which prompting technique is being applied?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Zero-shot prompting"},{"id":"b","text":"Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG)"},{"id":"c","text":"Few-shot prompting"},{"id":"d","text":"Chain-of-thought prompting"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["d"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines chain-of-thought prompting as asking 'the model to reason step by step,' which precisely describes explicitly eliciting intermediate reasoning steps before a final answer. Zero-shot prompting provides no examples or special instructions. RAG injects retrieved documents into the prompt context. Few-shot prompting provides input-output examples but does not inherently require visible step-by-step reasoning. Only chain-of-thought targets the explicit verbalization of reasoning steps.$patch$, $patch$Fundamentals of Generative AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/prompt-engineering-guidelines.html","label":"Prompt Engineering – Chain-of-Thought (AWS)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'AIF-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A prompt engineer is trying to improve a foundation model's accuracy on a multi-step math problem by instructing the model to explicitly describe each reasoning step before providing the final answer. Which prompting technique is being applied?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A machine learning engineer at a financial services company wants to ensure that an AI system built on Amazon Bedrock does not respond to any questions about competitor products. Which Amazon Bedrock Guardrails policy should they configure to enforce this restriction?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Content filters"},{"id":"b","text":"Sensitive information filters"},{"id":"c","text":"Denied topics"},{"id":"d","text":"Contextual grounding checks"},{"id":"e","text":"Automated Reasoning checks"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the AWS Bedrock Guardrails documentation, 'Denied topics' allow you to define topics that are undesirable in your specific application context — making it the correct choice for blocking all responses about competitor products. Content filters address harmful content categories (Hate, Violence, etc.) and are not designed for business-context topic restrictions. Sensitive information filters handle PII redaction. Contextual grounding checks detect hallucinations in RAG pipelines. Automated Reasoning checks validate responses against logical rules.$patch$, $patch$Guidelines for Responsible AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/guardrails-components.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock Guardrails – Denied topics"},{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/machine-learning/responsible-ai/","label":"AWS Responsible AI – Controllability"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'AIF-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A machine learning engineer at a financial services company wants to ensure that an AI system built on Amazon Bedrock does not respond to any questions about competitor products. Which Amazon Bedrock Guardrails policy should they configure to enforce this restriction?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An AI product team has deployed a Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) application using Amazon Bedrock. They are concerned that the model may sometimes produce responses that are not supported by the retrieved documents. Which Amazon Bedrock Guardrails feature directly addresses this concern by scoring how well the response is grounded in the retrieved source?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Word filters"},{"id":"b","text":"Contextual grounding checks"},{"id":"c","text":"Content filters"},{"id":"d","text":"Amazon SageMaker Model Monitor"},{"id":"e","text":"Automated Reasoning checks"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that 'Contextual grounding checks detect hallucinations by scoring whether model responses are grounded in retrieved source (for RAG) and relevant to the user query.' This is the feature purpose-built to detect ungrounded or hallucinated outputs in RAG workflows. Word filters block specific words or phrases. Content filters handle harmful-content categories. SageMaker Model Monitor detects data drift and inaccurate predictions in production but does not score grounding of individual responses. Automated Reasoning checks validate responses against logical rules, not source document grounding.$patch$, $patch$Guidelines for Responsible AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/guardrails-grounding.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock Guardrails – Contextual grounding checks"},{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/machine-learning/responsible-ai/","label":"AWS Responsible AI – Veracity and Robustness"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'AIF-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An AI product team has deployed a Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) application using Amazon Bedrock. They are concerned that the model may sometimes produce responses that are not supported by the retrieved documents. Which Amazon Bedrock Guardrails feature directly addresses this concern by scoring how well the response is grounded in the retrieved source?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data scientist needs to evaluate and compare multiple foundation models (FMs) on Amazon Bedrock before selecting one for a customer-service chatbot. The evaluation must measure accuracy, robustness, and toxicity using both automated metrics and human reviewers. Which AWS service is purpose-built for this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Amazon SageMaker Clarify"},{"id":"b","text":"Amazon SageMaker Ground Truth"},{"id":"c","text":"Model Evaluation on Amazon Bedrock"},{"id":"d","text":"Amazon Bedrock Guardrails"},{"id":"e","text":"Amazon SageMaker Model Monitor"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Model Evaluation on Amazon Bedrock: evaluate, compare, and select the best FMs for a use case based on custom metrics such as accuracy, robustness, and toxicity. Supports automatic and human-based evaluation.' This directly satisfies all three requirements: evaluation across multiple FMs, custom metrics including toxicity, and both automated and human-based evaluation modes. SageMaker Clarify focuses on bias detection and explainability for traditional ML models. SageMaker Ground Truth applies human feedback (RLHF) during training but does not provide structured FM comparison. Bedrock Guardrails enforces runtime safety policies. SageMaker Model Monitor tracks production data drift.$patch$, $patch$Guidelines for Responsible AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/model-evaluation.html","label":"Model evaluation on Amazon Bedrock"},{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/machine-learning/responsible-ai/","label":"AWS Responsible AI – Safety"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'AIF-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data scientist needs to evaluate and compare multiple foundation models (FMs) on Amazon Bedrock before selecting one for a customer-service chatbot. The evaluation must measure accuracy, robustness, and toxicity using both automated metrics and human reviewers. Which AWS service is purpose-built for this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A compliance officer at a healthcare company wants to understand the intended use cases, known limitations, and responsible AI design choices behind an AWS managed AI service before approving it for use. Which AWS artifact is specifically designed to provide this level of transparency for each AWS AI service?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"AWS Shared Responsibility Model documentation"},{"id":"b","text":"Amazon SageMaker Model Cards"},{"id":"c","text":"AWS AI Service Cards"},{"id":"d","text":"AWS Well-Architected Framework – Machine Learning Lens"},{"id":"e","text":"Amazon Bedrock Guardrails policy summary"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines AI Service Cards as 'AWS-published transparency documents describing intended use cases, limitations, responsible AI design choices, and performance optimization best practices for each AI service.' This maps directly to what the compliance officer needs. SageMaker Model Cards document a specific customer-trained model's intended use, training data, and evaluation results — they are customer-authored, not AWS-published service-level documents. The Shared Responsibility Model addresses security divisions of responsibility, not AI-specific transparency. The Well-Architected ML Lens provides architectural best practices rather than service-specific responsible AI details. Bedrock Guardrails policy summaries describe runtime safety configurations, not service transparency.$patch$, $patch$Guidelines for Responsible AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/machine-learning/responsible-ai/resources/","label":"AWS AI Service Cards"},{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/machine-learning/responsible-ai/","label":"AWS Responsible AI – Transparency"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'AIF-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A compliance officer at a healthcare company wants to understand the intended use cases, known limitations, and responsible AI design choices behind an AWS managed AI service before approving it for use. Which AWS artifact is specifically designed to provide this level of transparency for each AWS AI service?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A development team building a generative AI application on Amazon Bedrock wants to test whether their guardrail configuration correctly blocks a specific prohibited user input — without actually invoking a foundation model and incurring inference costs. Which Amazon Bedrock feature allows them to evaluate content against a guardrail independently of any FM invocation?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Denied topics policy"},{"id":"b","text":"Contextual grounding checks"},{"id":"c","text":"ApplyGuardrail API"},{"id":"d","text":"Model Evaluation on Amazon Bedrock"},{"id":"e","text":"Amazon SageMaker Clarify"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'ApplyGuardrail API: evaluate input or output against a guardrail without invoking an FM.' This is precisely the capability the team needs — testing a guardrail configuration against specific inputs without triggering a full model inference call. Denied topics is a guardrail policy type, not an API for standalone testing. Contextual grounding checks score grounding in RAG responses and require a response to evaluate. Model Evaluation on Amazon Bedrock compares FMs on predefined metrics, which would still require FM invocations. SageMaker Clarify handles bias detection and explainability for traditional ML pipelines.$patch$, $patch$Guidelines for Responsible AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/guardrails-apply.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock Guardrails – ApplyGuardrail API"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/guardrails.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock Guardrails overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'AIF-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A development team building a generative AI application on Amazon Bedrock wants to test whether their guardrail configuration correctly blocks a specific prohibited user input — without actually invoking a foundation model and incurring inference costs. Which Amazon Bedrock feature allows them to evaluate content against a guardrail independently of any FM invocation?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An ML team wants to detect bias in their loan-approval model at three stages: during data preparation, immediately after training, and continuously in the deployed production endpoint. Which AWS service provides bias detection capabilities across all three of these lifecycle stages?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Amazon SageMaker Ground Truth"},{"id":"b","text":"Amazon SageMaker Model Monitor"},{"id":"c","text":"Amazon SageMaker Clarify"},{"id":"d","text":"Amazon Bedrock Guardrails"},{"id":"e","text":"AWS AI Service Cards"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material specifies that 'Amazon SageMaker Clarify: bias detection during data preparation, after model training, and in the deployed model; explainability for stakeholder transparency (SHAP values, feature attribution).' This is the only service listed that explicitly covers all three lifecycle stages requested. SageMaker Ground Truth handles human labeling and RLHF feedback but does not perform bias detection. SageMaker Model Monitor detects data drift and inaccurate predictions in production but is not described as covering bias during data preparation or post-training evaluation. Bedrock Guardrails enforces runtime content policies for generative AI, not bias analysis in supervised ML models. AI Service Cards are documentation artifacts, not runtime analysis tools.$patch$, $patch$Guidelines for Responsible AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sagemaker/latest/dg/clarify-configure-processing-jobs.html","label":"Amazon SageMaker Clarify – Bias detection and explainability"},{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/machine-learning/responsible-ai/","label":"AWS Responsible AI – Fairness"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'AIF-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An ML team wants to detect bias in their loan-approval model at three stages: during data preparation, immediately after training, and continuously in the deployed production endpoint. Which AWS service provides bias detection capabilities across all three of these lifecycle stages?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$According to the AWS Responsible AI framework, a team discovers that their deployed image-recognition model performs significantly worse for users from certain demographic groups compared to others. Which responsible AI dimension does this gap most directly violate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Transparency"},{"id":"b","text":"Controllability"},{"id":"c","text":"Fairness"},{"id":"d","text":"Veracity and Robustness"},{"id":"e","text":"Governance"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The AWS Responsible AI framework defines Fairness as 'Considering impacts on different groups of stakeholders.' A model that performs substantially worse for a specific demographic group is failing to equitably serve all groups of stakeholders — a direct violation of the Fairness dimension. Transparency involves enabling stakeholders to make informed choices about their engagement with an AI system, not differential performance across groups. Controllability concerns monitoring and steering AI behavior, not the equity of outcomes. Veracity and Robustness addresses correct outputs even under unexpected or adversarial inputs, which is different from systematic demographic performance disparity. Governance relates to incorporating best practices across the AI supply chain.$patch$, $patch$Guidelines for Responsible AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/machine-learning/responsible-ai/","label":"AWS Responsible AI – Fairness"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sagemaker/latest/dg/clarify-detect-data-bias.html","label":"Amazon SageMaker Clarify – Detecting bias"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'AIF-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$According to the AWS Responsible AI framework, a team discovers that their deployed image-recognition model performs significantly worse for users from certain demographic groups compared to others. Which responsible AI dimension does this gap most directly violate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A generative AI application built on Amazon Bedrock must prevent users from submitting their social security numbers (SSNs) and dates of birth in the prompt, and must also mask any such data that appears in model responses. Which Amazon Bedrock Guardrails policy type should be configured to meet this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Content filters targeting the Misconduct category"},{"id":"b","text":"Sensitive information filters"},{"id":"c","text":"Word filters"},{"id":"d","text":"Denied topics"},{"id":"e","text":"Automated Reasoning checks"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that 'Sensitive information filters: block or mask PII (SSN, DOB, address, etc.) and custom regex patterns.' SSNs and dates of birth are explicitly listed examples of PII handled by this policy type, and it supports both blocking input and masking output — matching all requirements. Word filters block specific exact words or phrases, which is not suitable for dynamic PII like SSNs and DOBs that vary per user. Content filters target harmful-content categories such as Hate, Violence, and Misconduct — not personal data. Denied topics restrict application-context topics, not data types. Automated Reasoning checks validate logical consistency of responses, not PII presence.$patch$, $patch$Guidelines for Responsible AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/guardrails-sensitive-information-filter.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock Guardrails – Sensitive information filters"},{"url":"https://aws.amazon.com/machine-learning/responsible-ai/","label":"AWS Responsible AI – Privacy and Security"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'AIF-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A generative AI application built on Amazon Bedrock must prevent users from submitting their social security numbers (SSNs) and dates of birth in the prompt, and must also mask any such data that appears in model responses. Which Amazon Bedrock Guardrails policy type should be configured to meet this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer wants to ensure that all Amazon Bedrock API calls made in their AWS account are recorded for audit purposes. Which AWS service should they enable to capture a log of every InvokeModel and management API call made against Bedrock?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Amazon CloudWatch Metrics"},{"id":"b","text":"AWS CloudTrail"},{"id":"c","text":"AWS Config"},{"id":"d","text":"Amazon VPC Flow Logs"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the Amazon Bedrock security documentation, AWS CloudTrail logs all Bedrock InvokeModel and management API calls for audit purposes. CloudWatch Metrics provides performance and operational data but does not record individual API calls as an audit trail. AWS Config tracks configuration changes to resources, not API-level invocation logs. VPC Flow Logs capture network traffic metadata at the VPC level, not Bedrock API activity.$patch$, $patch$Security, Compliance, and Governance for AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/security.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock Security – Logging and Monitoring"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/logging-using-cloudtrail.html","label":"Logging Amazon Bedrock API calls with AWS CloudTrail"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'AIF-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer wants to ensure that all Amazon Bedrock API calls made in their AWS account are recorded for audit purposes. Which AWS service should they enable to capture a log of every InvokeModel and management API call made against Bedrock?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A healthcare company is deploying a generative AI chatbot on Amazon Bedrock and must ensure that patient data (such as Social Security Numbers and dates of birth) is never exposed in model responses. Which Amazon Bedrock feature should they configure to automatically detect and mask this information?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Bedrock model invocation logging with S3 output"},{"id":"b","text":"Bedrock Guardrails – Sensitive information filter"},{"id":"c","text":"Bedrock Guardrails – Word filters"},{"id":"d","text":"AWS KMS customer-managed keys for encryption at rest"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The Bedrock Guardrails documentation explicitly states that the Sensitive information filter 'detects PII entities (SSN, DOB, address, phone, email, etc.) and configurable regex patterns; can block or mask.' This is the correct control for preventing PII exposure in model inputs and outputs. Word filters are designed to block specific terms (e.g., competitor names), not PII. Invocation logging captures payloads for auditing but does not mask PII in responses. KMS encryption protects data at rest, not content within model responses.$patch$, $patch$Security, Compliance, and Governance for AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/guardrails-sensitive-info-filter.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock Guardrails – Sensitive Information Filters"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/guardrails.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock Guardrails Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'AIF-C01-P1'
