INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company wants to prevent Amazon Bedrock traffic from traversing the public internet when its applications call the Bedrock API from within their AWS VPC. Which networking solution should they implement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure a NAT Gateway to route outbound Bedrock traffic"},{"id":"b","text":"Use an internet-facing Application Load Balancer in front of Bedrock endpoints"},{"id":"c","text":"Create a VPC endpoint using AWS PrivateLink for Amazon Bedrock"},{"id":"d","text":"Enable TLS 1.3 on all Bedrock API calls"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source documentation states: 'VPC endpoints / PrivateLink: keep traffic to Bedrock and SageMaker on the AWS backbone without traversing the public internet.' A VPC endpoint powered by AWS PrivateLink allows applications inside a VPC to reach Bedrock APIs privately, with no internet gateway or NAT device required. A NAT Gateway still routes traffic over the public internet. An internet-facing ALB increases exposure to the public internet rather than reducing it. Enabling TLS 1.3 encrypts data in transit but does not change the network path — traffic would still traverse the internet.$patch$, $patch$Security, Compliance, and Governance for AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/usingVPC.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock – Interface VPC Endpoints (AWS PrivateLink)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/security.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock Security"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'AIF-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company wants to prevent Amazon Bedrock traffic from traversing the public internet when its applications call the Bedrock API from within their AWS VPC. Which networking solution should they implement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An AI platform team is concerned that end-users might attempt to manipulate a Bedrock-powered chatbot through prompt injection attacks. Which Amazon Bedrock Guardrails filter is specifically designed to detect and block these attempts?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Sensitive information filter"},{"id":"b","text":"Word filter with a custom denylist"},{"id":"c","text":"Prompt Attack content filter"},{"id":"d","text":"Bedrock model invocation logging with PII masking"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The Bedrock Guardrails documentation explicitly names the 'Prompt Attack content filter' as the control that 'detects attempts at prompt injection and jailbreak.' The Sensitive information filter targets PII exposure, not adversarial prompt manipulation. Word filters block specific terms from a denylist, such as competitor names — they cannot detect the semantic intent of an injection attack. Invocation logging with PII masking is a monitoring and data-protection control, not an active inference-time defense against prompt attacks.$patch$, $patch$Security, Compliance, and Governance for AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/guardrails-prompt-attack.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock Guardrails – Prompt Attacks"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/guardrails.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock Guardrails Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
