INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A large enterprise runs multiple AI experimentation teams and wants to enforce strict workload isolation so that one team's Amazon Bedrock usage and data cannot affect another team's environment. According to AWS governance best practices, what is the recommended organizational approach?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create separate IAM roles for each team within a single AWS account and use resource-based policies to isolate access"},{"id":"b","text":"Use multiple AWS accounts (via AWS Organizations) to isolate AI workloads by team or environment"},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy separate VPCs per team within a single account and use VPC peering for inter-team communication"},{"id":"d","text":"Assign unique KMS CMKs per team within a single account to achieve workload isolation"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source governance best practices section explicitly recommends: 'Use multiple AWS accounts (Organizations) to isolate AI workloads by team or environment.' Account-level isolation is the strongest boundary AWS provides and also enables per-team billing, service quotas, and blast-radius containment. IAM roles within a single account (option A) can limit permissions but do not provide full workload isolation — a misconfigured policy or compromised role could expose another team's resources. Separate VPCs (option C) provide network isolation but all resources still share the same account boundary, service limits, and potential IAM trust paths. KMS CMKs (option D) protect data confidentiality but do not isolate compute, quotas, or management planes between teams.$patch$, $patch$Security, Compliance, and Governance for AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/security.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock – Governance Best Practices"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/organizations/latest/userguide/orgs_best-practices.html","label":"AWS Organizations – Best Practices for Organizing Accounts"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'AIF-C01-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A large enterprise runs multiple AI experimentation teams and wants to enforce strict workload isolation so that one team's Amazon Bedrock usage and data cannot affect another team's environment. According to AWS governance best practices, what is the recommended organizational approach?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A compliance officer asks whether Amazon Bedrock uses customer-submitted prompts and model completions to train or improve the underlying foundation models. Based on AWS documentation, what is the correct answer?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Yes, prompts and completions are used to continuously fine-tune the foundation models unless the customer opts out."},{"id":"b","text":"Yes, AWS uses aggregated, anonymized customer prompts to improve model safety filters only."},{"id":"c","text":"No, customer prompts and completions are NOT used to train the underlying foundation models."},{"id":"d","text":"It depends on the foundation model provider; third-party models may use the data unless a separate DPA is signed."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Customer data privacy in Bedrock: customer prompts and completions are NOT used to train the underlying foundation models. Data is encrypted in transit and at rest. Provisioned models are isolated per account.' This is an important compliance and data-privacy assurance for regulated industries. Options A and B contradict this documented guarantee. Option D introduces a nuance not supported by the source material; the documented policy applies to Bedrock-hosted models, and customers should also review individual model provider terms, but the baseline AWS assurance is clear.$patch$, $patch$Security, Compliance, and Governance for AI$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/data-protection.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock – Data Privacy and Security"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/bedrock/latest/userguide/security.html","label":"Amazon Bedrock Security"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
