-- DEA-C01-P2: 4 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data engineering team stores five years of archived clickstream logs in Amazon S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval. Compliance requirements now mandate that these objects cannot be deleted or overwritten for a minimum of seven years from their creation date, and even storage administrators must be prevented from circumventing this rule. Which S3 feature and retention mode should the team apply to satisfy this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"S3 Versioning with MFA Delete enabled"},{"id":"b","text":"S3 Object Lock in Governance mode with a seven-year retention period"},{"id":"c","text":"S3 Object Lock in Compliance mode with a seven-year retention period"},{"id":"d","text":"S3 Lifecycle policy that transitions objects to Glacier Deep Archive and blocks expiration for seven years"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that S3 Object Lock provides WORM (write-once-read-many) protection with two retention modes: Governance and Compliance. Governance mode allows users with special IAM permissions to bypass or shorten the retention period, meaning a privileged administrator could still delete objects. Compliance mode, by contrast, prevents ANY user — including the root account — from deleting or overwriting a protected object before the retention period expires, making it the only mode that satisfies a strict regulatory mandate where even administrators must be blocked. S3 Versioning with MFA Delete protects against accidental deletion but does not enforce a time-based, tamper-proof retention window. A Lifecycle policy controls storage-class transitions and object expiration scheduling but provides no WORM enforcement and can be modified or deleted by an administrator at any time.$patch$, $patch$Data Store Management$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/object-lock-overview.html","label":"Amazon S3 Object Lock overview – AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/object-lock-overview.html#object-lock-retention-modes","label":"S3 Object Lock: Governance vs. Compliance retention modes"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DEA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data engineering team stores five years of archived clickstream logs in Amazon S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval. Compliance requirements now mandate that these objects cannot be deleted or overwritten for a minimum of seven years from their creation date, and even storage administrators must be prevented from circumventing this rule. Which S3 feature and retention mode should the team apply to satisfy this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An analytics team runs a multi-node Amazon Redshift cluster. Their workload consists of large fact tables that are frequently joined to several small dimension tables (each under 2 GB). Query plans show significant data movement across nodes during these joins, causing high network I/O. Which combination of Redshift distribution styles will best eliminate this inter-node data movement for the described join pattern?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Apply EVEN distribution to the fact table and EVEN distribution to all dimension tables."},{"id":"b","text":"Apply KEY distribution to the fact table on the join column and KEY distribution to each dimension table on the same join column."},{"id":"c","text":"Apply KEY distribution to the fact table on the join column and ALL distribution to each small dimension table."},{"id":"d","text":"Apply AUTO distribution to the fact table and ALL distribution to each small dimension table, allowing Redshift to override AUTO with EVEN at runtime."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material describes four Redshift distribution styles: KEY collocates rows from joining tables on the same node by a specified key; EVEN distributes rows round-robin with no join awareness; ALL replicates an entire table to every compute node; and AUTO lets Redshift choose. For a star-schema join between a large fact table and small dimension tables, the recommended best practice is to distribute the fact table by KEY on the join column so that related fact rows land on the same node, and to distribute each small dimension table with ALL so that a complete copy of the dimension table exists on every node. This means every node already holds both the relevant fact rows and the entire dimension table locally, eliminating cross-node data movement (broadcast or redistribution) entirely. Option A (EVEN/EVEN) distributes rows with no join affinity, guaranteeing redistribution at query time. Option B (KEY/KEY) works when two large tables join on the same key but is impractical for multiple dimension tables each with different join keys and adds overhead for small tables. Option D is incorrect because AUTO does not override itself to EVEN at runtime based on a partner table's style; AUTO is a design-time setting and would not guarantee KEY colocation with the fact table.$patch$, $patch$Data Store Management$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/latest/dg/c_best-practices-best-dist-key.html","label":"Choosing the best distribution style – Amazon Redshift Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/latest/dg/c_choosing_dist_sort.html","label":"Distribution styles – Amazon Redshift Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DEA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An analytics team runs a multi-node Amazon Redshift cluster. Their workload consists of large fact tables that are frequently joined to several small dimension tables (each under 2 GB). Query plans show significant data movement across nodes during these joins, causing high network I/O. Which combination of Redshift distribution styles will best eliminate this inter-node data movement for the described join pattern?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data engineering team has built an AWS Step Functions state machine to orchestrate a multi-step ETL pipeline. One of the states calls an AWS Glue job that can take anywhere from 10 minutes to 2 hours to complete. The team wants the state machine to pause execution and only advance to the next state after the Glue job has fully finished — without polling or introducing unnecessary wait loops. Which Step Functions service integration pattern should they use for this Glue Task state?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Request Response (default) — call the Glue StartJobRun API and immediately transition to the next state."},{"id":"b","text":"Run a Job (.sync) — call the Glue StartJobRun API and pause the state machine until the Glue job reaches a terminal state."},{"id":"c","text":"Wait for Callback (.waitForTaskToken) — pass a task token to Glue and have Glue send the token back to Step Functions via SendTaskSuccess when the job finishes."},{"id":"d","text":"Parallel state — run the Glue job inside a Parallel branch so Step Functions can monitor multiple branches concurrently."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly identifies the 'Run a Job (.sync)' integration pattern as the correct choice when you need to 'call an AWS service, wait for job to complete,' listing AWS Glue as one of the optimized services that support this pattern (alongside Athena, EMR, SageMaker, ECS, etc.). With .sync, Step Functions polls the Glue job status internally and only advances to the next state once the job reaches a terminal state (SUCCEEDED, FAILED, STOPPED), with no custom polling logic required in the workflow definition.

Why the other options are wrong:
• (a) Request Response is the default pattern: it fires the API call and immediately moves to the next state — the state machine does not wait for the Glue job to finish, which would cause downstream states to execute before the ETL data is ready.
• (c) Wait for Callback (.waitForTaskToken) is designed for asynchronous, human-in-the-loop, or external-system scenarios where Step Functions must pause until an external process calls SendTaskSuccess/SendTaskFailure with the token. Glue natively supports .sync, making the callback pattern unnecessarily complex for this use case.
• (d) A Parallel state enables concurrent execution of independent branches; it does not change how a single Task state waits for a service call to complete, and adding a Parallel wrapper does not solve the synchronization problem.$patch$, $patch$Data Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/step-functions/latest/dg/concepts-service-integrations.html","label":"AWS Step Functions — Service Integration Patterns"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/step-functions/latest/dg/concepts-service-integrations.html#supported-services-glue","label":"AWS Step Functions — Optimized Integrations (AWS Glue)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/glue/latest/dg/orchestrate-using-step-functions.html","label":"AWS Glue — Using Step Functions to orchestrate Glue jobs (.sync pattern)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DEA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data engineering team has built an AWS Step Functions state machine to orchestrate a multi-step ETL pipeline. One of the states calls an AWS Glue job that can take anywhere from 10 minutes to 2 hours to complete. The team wants the state machine to pause execution and only advance to the next state after the Glue job has fully finished — without polling or introducing unnecessary wait loops. Which Step Functions service integration pattern should they use for this Glue Task state?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data engineering team manages a large AWS data lake with hundreds of S3-backed tables registered in the AWS Glue Data Catalog. Different analyst groups require access to overlapping subsets of tables, and the security team wants to avoid managing hundreds of individual table-level Lake Formation grants. Which Lake Formation feature BEST addresses this scalability challenge by allowing permissions to be defined once and automatically applied to any resource sharing a common attribute?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Lake Formation data filters with row-level predicate expressions applied per table"},{"id":"b","text":"LF-Tags (tag-based access control / TBAC), where tags are attached to databases, tables, or columns and grant policies reference tag key-value attributes"},{"id":"c","text":"S3 bucket policies with IAM condition keys matching table prefixes for each analyst group"},{"id":"d","text":"AWS IAM Identity Center permission sets scoped to individual Glue Data Catalog table ARNs"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'LF-Tags (tag-based access control / TBAC): attach tags to databases/tables/columns; grant policies based on tag attributes; scales to thousands of resources.' TBAC decouples permission grants from individual resource names — an administrator attaches a tag (e.g., domain=finance) to every relevant table, then grants an IAM principal access to any resource carrying that tag. When new tables are added and tagged, they automatically inherit the correct access controls with no additional grant statements. This is the purpose-built Lake Formation mechanism for scaling governance across large catalogs.

Option A (data filters) is incorrect in this context: data filters address row- and cell-level security for restricting *what data rows or columns* a user sees within a table, not for managing *which tables* a principal can access at scale.

Option C (S3 bucket policies) is incorrect because bucket policies operate at the S3 layer and cannot natively reference Glue Data Catalog metadata or Lake Formation's fine-grained permission model; managing hundreds of prefix-based conditions also does not scale cleanly.

Option D (IAM Identity Center permission sets scoped to individual table ARNs) would require creating and updating a permission set per table per group — precisely the per-resource management overhead that TBAC is designed to eliminate. The source notes IAM Identity Center for centralized identity but not as a replacement for Lake Formation TBAC scalability.$patch$, $patch$Data Security and Governance$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lake-formation/latest/dg/tag-based-access-control.html","label":"AWS Lake Formation Tag-Based Access Control (LF-Tags)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lake-formation/latest/dg/access-control-overview.html","label":"AWS Lake Formation Permissions Overview"},{"url":"https://d1.awsstatic.com/training-and-certification/docs-data-engineer-associate/AWS-Certified-Data-Engineer-Associate_Exam-Guide.pdf","label":"AWS Certified Data Engineer – Associate Exam Guide (DEA-C01)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DEA-C01-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data engineering team manages a large AWS data lake with hundreds of S3-backed tables registered in the AWS Glue Data Catalog. Different analyst groups require access to overlapping subsets of tables, and the security team wants to avoid managing hundreds of individual table-level Lake Formation grants. Which Lake Formation feature BEST addresses this scalability challenge by allowing permissions to be defined once and automatically applied to any resource sharing a common attribute?$patch$);

