INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data engineering team stores raw clickstream data in Amazon S3. The data is accessed frequently for the first 30 days, rarely accessed between 31 and 90 days, and almost never accessed after 90 days. The team wants to minimize storage costs automatically without managing manual transitions and without incurring retrieval fees during the infrequent-access phase. Which S3 storage class BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"S3 Standard-IA with a Lifecycle policy transitioning objects to S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval after 90 days"},{"id":"b","text":"S3 Intelligent-Tiering, which automatically moves objects between Frequent, Infrequent, and archive tiers based on access patterns with no retrieval fees in the Frequent and Infrequent tiers"},{"id":"c","text":"S3 Glacier Instant Retrieval configured from day one for all incoming objects"},{"id":"d","text":"S3 Express One Zone to maximize throughput and then expire objects after 90 days"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'S3 Intelligent-Tiering: auto-moves objects between Frequent, Infrequent, Archive Instant, Archive, Deep Archive tiers based on access patterns. No retrieval fees in Frequent/Infrequent tiers.' This matches the requirement for automatic cost optimization without manual lifecycle management and without retrieval fees during the infrequent phase. Option A (Standard-IA + Lifecycle) requires manual policy configuration and does incur per-GB retrieval fees on Standard-IA. Option C (Glacier Instant Retrieval) has a 90-day minimum storage charge and is designed for archive data, not data that starts as frequently accessed — applying it from day one would be cost-inefficient and operationally inappropriate. Option D (S3 Express One Zone) is a high-performance, single-AZ class optimized for single-digit-millisecond latency on hot workloads, not for cost tiering of aging data.$patch$, $patch$Data Store Management$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/intelligent-tiering.html","label":"Amazon S3 Intelligent-Tiering storage class – AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/storage-class-intro.html","label":"Amazon S3 storage classes overview – AWS Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DEA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data engineering team stores raw clickstream data in Amazon S3. The data is accessed frequently for the first 30 days, rarely accessed between 31 and 90 days, and almost never accessed after 90 days. The team wants to minimize storage costs automatically without managing manual transitions and without incurring retrieval fees during the infrequent-access phase. Which S3 storage class BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company runs a large Amazon Redshift data warehouse on RA3 nodes. Several business-critical reporting queries run concurrently during peak business hours, causing queue wait times to spike and degrading dashboard refresh rates. The data engineering team wants to handle these burst read workloads automatically while controlling costs. Which Redshift feature BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable AQUA (Advanced Query Accelerator) on the RA3 cluster to cache frequently scanned data in hardware-accelerated memory"},{"id":"b","text":"Switch all tables to an EVEN distribution style so data is spread uniformly and reduces per-node CPU pressure"},{"id":"c","text":"Enable Concurrency Scaling, which automatically adds transient read capacity during demand spikes, with the first hour of usage per day provided free per cluster"},{"id":"d","text":"Create materialized views for each dashboard query and configure auto-refresh so results are always precomputed"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Concurrency Scaling: automatic transient cluster expansion for read workloads; first hour daily free per cluster.' This directly solves burst concurrency problems by transparently adding read capacity when queue wait times spike, and it is cost-controlled because the first hour of scaling per day is free. Option A (AQUA) is a hardware-accelerated cache that speeds up individual query execution on RA3 nodes but does not add concurrency slots or reduce queue wait times caused by too many simultaneous queries. Option B (EVEN distribution) affects data placement and can help some query patterns, but it does not address the concurrency bottleneck — queries would still queue if concurrency slots are exhausted. Option D (materialized views with auto-refresh) can reduce query execution time for known, static queries, but does not handle dynamic ad-hoc reporting bursts or automatically scale concurrency; it also introduces refresh lag depending on the refresh schedule.$patch$, $patch$Data Store Management$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/latest/dg/concurrency-scaling.html","label":"Amazon Redshift Concurrency Scaling – AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/redshift/latest/mgmt/working-with-clusters.html#rs-ra3-node-types","label":"Amazon Redshift RA3 node types and managed storage – AWS Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DEA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company runs a large Amazon Redshift data warehouse on RA3 nodes. Several business-critical reporting queries run concurrently during peak business hours, causing queue wait times to spike and degrading dashboard refresh rates. The data engineering team wants to handle these burst read workloads automatically while controlling costs. Which Redshift feature BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data engineering team has built an AWS Step Functions state machine to orchestrate a multi-step ETL pipeline. One of the states invokes an AWS Glue job that can take between 10 and 45 minutes to complete. The team needs the state machine to wait until the Glue job fully finishes before transitioning to the next state. Which Step Functions service integration pattern should they configure for the Glue job Task state?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Request Response — call the Glue job API and immediately transition to the next state without waiting."},{"id":"b","text":"Run a Job (.sync) — call the Glue job and pause the state machine until the job reaches a terminal state."},{"id":"c","text":"Wait for Callback (.waitForTaskToken) — pause the state machine until a human manually sends a task token back."},{"id":"d","text":"Distributed Map — fan out the Glue job across many parallel workers and aggregate results when all workers finish."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Run a Job (.sync): call AWS service, wait for job to complete (e.g. Athena, Glue, EMR, SageMaker, ECS).' This pattern is purpose-built for long-running managed jobs where the state machine must block until completion. Option A (Request Response) is the default pattern that moves to the next state immediately after invoking the API — it would not wait for the Glue job to finish. Option C (Wait for Callback / .waitForTaskToken) is used for asynchronous human-in-the-loop or external-system scenarios where an external actor must explicitly return a token; it is not the right choice for a Glue job that reports its own completion status. Option D (Distributed Map) is a state type for parallel iteration over large S3 datasets and is unrelated to the service integration pattern used to invoke a Glue job.$patch$, $patch$Data Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/step-functions/latest/dg/concepts-service-integrations.html","label":"AWS Step Functions — Service Integration Patterns"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/step-functions/latest/dg/connect-glue.html","label":"AWS Step Functions — Optimized Integration: AWS Glue"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DEA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data engineering team has built an AWS Step Functions state machine to orchestrate a multi-step ETL pipeline. One of the states invokes an AWS Glue job that can take between 10 and 45 minutes to complete. The team needs the state machine to wait until the Glue job fully finishes before transitioning to the next state. Which Step Functions service integration pattern should they configure for the Glue job Task state?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data operations team runs a high-throughput event-driven pipeline that executes thousands of short workflow runs per minute, each completing within 90 seconds. They are evaluating whether to use Standard or Express workflows in AWS Step Functions. The team's top priorities are minimizing cost and ensuring the execution logs are available for debugging in Amazon CloudWatch. Which workflow type should they choose and why?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Standard workflows, because they provide exactly-once execution semantics and retain full execution history for up to 1 year."},{"id":"b","text":"Express workflows, because they are optimized for high-volume, short-duration executions, are priced by number and duration of executions, and send logs to CloudWatch."},{"id":"c","text":"Standard workflows, because they are the only type that can send execution logs to Amazon CloudWatch Logs."},{"id":"d","text":"Express workflows, because they guarantee exactly-once execution semantics, making them safe for any financial transaction workload."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly describes Express workflows as: 'high-volume (up to 5 min), at-least-once, priced by number + duration of executions, logs to CloudWatch.' This matches all three of the team's criteria — high throughput, short duration (90 s < 5 min cap), cost efficiency, and CloudWatch log availability. Option A is factually correct about Standard workflows but misaligns with the team's priorities: Standard workflows are priced per state transition, which becomes expensive at thousands of runs per minute, making them the wrong cost choice here. Option C is incorrect; both workflow types can emit logs to CloudWatch — Standard workflows retain full execution history in the Step Functions console, while Express workflows log to CloudWatch Logs. Option D is incorrect because the source material clearly states Express workflows use at-least-once (not exactly-once) execution semantics, making them unsuitable for workloads that require idempotency guarantees such as financial transactions.$patch$, $patch$Data Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/step-functions/latest/dg/concepts-standard-vs-express.html","label":"AWS Step Functions — Standard vs. Express Workflows"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/step-functions/latest/dg/cw-logs.html","label":"AWS Step Functions — Logging Express Workflow Executions to CloudWatch"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DEA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data operations team runs a high-throughput event-driven pipeline that executes thousands of short workflow runs per minute, each completing within 90 seconds. They are evaluating whether to use Standard or Express workflows in AWS Step Functions. The team's top priorities are minimizing cost and ensuring the execution logs are available for debugging in Amazon CloudWatch. Which workflow type should they choose and why?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data engineering team manages a large AWS data lake with hundreds of S3-backed tables registered in the AWS Glue Data Catalog. They need to implement a scalable access control strategy that allows them to grant and revoke permissions across thousands of resources without individually managing permissions on each table or column. Which AWS Lake Formation feature BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Lake Formation data filters with row-level predicates applied to each table individually"},{"id":"b","text":"LF-Tags (tag-based access control / TBAC), which allow permissions to be granted based on tag attributes attached to databases, tables, and columns"},{"id":"c","text":"IAM resource-based policies attached directly to each S3 bucket backing the data lake tables"},{"id":"d","text":"AWS Macie sensitivity labels applied to S3 objects to automatically enforce access restrictions"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'LF-Tags (tag-based access control / TBAC): attach tags to databases/tables/columns; grant policies based on tag attributes; scales to thousands of resources.' This directly addresses the requirement for a scalable approach across thousands of resources — instead of managing permissions table-by-table, administrators assign LF-Tags to resources and write grant policies referencing those tags. When a new resource receives the appropriate tag, it automatically inherits the correct access controls. Option A (data filters) is designed for row- and cell-level security on individual tables, not for broad scalable access management across thousands of resources. Option C (IAM resource-based policies on S3 buckets) does not provide the fine-grained, metadata-aware governance that Lake Formation TBAC offers and would be difficult to scale across thousands of individual tables. Option D (Amazon Macie) is a data discovery and classification service for sensitive data in S3; it does not enforce access control permissions.$patch$, $patch$Data Security and Governance$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lake-formation/latest/dg/tag-based-access-control.html","label":"AWS Lake Formation Tag-Based Access Control (TBAC)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lake-formation/latest/dg/lake-formation-permissions.html","label":"AWS Lake Formation Permissions Overview"},{"url":"https://d1.awsstatic.com/training-and-certification/docs-data-engineer-associate/AWS-Certified-Data-Engineer-Associate_Exam-Guide.pdf","label":"AWS Certified Data Engineer Associate Exam Guide (DEA-C01)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DEA-C01-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data engineering team manages a large AWS data lake with hundreds of S3-backed tables registered in the AWS Glue Data Catalog. They need to implement a scalable access control strategy that allows them to grant and revoke permissions across thousands of resources without individually managing permissions on each table or column. Which AWS Lake Formation feature BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$);

