INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data engineering team stores five years of archived clickstream data in Amazon S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval. A new compliance requirement mandates that a subset of these objects must become immutable and cannot be deleted or overwritten for the next seven years, even by users with administrative privileges. Which S3 feature and retention mode should the team configure to satisfy this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable S3 Versioning with MFA Delete so that every deletion requires a second authentication factor, preventing accidental removal."},{"id":"b","text":"Configure S3 Object Lock in Compliance mode with a retention period of seven years on the affected objects."},{"id":"c","text":"Configure S3 Object Lock in Governance mode with a retention period of seven years on the affected objects."},{"id":"d","text":"Apply an S3 Lifecycle policy that transitions the objects to S3 Glacier Deep Archive and blocks expiration actions for seven years."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that S3 Object Lock provides WORM (write-once-read-many) protection with two retention modes: Governance and Compliance. In Compliance mode, no user — including the AWS root account — can overwrite or delete a protected object until the retention period expires, satisfying the requirement that even administrators cannot remove the data. Governance mode (option c) is incorrect because users who hold the s3:BypassGovernanceRetention permission can override the lock, meaning administrators could still delete the objects. S3 Versioning with MFA Delete (option a) adds an extra authentication step for deletions but does not impose a time-bound, tamper-proof WORM lock and can be disabled by a privileged user. S3 Lifecycle policies (option d) manage transitions and expirations on a schedule but are not a mechanism for preventing deletion by privileged users; they are not an immutability control.$patch$, $patch$Data Store Management$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/object-lock-overview.html","label":"Amazon S3 Object Lock overview – AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/object-lock-overview.html#object-lock-retention-modes","label":"S3 Object Lock: Governance vs. Compliance retention modes"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DEA-C01-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data engineering team stores five years of archived clickstream data in Amazon S3 Glacier Flexible Retrieval. A new compliance requirement mandates that a subset of these objects must become immutable and cannot be deleted or overwritten for the next seven years, even by users with administrative privileges. Which S3 feature and retention mode should the team configure to satisfy this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A data engineering team has built an AWS Step Functions state machine that orchestrates a multi-stage ETL pipeline. One stage submits an AWS Glue job and must wait for the job to fully complete before proceeding to the next stage. The team notices that when using the default service integration pattern, the state machine moves to the next state immediately after submitting the Glue job, without waiting for the job to finish. Which service integration pattern should the team configure for the Glue job task state to ensure the state machine waits for the Glue job to complete before transitioning?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Request Response — the default pattern that calls the Glue API and immediately moves to the next state regardless of job completion."},{"id":"b","text":"Run a Job (.sync) — pauses the state machine and polls the Glue job until it reaches a terminal state before transitioning."},{"id":"c","text":"Wait for Callback (.waitForTaskToken) — sends a task token to Glue and resumes only when Glue explicitly returns the token."},{"id":"d","text":"Parallel — launches the Glue job in a concurrent branch and merges results back into the main flow after all branches complete."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Run a Job (.sync): call AWS service, wait for job to complete (e.g. Athena, Glue, EMR, SageMaker, ECS).' This integration pattern makes Step Functions internally poll the Glue job's status and only transition to the next state once the job reaches a terminal state (SUCCEEDED, FAILED, etc.). Option A describes the default 'Request Response' pattern, which is explicitly identified as the pattern that 'move[s] to next state immediately' — exactly the broken behavior the team is observing. Option C (.waitForTaskToken) is designed for asynchronous human-in-the-loop or external-system scenarios where Step Functions must pause until an external caller explicitly returns a task token; Glue does not natively return a task token, so this pattern would cause the state machine to pause indefinitely. Option D (Parallel) is a state type for running concurrent branches within the workflow and is unrelated to controlling how a single service API call waits for job completion.$patch$, $patch$Data Operations and Support$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/step-functions/latest/dg/concepts-service-integrations.html","label":"AWS Step Functions — Service Integration Patterns"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/step-functions/latest/dg/connect-glue.html","label":"AWS Step Functions — Optimized integration for AWS Glue"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DEA-C01-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A data engineering team has built an AWS Step Functions state machine that orchestrates a multi-stage ETL pipeline. One stage submits an AWS Glue job and must wait for the job to fully complete before proceeding to the next stage. The team notices that when using the default service integration pattern, the state machine moves to the next state immediately after submitting the Glue job, without waiting for the job to finish. Which service integration pattern should the team configure for the Glue job task state to ensure the state machine waits for the Glue job to complete before transitioning?$patch$);

