INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is building a serverless application using AWS Lambda. The Lambda function needs to retrieve a database password stored in AWS Secrets Manager. A colleague suggests embedding the IAM access keys directly in the Lambda function's environment variables to authenticate API calls to Secrets Manager. What is the MOST secure and recommended approach instead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Embed the IAM access keys in the Lambda function's environment variables and encrypt them using an AWS KMS key."},{"id":"b","text":"Assign an IAM execution role to the Lambda function with a permissions policy that allows access to Secrets Manager, and let Lambda obtain temporary credentials automatically."},{"id":"c","text":"Store the IAM access keys in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store as a SecureString and have the Lambda function retrieve them at runtime."},{"id":"d","text":"Create an IAM user with Secrets Manager read permissions, generate long-term access keys, and pass them to the Lambda function via an environment variable."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'EC2 instance profile / Lambda execution role / ECS task role: attach roles to compute so code never needs to embed credentials.' By attaching an IAM execution role to the Lambda function, AWS automatically provides the function with short-lived temporary credentials (via STS) scoped to exactly the permissions defined in the role's permissions policy. This eliminates the risk of credential leakage or long-term key exposure. Option A is incorrect because embedding access keys in environment variables — even KMS-encrypted ones — still constitutes storing long-term credentials in the function configuration, which is an anti-pattern. Option C is incorrect for a similar reason: fetching long-term IAM access keys at runtime still means long-term credentials exist somewhere and must be managed and rotated manually. Option D is the explicit anti-pattern the source warns against, as IAM user long-term credentials embedded in compute environments are a security risk and directly contradict AWS best practices around role-based access for compute services.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/lambda-intro-execution-role.html","label":"AWS IAM Roles for Lambda – AWS Lambda Developer Guide"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/best-practices.html#use-roles-with-aws-service","label":"IAM Best Practices – Use Roles for Applications on AWS Compute"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/auth-and-access.html","label":"AWS Secrets Manager – Authentication and Access Control"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DVA-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer is building a serverless application using AWS Lambda. The Lambda function needs to retrieve a database password stored in AWS Secrets Manager. A colleague suggests embedding the IAM access keys directly in the Lambda function's environment variables to authenticate API calls to Secrets Manager. What is the MOST secure and recommended approach instead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is configuring an AWS CodeDeploy blue/green deployment for an Amazon ECS service. They need to run integration tests against the new task set before it receives any production traffic. Which AppSpec lifecycle hook should be used to execute these integration tests at the correct point in the deployment lifecycle?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"BeforeInstall"},{"id":"b","text":"AfterInstall"},{"id":"c","text":"AfterAllowTestTraffic"},{"id":"d","text":"BeforeAllowTraffic"},{"id":"e","text":"ValidateService"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the source material, the ECS lifecycle hooks in order are: BeforeInstall, AfterInstall, AfterAllowTestTraffic, BeforeAllowTraffic, AfterAllowTraffic. The AfterAllowTestTraffic hook fires after CodeDeploy has shifted a small amount of test traffic to the replacement task set, making it the ideal hook to run integration tests against the new version before committing any production traffic. BeforeInstall and AfterInstall run before the new task set is even ready for test traffic, so tests cannot yet target the new version. BeforeAllowTraffic runs after the test phase but just before production traffic is shifted — too late to validate with test traffic. ValidateService is an EC2/On-Premises hook, not available in the ECS deployment lifecycle, making option (e) incorrect for this platform.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codedeploy/latest/userguide/reference-appspec-file-structure-hooks.html#appspec-hooks-ecs","label":"AWS CodeDeploy – AppSpec hooks for Amazon ECS deployments"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codedeploy/latest/userguide/deployment-steps-ecs.html","label":"AWS CodeDeploy – Blue/Green deployments on Amazon ECS"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DVA-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer is configuring an AWS CodeDeploy blue/green deployment for an Amazon ECS service. They need to run integration tests against the new task set before it receives any production traffic. Which AppSpec lifecycle hook should be used to execute these integration tests at the correct point in the deployment lifecycle?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is building a high-traffic serverless application on AWS Lambda that generates thousands of custom business metrics per second. The developer wants to publish these metrics to Amazon CloudWatch with minimal latency, no additional API call overhead, and no risk of hitting the PutMetricData throttle limits. Which approach BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Call PutMetricData from within each Lambda invocation to push each metric individually as it is generated."},{"id":"b","text":"Use the CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format (EMF) by writing structured JSON to stdout/stderr; CloudWatch will automatically extract the metrics from the logs without separate PutMetricData calls."},{"id":"c","text":"Configure a CloudWatch Metric Filter on the Lambda log group to extract metrics from unstructured log lines."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable CloudWatch Lambda Insights on the function, which automatically publishes all custom business metrics in real time."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Embedded Metric Format (EMF): structured JSON in logs; CloudWatch extracts metrics automatically without separate PutMetricData calls. Best practice for high-volume metrics from Lambda.' EMF allows the Lambda function to embed metric data inside its log output as structured JSON, and CloudWatch Logs automatically parses and ingests them as CloudWatch metrics — eliminating any PutMetricData API calls and the associated throttling risk. 

Option A is incorrect because calling PutMetricData individually inside each high-volume Lambda invocation adds latency per invocation and risks hitting the PutMetricData service quota (TPS throttle). 

Option C is incorrect because Metric Filters can extract simple numeric values from log lines, but they require manual regex patterns and are not purpose-built for high-volume custom metric publishing; they also add configuration complexity and are not described as best practice for Lambda in the source material. 

Option D is incorrect because Lambda Insights provides pre-defined performance/operational metrics (memory, CPU, duration, cold starts) about the Lambda runtime itself — it does not capture or publish arbitrary custom business metrics defined by the developer.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting and Optimization$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch_Embedded_Metric_Format_Overview.html","label":"Amazon CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format – Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch_Embedded_Metric_Format_Specification.html","label":"Amazon CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format – Specification"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/monitoring-insights.html","label":"AWS Lambda – Using Lambda Insights"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DVA-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer is building a high-traffic serverless application on AWS Lambda that generates thousands of custom business metrics per second. The developer wants to publish these metrics to Amazon CloudWatch with minimal latency, no additional API call overhead, and no risk of hitting the PutMetricData throttle limits. Which approach BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$);

-- DVA-C02-P2: 1 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is building a serverless application using AWS Lambda. The function needs to access a database password stored in AWS Secrets Manager. The security team has mandated that no long-term credentials may be embedded in code or environment variables. Which approach correctly follows AWS security best practices to grant the Lambda function access to the secret?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an IAM user, attach a policy allowing secretsmanager:GetSecretValue, and store the user's access key and secret key in the Lambda environment variables."},{"id":"b","text":"Attach an IAM execution role to the Lambda function with a permissions policy that allows secretsmanager:GetSecretValue on the specific secret ARN; the function retrieves temporary credentials automatically via the instance metadata service."},{"id":"c","text":"Hard-code the database password directly in the Lambda source code and use AWS CodeCommit's encryption at rest to protect it."},{"id":"d","text":"Store the database password in a Lambda layer and restrict layer access using a resource-based policy on the layer ARN."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the source material: 'EC2 instance profile / Lambda execution role / ECS task role: attach roles to compute so code never needs to embed credentials.' By attaching an IAM execution role to the Lambda function, the AWS SDK inside the function automatically retrieves short-lived temporary credentials (AccessKeyId, SecretAccessKey, SessionToken) from the Lambda runtime environment — no long-term credentials are ever stored in code or environment variables. The permissions policy on that role must grant secretsmanager:GetSecretValue scoped to the specific secret ARN to follow least-privilege. Option A violates the mandate by embedding long-term IAM user credentials in environment variables. Option C violates it by hard-coding the password in source code, which also exposes it in version control. Option D misunderstands Lambda layers — they are for code/libraries, not secrets storage, and do not provide authentication to Secrets Manager.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/lambda-intro-execution-role.html","label":"AWS Lambda execution role – AWS Lambda Developer Guide"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/integrating_lambda.html","label":"Use AWS Secrets Manager secrets in AWS Lambda functions"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/best-practices.html#use-roles-with-aws-services","label":"IAM best practices: Use roles for applications and AWS services"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DVA-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer is building a serverless application using AWS Lambda. The function needs to access a database password stored in AWS Secrets Manager. The security team has mandated that no long-term credentials may be embedded in code or environment variables. Which approach correctly follows AWS security best practices to grant the Lambda function access to the secret?$patch$);

-- DVA-C02-P3: 1 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is configuring an AWS CodeDeploy deployment for a Lambda function. They want traffic to shift in equal increments every 10 minutes until all traffic is routed to the new version. Which traffic-shift configuration should they specify in the deployment configuration?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"CodeDeployDefault.LambdaCanary10Percent10Minutes"},{"id":"b","text":"CodeDeployDefault.LambdaLinear10PercentEvery10Minutes"},{"id":"c","text":"CodeDeployDefault.LambdaAllAtOnce"},{"id":"d","text":"CodeDeployDefault.LambdaCanary50Percent10Minutes"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the source material, a Linear traffic-shift configuration shifts traffic in 'equal intervals over time,' which precisely matches the requirement of equal increments every 10 minutes. CodeDeployDefault.LambdaLinear10PercentEvery10Minutes shifts 10% of traffic every 10 minutes until 100% is reached. Option A (Canary10Percent10Minutes) is incorrect because a Canary configuration shifts a small percentage first, waits, and then shifts the remaining 100% all at once — it does not use equal increments throughout. Option C (AllAtOnce) is incorrect because it shifts all traffic immediately with no staged rollout. Option D (Canary50Percent10Minutes) is also a Canary variant and shifts 50% first, then the remaining 50% all at once after 10 minutes — not equal increments.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codedeploy/latest/userguide/deployment-configurations.html#deployment-configuration-lambda","label":"AWS CodeDeploy – Lambda Deployment Configurations"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codedeploy/latest/userguide/deployment-configurations.html","label":"AWS CodeDeploy – Working with Deployment Configurations for Lambda"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
