-- DVA-C02-P4: 2 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is building a serverless application where an AWS Lambda function needs to retrieve a database password stored in AWS Secrets Manager. The Lambda function currently has no credentials configured. Which approach correctly follows AWS security best practices to grant the Lambda function access to the secret?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Embed the IAM access key and secret access key directly in the Lambda function's environment variables so the function can call the Secrets Manager API."},{"id":"b","text":"Attach an IAM execution role to the Lambda function with a permissions policy that allows secretsmanager:GetSecretValue on the specific secret ARN."},{"id":"c","text":"Create an IAM user, attach a policy granting access to the secret, and store the user's long-term credentials in Parameter Store for the Lambda function to retrieve."},{"id":"d","text":"Add a resource-based policy directly to the Lambda function that references the Secrets Manager ARN, enabling the function to self-authorize."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The correct answer is (b). The source material explicitly states: 'EC2 instance profile / Lambda execution role / ECS task role: attach roles to compute so code never needs to embed credentials.' By attaching an IAM execution role to the Lambda function with a permissions policy granting secretsmanager:GetSecretValue on the specific secret, the Lambda service automatically provides the function with short-lived temporary credentials via STS — no static credentials are needed. Option (a) is wrong because embedding long-term IAM access keys in environment variables violates the principle of least privilege and creates a credential-leakage risk; the source highlights roles as the correct mechanism precisely to avoid this. Option (c) is wrong for the same reason — IAM users produce long-term credentials, and storing them in Parameter Store adds unnecessary complexity and risk compared to using a role. Option (d) is wrong because a Lambda resource-based policy controls who can invoke the Lambda function, not what the Lambda function itself can access; it cannot grant the function permission to call Secrets Manager.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/lambda-intro-execution-role.html","label":"AWS Lambda execution role — IAM Developer Guide"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/auth-and-access.html","label":"AWS Secrets Manager — Authentication and access control"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/best-practices.html#use-roles-with-aws-services","label":"IAM best practices: Use roles for applications on AWS compute services"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DVA-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer is building a serverless application where an AWS Lambda function needs to retrieve a database password stored in AWS Secrets Manager. The Lambda function currently has no credentials configured. Which approach correctly follows AWS security best practices to grant the Lambda function access to the secret?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is configuring an AWS CodeDeploy deployment for a containerized application running on Amazon ECS. They want to shift 10% of production traffic to the new task set immediately, then wait 15 minutes before shifting the remaining 90%. Which CodeDeploy traffic-shift configuration should the developer choose?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"CodeDeployDefault.ECSLinear10PercentEvery3Minutes"},{"id":"b","text":"CodeDeployDefault.ECSCanary10Percent15Minutes"},{"id":"c","text":"CodeDeployDefault.ECSAllAtOnce"},{"id":"d","text":"CodeDeployDefault.ECSLinear10PercentEvery1Minute"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that the Canary traffic-shift configuration shifts a small percentage of traffic first, waits, then shifts 100%. 'CodeDeployDefault.ECSCanary10Percent15Minutes' matches exactly this requirement: 10% of traffic is routed to the new ECS task set immediately, and after a 15-minute bake period the remaining 90% is shifted all at once. Linear configurations (options A and D) shift traffic in equal increments at regular intervals — for example, 10% every 3 minutes or every 1 minute — rather than a two-phase canary approach. All-at-once (option C) shifts 100% of traffic immediately with no phased rollout, which contradicts the requirement to wait 15 minutes before completing the shift.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codedeploy/latest/userguide/deployment-configurations.html#deployment-configuration-ecs","label":"AWS CodeDeploy — Deployment configurations for Amazon ECS"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codedeploy/latest/userguide/deployment-steps-ecs.html","label":"AWS CodeDeploy — Blue/green deployments on Amazon ECS"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
