  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer is configuring an AWS CodeDeploy deployment for a containerized application running on Amazon ECS. They want to shift 10% of production traffic to the new task set immediately, then wait 15 minutes before shifting the remaining 90%. Which CodeDeploy traffic-shift configuration should the developer choose?$patch$);

-- DVA-C02-P5: 3 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is building a serverless application where an AWS Lambda function must read a database password stored in AWS Secrets Manager. The Lambda function currently has no IAM permissions configured. Which combination of configurations is the MINIMUM required to allow the Lambda function to successfully retrieve the secret at runtime without embedding any long-term credentials in the code?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an IAM user with secretsmanager:GetSecretValue permission, generate access keys for that user, and store the keys as Lambda environment variables."},{"id":"b","text":"Attach an IAM execution role to the Lambda function that includes secretsmanager:GetSecretValue permission for the specific secret ARN, and ensure the role's trust policy allows lambda.amazonaws.com to assume it."},{"id":"c","text":"Add a resource-based policy directly on the Lambda function granting secretsmanager.amazonaws.com permission to invoke it, then hardcode the secret ARN in the function environment variables."},{"id":"d","text":"Attach an S3 bucket policy that allows the Lambda function to read a file containing the database password, then parse the password from the file at runtime."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the source material, 'EC2 instance profile / Lambda execution role / ECS task role: attach roles to compute so code never needs to embed credentials.' This is the AWS-recommended pattern: a Lambda execution role is an IAM role whose trust policy designates lambda.amazonaws.com as the trusted principal (allowing Lambda to assume the role via STS), and whose permissions policy grants secretsmanager:GetSecretValue on the target secret. At runtime, Lambda automatically injects temporary STS credentials into the execution environment — no long-term keys are ever embedded. Option A violates the principle by using long-term IAM user access keys stored in environment variables, which is an anti-pattern explicitly avoided by using execution roles. Option C conflates resource-based policies on Lambda (used to control who can invoke the function) with the unrelated need to call Secrets Manager — this configuration does not grant the function any ability to call Secrets Manager. Option D avoids Secrets Manager entirely and introduces a less secure, more complex pattern using S3, which does not satisfy the requirement of retrieving the secret from Secrets Manager.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/lambda-intro-execution-role.html","label":"AWS Lambda execution role – IAM Developer Guide"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/retrieving-secrets_lambda.html","label":"AWS Secrets Manager – Retrieve secrets in Lambda"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/id_roles.html","label":"IAM Roles – AWS Identity and Access Management"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DVA-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer is building a serverless application where an AWS Lambda function must read a database password stored in AWS Secrets Manager. The Lambda function currently has no IAM permissions configured. Which combination of configurations is the MINIMUM required to allow the Lambda function to successfully retrieve the secret at runtime without embedding any long-term credentials in the code?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is configuring an AWS CodeDeploy deployment for an Amazon ECS service and wants to gradually shift traffic to a new task set by moving 10% of traffic every 5 minutes until the new task set receives 100% of traffic. Which CodeDeploy traffic-shift configuration should the developer use?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Canary10Percent5Minutes"},{"id":"b","text":"Linear10PercentEvery5Minutes"},{"id":"c","text":"AllAtOnce"},{"id":"d","text":"Canary10Percent15Minutes"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that a Linear traffic-shift configuration moves traffic in 'equal intervals over time.' Linear10PercentEvery5Minutes shifts exactly 10% of traffic every 5 minutes until 100% is reached — matching the requirement precisely. Canary configurations (options A and D) only make two shifts: a small initial percentage first, then the remainder all at once, which does not produce equal incremental steps. AllAtOnce (option C) shifts 100% of traffic immediately, providing no gradual rollout. Therefore, the Linear deployment configuration is the correct choice for equal, time-based incremental traffic shifting.$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codedeploy/latest/userguide/deployment-configurations.html#deployment-configuration-ecs","label":"AWS CodeDeploy — Deployment configurations for Amazon ECS"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codedeploy/latest/userguide/deployment-configurations.html","label":"AWS CodeDeploy — Traffic-shifting options for Lambda and ECS"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DVA-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer is configuring an AWS CodeDeploy deployment for an Amazon ECS service and wants to gradually shift traffic to a new task set by moving 10% of traffic every 5 minutes until the new task set receives 100% of traffic. Which CodeDeploy traffic-shift configuration should the developer use?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is building a high-traffic AWS Lambda function that generates dozens of custom business metrics on every invocation. The developer wants to publish these metrics to Amazon CloudWatch without making individual PutMetricData API calls, in order to reduce latency and avoid throttling. Which approach should the developer use?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use the AWS SDK inside the Lambda function to call PutMetricData once per metric at the end of each invocation."},{"id":"b","text":"Write metrics using the CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format (EMF) as structured JSON to stdout, allowing CloudWatch Logs to automatically extract the metrics."},{"id":"c","text":"Install the X-Ray Daemon as a Lambda Layer and annotate segments with the custom metric values."},{"id":"d","text":"Create a Metric Filter on the Lambda log group and manually define each metric name and value in the filter pattern."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Embedded Metric Format (EMF): structured JSON in logs; CloudWatch extracts metrics automatically without separate PutMetricData calls. Best practice for high-volume metrics from Lambda.' By emitting EMF-formatted JSON to stdout, Lambda's built-in log shipping sends the data to CloudWatch Logs, which then extracts the embedded metrics asynchronously — eliminating PutMetricData API calls entirely and removing the associated latency and throttling risk. Option A is the anti-pattern EMF is designed to replace. Option C is incorrect because X-Ray segments and subsegments are for distributed tracing, not CloudWatch metric publication; the X-Ray Daemon is not needed for Lambda (Active Tracing is used instead). Option D (Metric Filters) can extract metrics from logs but requires manual regex-based filter patterns defined per metric and cannot dynamically handle dozens of different metric names without creating a separate filter for each one, making it impractical for high-volume, varied custom metrics.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting and Optimization$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch_Embedded_Metric_Format_Specification.html","label":"AWS CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format – Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch_Embedded_Metric_Format_Libraries.html","label":"AWS CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format – Getting Started with Lambda"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DVA-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer is building a high-traffic AWS Lambda function that generates dozens of custom business metrics on every invocation. The developer wants to publish these metrics to Amazon CloudWatch without making individual PutMetricData API calls, in order to reduce latency and avoid throttling. Which approach should the developer use?$patch$);

-- DVA-C02-P6: 4 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is writing an AWS Lambda function that must retrieve a database password stored securely. The security team requires that the password be automatically rotated every 30 days without any code changes to the Lambda function. Which AWS service and approach best satisfies both requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Store the password in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store as a SecureString and write a separate Lambda function that updates the value on a 30-day CloudWatch Events schedule."},{"id":"b","text":"Store the password in AWS Secrets Manager and configure an automatic rotation schedule with a Lambda rotation function; retrieve the secret by name at runtime."},{"id":"c","text":"Embed the password as an environment variable in the Lambda function and redeploy the function every 30 days using a CI/CD pipeline."},{"id":"d","text":"Store the password in an Amazon S3 object encrypted with SSE-KMS and have the Lambda function download the object on each invocation."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$AWS Secrets Manager is purpose-built for storing secrets (DB credentials, API keys) and supports automatic rotation via a configurable Lambda rotation function on a schedule — satisfying the 30-day rotation requirement without code changes (the Lambda retrieves the secret by name using the AWSCURRENT staging label). The source material states: 'Stores secrets (DB credentials, API keys); auto-rotates via Lambda rotation functions on a schedule' and 'Versioned secrets with AWSCURRENT, AWSPENDING, AWSPREVIOUS staging labels.' Option A (Parameter Store) is incorrect because Parameter Store has no built-in rotation — the source explicitly notes 'no built-in rotation (you must build it),' and a custom scheduler still requires operational overhead and code awareness of the rotation mechanism. Option C is incorrect because embedding credentials in environment variables is a security anti-pattern and requires redeployment. Option D is incorrect because S3 is not a secrets management service; it does not provide versioned staging labels or automated rotation logic.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/rotating-secrets.html","label":"AWS Secrets Manager – Rotating Secrets"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/intro.html","label":"AWS Secrets Manager – How It Works"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DVA-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer is writing an AWS Lambda function that must retrieve a database password stored securely. The security team requires that the password be automatically rotated every 30 days without any code changes to the Lambda function. Which AWS service and approach best satisfies both requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A mobile application authenticates users through an Amazon Cognito User Pool. After sign-in, the app needs to upload files directly to an Amazon S3 bucket on behalf of each user using temporary AWS credentials scoped to that user. Which Cognito feature should the developer use to obtain these temporary AWS credentials?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Retrieve the Cognito User Pool ID token and use it directly as an AWS access key when calling the S3 API."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a long-term IAM user for each mobile user and distribute the access key and secret access key inside the app bundle."},{"id":"c","text":"Exchange the Cognito User Pool token through an Amazon Cognito Identity Pool (Federated Identities) to receive temporary AWS credentials via STS, then use those credentials to call S3."},{"id":"d","text":"Call STS AssumeRole directly from the mobile device using the root account credentials stored in the app configuration file."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Amazon Cognito Identity Pools (Federated Identities) are designed exactly for this use case. The source material states: 'Identity Pools (Federated Identities): exchange tokens (Cognito User Pool, Google, Facebook, SAML) for temporary AWS credentials via STS.' The mobile app passes the User Pool JWT to the Identity Pool, which calls STS and returns short-lived credentials (AccessKeyId, SecretAccessKey, SessionToken) that the app uses to call S3 directly — following least-privilege principles. Option A is incorrect because a Cognito JWT is an authentication token, not AWS API credentials; the S3 API requires SigV4-signed requests using AWS credentials. Option B is incorrect because embedding long-term IAM credentials in an app bundle is a serious security vulnerability — credentials can be extracted and misused, and this violates AWS best practices for compute/mobile clients. Option D is incorrect because using root account credentials in any application is strictly prohibited by AWS security best practices, and distributing them in a mobile app would be catastrophic.$patch$, $patch$Security$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cognito/latest/developerguide/cognito-identity.html","label":"Amazon Cognito Identity Pools – Getting Started"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cognito/latest/developerguide/amazon-cognito-integrating-user-pools-with-identity-pools.html","label":"Amazon Cognito – Using Identity Pools with User Pools"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DVA-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A mobile application authenticates users through an Amazon Cognito User Pool. After sign-in, the app needs to upload files directly to an Amazon S3 bucket on behalf of each user using temporary AWS credentials scoped to that user. Which Cognito feature should the developer use to obtain these temporary AWS credentials?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is deploying a new version of an AWS Lambda function using AWS CodeDeploy with a traffic-shifting strategy. The requirement is to route 10% of production traffic to the new version immediately, wait 15 minutes to monitor for errors, and then shift the remaining 90% all at once. Which CodeDeploy traffic-shift configuration satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"CodeDeployDefault.LambdaLinear10PercentEvery1Minute"},{"id":"b","text":"CodeDeployDefault.LambdaCanary10Percent15Minutes"},{"id":"c","text":"CodeDeployDefault.LambdaAllAtOnce"},{"id":"d","text":"CodeDeployDefault.LambdaLinear10PercentEvery15Minutes"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the source material, a Canary traffic-shift configuration routes a small percentage of traffic first, waits a defined interval, and then shifts the remaining 100% of traffic. 'CodeDeployDefault.LambdaCanary10Percent15Minutes' shifts exactly 10% of traffic immediately, waits 15 minutes (allowing time for alarms and monitoring), and then shifts the remaining 90% — perfectly matching the stated requirement. Option A (Linear10PercentEvery1Minute) shifts traffic in equal 10% increments every 1 minute until complete, which does not describe a two-step canary behavior. Option C (AllAtOnce) shifts all traffic immediately with no phased rollout. Option D (Linear10PercentEvery15Minutes) also uses equal incremental shifts every 15 minutes, not a canary pattern. The source material explicitly distinguishes these: 'Canary: small % first, wait, then 100%' versus 'Linear: equal intervals over time' versus 'All-at-once: shift all traffic immediately.'$patch$, $patch$Deployment$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codedeploy/latest/userguide/deployment-configurations.html#deployment-configuration-lambda","label":"AWS CodeDeploy – Lambda Deployment Configurations"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/codedeploy/latest/userguide/deployment-groups-create-lambda-function.html","label":"AWS CodeDeploy – Traffic Shifting for Lambda Deployments"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DVA-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer is deploying a new version of an AWS Lambda function using AWS CodeDeploy with a traffic-shifting strategy. The requirement is to route 10% of production traffic to the new version immediately, wait 15 minutes to monitor for errors, and then shift the remaining 90% all at once. Which CodeDeploy traffic-shift configuration satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A developer is building a high-throughput Lambda function that processes thousands of events per second and needs to publish custom business metrics (e.g., orders processed, payment failures) to CloudWatch without impacting function performance or incurring excessive PutMetricData API costs. Which approach best meets these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Call PutMetricData synchronously within the Lambda handler for each event to ensure metrics are published in real time."},{"id":"b","text":"Use the CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format (EMF) by writing structured JSON to stdout/stderr so CloudWatch automatically extracts metrics from the logs without additional API calls."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable AWS X-Ray Active Tracing on the Lambda function and use custom annotations on segments to store business metric values."},{"id":"d","text":"Create a CloudWatch Metric Filter on the Lambda log group to parse unstructured log lines and extract numeric values into CloudWatch metrics."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Embedded Metric Format (EMF): structured JSON in logs; CloudWatch extracts metrics automatically without separate PutMetricData calls. Best practice for high-volume metrics from Lambda.' By writing EMF-compliant JSON to stdout, the Lambda function avoids the overhead and API throttling risk of synchronous PutMetricData calls, making it the optimal choice for high-throughput scenarios.

Why the distractors are wrong:
- (a) Calling PutMetricData synchronously per event adds latency to the critical path of the handler and will quickly hit API rate limits at high throughput; it is explicitly the pattern EMF is designed to replace.
- (c) X-Ray Active Tracing and segment annotations are intended for distributed tracing and latency analysis, not for publishing business metrics to CloudWatch; annotations are not converted into CloudWatch metrics.
- (d) Metric Filters can extract metrics from logs, but they require log lines to match a specific filter pattern and do not support the rich, structured, zero-extra-API-call experience that EMF provides; they are also less efficient at scale and lack EMF's first-class dimension support.$patch$, $patch$Troubleshooting and Optimization$patch$,
         3, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch_Embedded_Metric_Format_Specification.html","label":"AWS Docs – Using Embedded Metric Format with CloudWatch"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/monitoring-metrics.html","label":"AWS Docs – CloudWatch EMF for Lambda best practices"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DVA-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A developer is building a high-throughput Lambda function that processes thousands of events per second and needs to publish custom business metrics (e.g., orders processed, payment failures) to CloudWatch without impacting function performance or incurring excessive PutMetricData API costs. Which approach best meets these requirements?$patch$);

-- DOP-C02-P1: 15 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team manages a CloudFormation stack containing a production Amazon RDS DB instance. A junior engineer accidentally submitted a stack update that would replace the RDS instance, causing data loss. Which CloudFormation feature should the team have enabled BEFORE the update was submitted to prevent this specific resource from being modified or replaced during any future stack update?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable stack termination protection on the CloudFormation stack."},{"id":"b","text":"Set a Stack Policy that explicitly denies Update actions on the logical RDS DBInstance resource."},{"id":"c","text":"Apply a DeletionPolicy of Retain to the RDS DBInstance resource in the template."},{"id":"d","text":"Create a Change Set and require manual approval before execution."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Stack Policies are the correct control here. The source material states: 'Stack Policies: protect specific logical resources from updates (e.g., RDS DBInstance).' A Stack Policy is a JSON document that defines which update actions are allowed or denied on specific resources within a stack. By denying Update:* on the RDS logical resource, any attempt to modify or replace it is blocked at the CloudFormation API level — even by users with full IAM permissions. 

Distractors: (a) Termination protection only prevents the entire stack from being deleted — it does not block individual resource updates within an update operation. (c) DeletionPolicy: Retain preserves the physical resource when the stack is deleted, but does not prevent the resource from being modified or replaced during a live stack update. (d) Change Sets preview changes and can serve as approval gates, but they do not inherently block the update from being executed — a user can still choose to execute the Change Set after reviewing it, so they are a review control, not a hard prevention control like a Stack Policy.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/protect-stack-resources.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – Prevent Updates to Stack Resources (Stack Policies)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/using-cfn-protect-stacks.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – Stack Termination Protection"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-attribute-deletionpolicy.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – DeletionPolicy Attribute"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team manages a CloudFormation stack containing a production Amazon RDS DB instance. A junior engineer accidentally submitted a stack update that would replace the RDS instance, causing data loss. Which CloudFormation feature should the team have enabled BEFORE the update was submitted to prevent this specific resource from being modified or replaced during any future stack update?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company is deploying application configuration values using AWS AppConfig. The security team requires that any configuration change be gradually rolled out, starting with 10% of clients for five minutes before expanding to 100%, so that a bad configuration can be detected and rolled back automatically before it affects all users. Which AppConfig deployment strategy satisfies this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"AllAtOnce — deploys the configuration to all targets simultaneously."},{"id":"b","text":"Linear — increases the percentage of targets at a constant rate over the deployment interval."},{"id":"c","text":"Canary — deploys to a small initial percentage for a bake time, then deploys the remainder all at once."},{"id":"d","text":"Custom — create a deployment strategy with GrowthType EXPONENTIAL set to 50% per interval."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that AppConfig supports deployment strategies including 'Canary / Linear / AllAtOnce.' The Canary strategy is specifically designed to release a configuration change to a small subset of targets first (e.g., 10%), wait through a bake period, and then automatically complete the rollout to the remaining targets if no alarms fire. This directly matches the described requirement of starting with 10% for five minutes before expanding to 100%.

Distractors: (a) AllAtOnce sends the new configuration to all clients immediately — there is no graduated rollout or bake time, making it the highest-risk option. (b) Linear grows the percentage of targets at a steady, constant rate throughout the entire deployment window (e.g., 10% every N minutes until 100%); it does not perform the specific '10% bake, then jump to 100%' pattern described in the question. (d) An Exponential custom strategy increases at an accelerating rate and is not described in the source material as a named strategy; more importantly, it would not produce the two-phase (canary + full) rollout the team requires.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/appconfig/latest/userguide/appconfig-creating-deployment-strategy.html","label":"AWS AppConfig – Deployment Strategies"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/appconfig/latest/userguide/appconfig-deploying.html","label":"AWS AppConfig – Deploying Configurations (rollback behavior)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company is deploying application configuration values using AWS AppConfig. The security team requires that any configuration change be gradually rolled out, starting with 10% of clients for five minutes before expanding to 100%, so that a bad configuration can be detected and rolled back automatically before it affects all users. Which AppConfig deployment strategy satisfies this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is authoring an AWS CDK application in Python to provision a new AWS Lambda function. The engineer wants to work at the highest level of abstraction available in the CDK construct library so that sensible defaults (such as IAM role creation, log group configuration, and metric/alarm helpers) are automatically applied without manually specifying every CloudFormation property. Which CDK construct level should the engineer use?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"L1 construct (e.g., aws_cdk.aws_lambda.CfnFunction) — provides a one-to-one mapping to the CloudFormation AWS::Lambda::Function resource."},{"id":"b","text":"L2 construct (e.g., aws_cdk.aws_lambda.Function) — a high-level resource construct that encapsulates AWS best practices and provides helper methods."},{"id":"c","text":"L3 construct (pattern) — composes multiple L2 constructs into a complete, opinionated solution such as a Lambda-backed API."},{"id":"d","text":"Raw CloudFormation JSON template embedded via CfnInclude — bypasses the CDK construct hierarchy entirely."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly defines CDK construct levels: 'L1 (CfnXxx, 1:1 to CloudFormation), L2 (high-level resource), L3 (patterns/Solution constructs).' The L2 construct is the correct answer because it operates at the individual resource level while providing high-level abstractions — automatic IAM role creation, CloudWatch log group wiring, metric/alarm convenience methods, and sensible defaults — all without requiring the engineer to specify every underlying CloudFormation property manually.

Distractors: (a) L1 constructs (prefixed 'Cfn') are thin wrappers that map one-to-one to raw CloudFormation resource types and expose every property explicitly. They offer no defaults or helper methods, making them the lowest-level and most verbose option. (c) L3 constructs (patterns) compose multiple resources into an end-to-end solution (e.g., an API Gateway + Lambda + DynamoDB pattern); they are higher-level than needed when the engineer only wants a single Lambda function. (d) Embedding raw CloudFormation JSON via CfnInclude entirely bypasses the CDK construct model and defeats the purpose of using CDK's abstraction layers.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cdk/v2/guide/constructs.html","label":"AWS CDK – Constructs (L1, L2, L3 levels explained)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cdk/api/v2/docs/aws-cdk-lib.aws_lambda.Function.html","label":"AWS CDK API Reference – aws-cdk-lib.aws_lambda.Function (L2 construct)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is authoring an AWS CDK application in Python to provision a new AWS Lambda function. The engineer wants to work at the highest level of abstraction available in the CDK construct library so that sensible defaults (such as IAM role creation, log group configuration, and metric/alarm helpers) are automatically applied without manually specifying every CloudFormation property. Which CDK construct level should the engineer use?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team needs to ensure that AWS Security Hub findings from GuardDuty, Inspector, and Macie across 12 AWS accounts in four AWS Regions are all visible in a single pane of glass. The team has designated us-east-1 as the primary oversight Region. Which combination of Security Hub features satisfies this requirement with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable Security Hub in each account and Region individually, then write a custom Lambda function that polls each Region's findings and writes them to an S3 bucket in us-east-1 for centralized querying."},{"id":"b","text":"In Security Hub, designate us-east-1 as the aggregation Region and link the remaining three Regions to it. Then configure Security Hub in AWS Organizations to designate a delegated administrator account in us-east-1 so findings from all member accounts flow to the central account."},{"id":"c","text":"Use an AWS Config Aggregator spanning all accounts and Regions, and rely on Config-native dashboards to view GuardDuty, Inspector, and Macie findings centrally."},{"id":"d","text":"Deploy an Amazon EventBridge cross-account event bus in us-east-1 and create rules in each source account and Region that forward all default event bus events to the central bus, then subscribe a Lambda to parse findings."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Cross-Region aggregation: designate a home Region; linked Regions feed it for global visibility.' It also notes that Security Hub acts as a 'central aggregator: consolidates findings from GuardDuty, Inspector, Macie, AWS Config, IAM Access Analyzer, Firewall Manager, and third-party partner products.' Combining cross-Region aggregation (linking all four Regions to us-east-1) with the Organizations delegated administrator feature provides multi-account, multi-Region consolidation natively in Security Hub — no custom code required. Option A introduces unnecessary Lambda polling overhead. Option C is incorrect because AWS Config Aggregator does not surface GuardDuty or Macie findings; it only collects Config resource configuration data. Option D can forward events but does not provide the normalized ASFF-based Security Hub finding management UI and automation rules.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/finding-aggregation.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Cross-Region aggregation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/securityhub-accounts-orgs.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Managing administrator and member accounts with AWS Organizations"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team needs to ensure that AWS Security Hub findings from GuardDuty, Inspector, and Macie across 12 AWS accounts in four AWS Regions are all visible in a single pane of glass. The team has designated us-east-1 as the primary oversight Region. Which combination of Security Hub features satisfies this requirement with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer wants to automatically suppress AWS Security Hub findings of INFORMATIONAL severity that are generated by a specific AWS Config rule (rule ID: 'ec2-instance-no-public-ip') in the development account. The suppression must trigger immediately when a matching finding is ingested—without human intervention and without writing any Lambda functions. Which Security Hub capability should the engineer use?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an Amazon EventBridge rule that matches findings from 'ec2-instance-no-public-ip' and invokes an AWS Systems Manager Automation document to delete the finding via the Security Hub API."},{"id":"b","text":"Configure a Security Hub automation rule with a criteria filter matching the GeneratorId 'ec2-instance-no-public-ip' and severity INFORMATIONAL, and set the automated action to update the finding's workflow status to SUPPRESSED."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable an AWS Config conformance pack for the development account and set the remediation action to mark Config rule findings as suppressed in Security Hub."},{"id":"d","text":"Use Amazon Macie to create a suppression rule that filters findings by rule ID and sets the severity threshold to exclude INFORMATIONAL findings from the Security Hub console."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Automation rules: auto-modify or suppress findings (e.g., set severity to INFORMATIONAL based on criteria).' Security Hub Automation Rules allow teams to define filter criteria (such as GeneratorId matching a specific Config rule and severity level) and then automatically take actions — including suppressing findings by updating their workflow status to SUPPRESSED — the moment a matching finding is ingested. No Lambda functions are required. Option A would work functionally but requires an SSM Automation document and is not the purpose-built Security Hub feature for this task. Option C is incorrect because Config conformance packs manage Config rules and SSM remediation; they cannot update Security Hub finding workflow statuses. Option D is incorrect because Macie suppression rules apply only to Macie's own data-sensitivity findings, not to Config-sourced Security Hub findings.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/automation-rules.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Automation rules"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/finding-workflow-status.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Suppressing findings"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer wants to automatically suppress AWS Security Hub findings of INFORMATIONAL severity that are generated by a specific AWS Config rule (rule ID: 'ec2-instance-no-public-ip') in the development account. The suppression must trigger immediately when a matching finding is ingested—without human intervention and without writing any Lambda functions. Which Security Hub capability should the engineer use?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company uses AWS Config with the managed rule 's3-bucket-public-read-prohibited' across all accounts in AWS Organizations. When a bucket is found non-compliant, the operations team wants it automatically remediated within minutes without manual approval steps. The team also wants to ensure future deployments of this rule and its remediation action can be rolled out consistently to new accounts as they join the organization. Which approach best satisfies both requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an Amazon EventBridge rule in each account that detects Config non-compliance notifications for 's3-bucket-public-read-prohibited' and triggers a Lambda function to call s3:PutBucketAcl and block public access."},{"id":"b","text":"Build an AWS Config Conformance Pack that bundles the 's3-bucket-public-read-prohibited' managed rule with an AWS Systems Manager Automation remediation action targeting the non-compliant S3 bucket. Deploy the Conformance Pack at the AWS Organizations level via the delegated administrator account."},{"id":"c","text":"Use AWS Security Hub's FSBP standard, which includes the S3.2 control, and enable the control's built-in auto-remediation toggle in the Security Hub console."},{"id":"d","text":"Configure an AWS Config Aggregator in the management account, then write a daily AWS Lambda function that queries the aggregator for non-compliant resources and applies remediation via the AWS SDK."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines both capabilities needed: 'Conformance Packs: bundle of Config rules + remediation actions for a compliance framework; deploy across accounts via Organizations.' and 'Auto-remediation: trigger SSM Automation document when a rule is non-compliant.' By packaging the 's3-bucket-public-read-prohibited' managed rule alongside an SSM Automation remediation action inside a Conformance Pack and deploying it organization-wide, new accounts that join the organization automatically receive the rule and its remediation without additional manual steps. Option A satisfies near-real-time remediation but requires per-account EventBridge rules and a Lambda function, and new accounts must be onboarded manually. Option C is incorrect because Security Hub FSBP controls surface findings via Security Hub but Security Hub itself does not have a native 'auto-remediation toggle' — remediation requires an EventBridge + SSM/Lambda integration. Option D is incorrect because a Config Aggregator is read-only; it cannot initiate remediation actions, and daily polling does not meet the 'within minutes' requirement.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/conformance-packs.html","label":"AWS Config – Conformance Packs"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/remediation.html","label":"AWS Config – Remediating Non-Compliant Resources with AWS Config Rules"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/conformance-pack-organization-apis.html","label":"AWS Config – Deploying Conformance Packs across an Organization"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company uses AWS Config with the managed rule 's3-bucket-public-read-prohibited' across all accounts in AWS Organizations. When a bucket is found non-compliant, the operations team wants it automatically remediated within minutes without manual approval steps. The team also wants to ensure future deployments of this rule and its remediation action can be rolled out consistently to new accounts as they join the organization. Which approach best satisfies both requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a stateful web application on EC2 instances managed by an Auto Scaling Group (ASG). During scale-in events, some in-flight user transactions are being terminated abruptly before the application can finish processing them. The team needs to ensure that the application completes all in-flight requests before an instance is removed from service. Which combination of features should the team configure to BEST address this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure a Terminating:Wait lifecycle hook on the ASG, and send a CompleteLifecycleAction signal from the instance only after the application drains all in-flight requests."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable Capacity Rebalancing on the ASG so that at-risk instances are proactively replaced before termination, giving the application time to finish requests."},{"id":"c","text":"Set the ASG minimum capacity equal to the desired capacity so that scale-in events never occur."},{"id":"d","text":"Use Predictive Scaling to forecast demand and pre-launch instances, ensuring the ASG never needs to terminate instances during peak periods."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Lifecycle hooks: Pending:Wait and Terminating:Wait states; perform actions (bootstrap, drain) before transition; emit CompleteLifecycleAction to proceed.' A Terminating:Wait lifecycle hook pauses the instance in a waiting state during scale-in, giving the application the opportunity to finish processing in-flight requests before the instance is fully terminated. The team's code (or an automation script) then calls CompleteLifecycleAction to allow termination to proceed. Option B (Capacity Rebalancing) is specifically for proactively replacing at-risk Spot instances, not for draining in-flight requests on any scale-in. Option C eliminates scale-in entirely but is not a resilience strategy — it wastes cost and doesn't address the underlying need. Option D (Predictive Scaling) reduces the likelihood of scale-in during peaks but does not prevent abrupt termination when scale-in does occur.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/lifecycle-hooks.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling Lifecycle Hooks"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/APIReference/API_CompleteLifecycleAction.html","label":"CompleteLifecycleAction API Reference"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a stateful web application on EC2 instances managed by an Auto Scaling Group (ASG). During scale-in events, some in-flight user transactions are being terminated abruptly before the application can finish processing them. The team needs to ensure that the application completes all in-flight requests before an instance is removed from service. Which combination of features should the team configure to BEST address this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company runs a globally distributed e-commerce platform across two AWS Regions: us-east-1 (primary) and eu-west-1 (DR). Their RTO target is under 10 minutes and their RPO target is under 1 minute for the database tier. The database workload is write-intensive with complex relational queries. Which database architecture BEST satisfies both the RTO and RPO requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy an Amazon Aurora Global Database with the primary cluster in us-east-1 and a secondary cluster in eu-west-1; use managed planned failover for promotion, which completes in under 1 minute."},{"id":"b","text":"Deploy an Amazon RDS for MySQL Multi-AZ instance in us-east-1 and create a cross-Region Read Replica in eu-west-1; promote the Read Replica manually during a disaster."},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy a DynamoDB Global Table across us-east-1 and eu-west-1 to achieve active-active replication with eventual consistency."},{"id":"d","text":"Use AWS Backup to replicate RDS snapshots from us-east-1 to eu-west-1 every 15 minutes, and restore from the latest snapshot in the event of a failure."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Aurora Global Database: cross-Region replicated cluster with <1s lag for DR.' This directly satisfies the sub-1-minute RPO requirement. Aurora Global Database supports managed failover (promotion of a secondary cluster) that can complete in under a minute, satisfying the sub-10-minute RTO requirement. Option B (RDS Read Replica promotion) uses asynchronous replication, which may result in replication lag greater than 1 minute under heavy write loads, violating the RPO; manual promotion also risks longer RTO. Option C (DynamoDB Global Tables) offers 'eventually consistent' replication and is not appropriate for complex relational, write-intensive workloads that require ACID compliance. Option D (AWS Backup snapshot replication) falls squarely in the 'Backup & Restore' DR strategy category, which the source material classifies as having 'hours of RPO, hours of RTO' — far exceeding both targets.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/AuroraUserGuide/aurora-global-database.html","label":"Amazon Aurora Global Database"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/disaster-recovery-workloads-on-aws/disaster-recovery-options-in-the-cloud.html","label":"Disaster Recovery of Workloads on AWS – DR Strategies"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
