INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company hosts a public API behind an Application Load Balancer (ALB) in a single AWS Region. To improve resilience, the team is designing an active-passive failover architecture using a second Region. Route 53 will route traffic between the two Regions. The primary endpoint should receive all traffic under normal conditions; the secondary endpoint should only receive traffic when Route 53 health checks detect that the primary ALB is unhealthy. Which Route 53 configuration achieves this behavior with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create two Route 53 Weighted routing records — assign a weight of 100 to the primary ALB and a weight of 0 to the secondary ALB; manually update weights to 0 and 100 respectively during a failover event."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a Route 53 Failover routing policy with the primary ALB as the PRIMARY record and the secondary ALB as the SECONDARY record; attach an endpoint health check to the primary record so Route 53 automatically routes traffic to the secondary when the primary is unhealthy."},{"id":"c","text":"Create two Route 53 Latency-based routing records pointing to the primary and secondary ALBs; rely on latency measurements to automatically steer traffic away from the degraded Region."},{"id":"d","text":"Create a Route 53 Geolocation routing policy routing all traffic to the primary Region by default and configure a manual DNS update procedure to redirect to the secondary Region during failures."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'DNS Failover for active-passive DR; latency for active-active.' The Route 53 Failover routing policy is purpose-built for active-passive DR scenarios. By designating one record as PRIMARY and another as SECONDARY, and attaching a Route 53 health check to the primary endpoint, Route 53 automatically evaluates the health of the primary ALB and redirects DNS to the secondary record when the primary is determined to be unhealthy — with no manual intervention required. Option A (Weighted routing with manual weight changes) requires a human operator to detect the failure and update weights, introducing operational overhead and extending RTO. Option C (Latency-based routing) is designed for active-active architectures, as confirmed by the source material; it does not implement automatic failover and may still route some traffic to a degraded Region. Option D (Geolocation routing with manual DNS updates) again requires manual intervention, which increases operational overhead and does not satisfy the 'least operational overhead' requirement.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/dns-failover-configuring.html","label":"Amazon Route 53 – Configuring DNS Failover"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/routing-policy.html","label":"Amazon Route 53 Routing Policy Types"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/health-checks-how-route-53-chooses-records.html","label":"Amazon Route 53 Health Checks and DNS Failover"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
