INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is running a high-throughput microservices application on AWS Lambda. They want to publish custom business metrics (e.g., order count, payment errors) from each Lambda invocation without incurring excessive costs from repeated PutMetricData API calls. Which approach best meets this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Invoke PutMetricData synchronously at the end of every Lambda function execution to publish each custom metric individually."},{"id":"b","text":"Use the Embedded Metric Format (EMF) to write structured JSON log lines to CloudWatch Logs, allowing CloudWatch to automatically extract the custom metrics."},{"id":"c","text":"Create a CloudWatch Metric Filter on the Lambda log group that parses unstructured log lines and publishes a single metric using a fixed numeric pattern."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable CloudWatch Lambda Insights on each function and configure it to forward business-level metrics directly to CloudWatch Metrics."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Embedded Metric Format (EMF): structured JSON log line; CloudWatch automatically extracts metrics. Reduces API calls and cost.' EMF allows Lambda functions to embed metric data inside log events without making direct PutMetricData calls, which would add latency and cost at scale. Option A is costly and adds synchronous latency. Option C (Metric Filters) can extract numbers from logs but requires a predefined pattern and is limited to a single metric per filter — it is not designed for publishing multiple rich business metrics efficiently. Option D (Lambda Insights) provides operational/performance metrics (memory, CPU, duration) not arbitrary business-level custom metrics.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch_Embedded_Metric_Format_Specification.html","label":"CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format — Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch_Embedded_Metric_Format_Libraries.html","label":"Using EMF with AWS Lambda"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is running a high-throughput microservices application on AWS Lambda. They want to publish custom business metrics (e.g., order count, payment errors) from each Lambda invocation without incurring excessive costs from repeated PutMetricData API calls. Which approach best meets this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company operates 12 AWS accounts under AWS Organizations. Their security team wants a single consolidated view of CloudTrail API activity across all accounts AND the ability to run SQL queries against historical events spanning up to two years for compliance investigations. They also need anomaly detection on management API call volumes. Which combination of CloudTrail features satisfies ALL three requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an organization trail that delivers logs to a central S3 bucket, enable CloudTrail Insights events on the trail, and use Amazon Athena to query the S3 log files."},{"id":"b","text":"Create an organization trail with CloudTrail Lake as the event data store, enable CloudTrail Insights events, and use CloudTrail Lake's built-in SQL query engine for compliance investigations."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable a multi-region trail in each account, stream logs to CloudWatch Logs, and use CloudWatch Logs Insights queries for compliance investigations and anomaly detection."},{"id":"d","text":"Create an organization trail delivering to S3, enable Data Events for all accounts, and use CloudTrail Lake for SQL queries."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'CloudTrail Lake: managed SQL-queryable event data store' and 'Insights events: anomaly detection on management activity' and 'Multi-region trail + organization trail.' Option B satisfies all three requirements: (1) an organization trail provides consolidated API activity across all 12 accounts; (2) CloudTrail Lake provides managed, SQL-queryable storage covering the required retention window without manual Athena setup; (3) enabling Insights events on the trail provides anomaly detection on management API call volumes. Option A uses Athena against raw S3 files — functional but not the purpose-built managed query solution that CloudTrail Lake provides, and it still satisfies the requirements partially; however, Lake is the superior and purpose-built answer. Option C relies on CloudWatch Logs Insights, which is not designed for long-term compliance SQL queries across CloudTrail data at this scale. Option D enables Data Events (object-level S3/Lambda), which is unrelated to the management API anomaly and consolidation requirements described.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/awscloudtrail/latest/userguide/cloudtrail-lake.html","label":"AWS CloudTrail Lake — Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/awscloudtrail/latest/userguide/logging-insights-events-with-cloudtrail.html","label":"CloudTrail Insights — Identifying Unusual Activity"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/awscloudtrail/latest/userguide/creating-trail-organization.html","label":"Creating an Organization Trail"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company operates 12 AWS accounts under AWS Organizations. Their security team wants a single consolidated view of CloudTrail API activity across all accounts AND the ability to run SQL queries against historical events spanning up to two years for compliance investigations. They also need anomaly detection on management API call volumes. Which combination of CloudTrail features satisfies ALL three requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing an alerting strategy for a production e-commerce platform. The platform has 15 individual CloudWatch alarms covering CPU, memory, 5xx errors, database connections, and queue depth. The on-call team is suffering from alert fatigue because multiple correlated alarms fire simultaneously during a single incident. The engineer wants to ensure the on-call team receives ONE notification per incident rather than 15 separate notifications, while still preserving all individual alarm states for dashboards. What is the MOST operationally efficient solution?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Increase the evaluation periods on all 15 alarms to reduce sensitivity, and configure each alarm to send to a separate SNS topic so notifications are throttled."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a CloudWatch Composite Alarm using AND/OR logic over the 15 child alarms, and configure the SNS notification action only on the composite alarm while leaving the individual alarms without notification actions."},{"id":"c","text":"Replace all 15 alarms with a single multi-metric math alarm that combines all metrics into one expression, and send its notification to SNS."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable CloudWatch Anomaly Detection on each of the 15 alarms and configure a single EventBridge rule to deduplicate alarm state-change events before forwarding to SNS."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Composite alarms: AND/OR/NOT logic over child alarms; reduces alert fatigue.' This is precisely the use case composite alarms are designed for. By creating a composite alarm that references all 15 child alarms as inputs, the engineer can define the logical condition under which an incident is declared (e.g., if CPU OR 5xx errors are in ALARM) and attach the SNS notification only to the composite alarm. The individual alarms retain their states and remain visible on dashboards without triggering noise. Option A increases evaluation periods, which reduces sensitivity and can delay detection — this sacrifices correctness for noise reduction rather than solving the problem properly. Option C uses a multi-metric math alarm, which is a single metric computation and cannot replicate the diverse semantics of 15 independently configured alarms (thresholds, periods, datapoints-to-alarm) — it also loses independent alarm state visibility. Option D introduces EventBridge deduplication logic, which is a custom-built workaround; composite alarms are the native, purpose-built AWS solution for this exact scenario and require no custom deduplication code.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/Create_Composite_Alarm.html","label":"CloudWatch Composite Alarms — Reducing Alert Fatigue"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/AlarmThatSendsEmail.html","label":"CloudWatch Alarms — Overview of Alarm Types"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing an alerting strategy for a production e-commerce platform. The platform has 15 individual CloudWatch alarms covering CPU, memory, 5xx errors, database connections, and queue depth. The on-call team is suffering from alert fatigue because multiple correlated alarms fire simultaneously during a single incident. The engineer wants to ensure the on-call team receives ONE notification per incident rather than 15 separate notifications, while still preserving all individual alarm states for dashboards. What is the MOST operationally efficient solution?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is configuring AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager for a production workload. They need to ensure that if the primary on-call engineer does not acknowledge a page within 10 minutes, a secondary engineer is automatically notified. Which Incident Manager construct is PRIMARILY responsible for implementing this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A response plan configured with a severity level of 1 and a linked CloudWatch alarm action"},{"id":"b","text":"An escalation plan that defines a primary contact with an acknowledgment timeout and a secondary contact stage"},{"id":"c","text":"An SSM Automation runbook with a manual approval gate set to a 10-minute wait period"},{"id":"d","text":"An EventBridge rule with a rate-based schedule that publishes to an SNS topic after 10 minutes of inactivity"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Contacts and escalation plans: schedule on-call rotations with primary, secondary contacts; channels = email, SMS, voice. Engagement: notify on-call responders; auto-escalate if not acknowledged within configurable timeouts.' An escalation plan is the dedicated Incident Manager construct for defining staged contact notification with configurable acknowledgment timeouts — if the primary contact does not acknowledge within the configured window, Incident Manager automatically advances to the next stage and pages the secondary contact. Option A (response plan severity) controls the incident's metadata and template, not escalation logic. Option C (SSM Automation manual approval gate) is a runbook execution concept used for remediation steps, not for on-call paging escalation. Option D (EventBridge schedule) is an external workaround that would not integrate natively with Incident Manager's engagement tracking and acknowledgment state.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/escalation.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Escalation plans"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/contacts.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Contacts"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is configuring AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager for a production workload. They need to ensure that if the primary on-call engineer does not acknowledge a page within 10 minutes, a secondary engineer is automatically notified. Which Incident Manager construct is PRIMARILY responsible for implementing this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security team receives a GuardDuty HIGH-severity finding indicating that an EC2 instance is communicating with a known command-and-control server. The team wants to automatically isolate the compromised instance by swapping its security group AND notify the on-call security engineer via SMS — all within seconds of the finding being generated. Which combination of AWS services implements this automated remediation flow with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure an AWS Config rule to detect the GuardDuty finding; trigger an AWS Lambda function to swap the security group and publish an SMS via Amazon SNS"},{"id":"b","text":"Create an Amazon EventBridge rule matching the GuardDuty HIGH-severity finding event; set two targets — an AWS Lambda function (security-group swap) and an Amazon SNS topic (SMS to on-call engineer)"},{"id":"c","text":"Enable GuardDuty threat intelligence export to an S3 bucket; configure an S3 Event Notification to invoke Lambda for isolation and use Amazon SES for SMS alerting"},{"id":"d","text":"Use AWS Security Hub to aggregate the finding; create a custom action that manually triggers an SSM Automation runbook and sends an email via Amazon SES"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material directly describes this pattern: 'GuardDuty findings integrate with EventBridge: route HIGH severity finding -> SNS to on-call + Lambda to isolate compromised instance via security-group swap.' GuardDuty automatically publishes findings as events to the default EventBridge event bus. A single EventBridge rule with an event pattern matching the HIGH-severity finding can fan out to multiple targets simultaneously (the source notes '5+ targets per rule'), making it trivial to invoke Lambda for isolation and SNS for SMS notification in parallel with no additional polling or orchestration. Option A is incorrect because AWS Config rules evaluate resource configuration compliance — they do not natively consume GuardDuty finding events, introducing unnecessary complexity. Option C is incorrect because GuardDuty does not natively stream findings to S3 in real time in a way suited for sub-second response, and Amazon SES does not send SMS. Option D is incorrect because a Security Hub custom action requires a human to manually trigger it in the console, violating the 'within seconds' and 'automated' requirements.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_findings_cloudwatch.html","label":"Amazon GuardDuty – Integrating with Amazon EventBridge"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/eventbridge/latest/userguide/eb-targets.html","label":"Amazon EventBridge – Targets"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sns/latest/dg/sns-mobile-phone-number-as-subscriber.html","label":"Amazon SNS – Mobile text messaging (SMS)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security team receives a GuardDuty HIGH-severity finding indicating that an EC2 instance is communicating with a known command-and-control server. The team wants to automatically isolate the compromised instance by swapping its security group AND notify the on-call security engineer via SMS — all within seconds of the finding being generated. Which combination of AWS services implements this automated remediation flow with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a post-incident review process using AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager. After a Severity-1 outage, the engineer wants to capture a structured timeline of all responder engagements, runbook execution steps, and custom lessons-learned answers in a single artifact. Which Incident Manager feature should the engineer use to generate this artifact?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"The incident's chat channel transcript exported from AWS Chatbot to an S3 bucket"},{"id":"b","text":"The Incident Manager post-incident analysis, which provides a structured timeline of events, contact engagements, runbook execution, and supports custom questions"},{"id":"c","text":"An SSM OpsItem report generated by the AWS Systems Manager OpsCenter console"},{"id":"d","text":"An EventBridge event archive replay that reconstructs the sequence of events for the incident window"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Post-incident analysis: structured timeline of events, contact engagements, and runbook execution; supports custom questions.' Incident Manager's built-in post-incident analysis feature is purpose-built to produce exactly the artifact described — it aggregates the incident timeline, all engagement notifications and acknowledgments, every step of the associated runbook, and allows teams to append custom lessons-learned questions and answers. This makes it the correct and most direct answer. Option A is incorrect because AWS Chatbot chat transcripts are conversational logs, not structured incident analysis artifacts; they also require manual export and do not natively include runbook execution details or a formal timeline. Option C is incorrect because OpsCenter OpsItems track operational work items but do not provide the structured post-incident analysis format with timeline and runbook integration described. Option D is incorrect because EventBridge event archive replay is used to re-deliver historical events to rules for testing or reprocessing — it is not a post-incident review or analysis tool.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/analysis.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Post-incident analysis"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/what-is-incident-manager.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – What is Incident Manager?"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P1'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a post-incident review process using AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager. After a Severity-1 outage, the engineer wants to capture a structured timeline of all responder engagements, runbook execution steps, and custom lessons-learned answers in a single artifact. Which Incident Manager feature should the engineer use to generate this artifact?$patch$);

-- DOP-C02-P2: 15 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a multi-account AWS environment using CloudFormation StackSets. They need to ensure that whenever a new AWS account is added to a specific Organizational Unit (OU), a baseline security stack is automatically provisioned in that account without any manual intervention. Which StackSets configuration achieves this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use StackSets with self-managed permissions and configure a CloudWatch Events rule to trigger a Lambda function that calls CreateStackInstances whenever a new account joins the OU."},{"id":"b","text":"Use StackSets with service-managed permissions and AWS Organizations trusted access enabled, then configure Automatic Deployments with 'Enabled' set to true and retain stacks on account removal if desired."},{"id":"c","text":"Use StackSets with service-managed permissions and deploy the stack instance to the root OU; CloudFormation will automatically replicate to all child OUs and new accounts without additional configuration."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable CloudFormation Drift Detection on the StackSet so that any new account missing the stack is flagged, then use an AWS Config rule to remediate by calling CreateStackInstances."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'StackSets: deploy a stack across multiple accounts and regions from a single admin account; uses AWS Organizations for trusted access; supports service-managed permissions.' Service-managed permissions with Organizations trusted access unlocks the Automatic Deployments feature, which automatically provisions (and optionally retains or deletes) stack instances whenever accounts join or leave a targeted OU — no manual or Lambda-based intervention required. Option A would work functionally but requires manual orchestration and does not use the native StackSets automation capability. Option C is incorrect because targeting the root OU does not automatically enable the Automatic Deployments feature; that must be explicitly configured. Option D misuses Drift Detection, which compares deployed resources against the template for existing stacks and does not detect the absence of a stack in a new account.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/stacksets-orgs-enable-trusted-access.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation StackSets with AWS Organizations"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/stacksets-orgs-manage-auto-deployment.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation StackSets Automatic Deployments"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a multi-account AWS environment using CloudFormation StackSets. They need to ensure that whenever a new AWS account is added to a specific Organizational Unit (OU), a baseline security stack is automatically provisioned in that account without any manual intervention. Which StackSets configuration achieves this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A platform engineering team uses AWS CloudFormation to manage a production RDS MySQL database. During a recent deployment, an engineer accidentally submitted a stack update that modified the DBInstanceClass, causing unexpected downtime. The team wants to prevent any future stack updates from modifying or replacing the RDS DBInstance resource, while still allowing other resources in the same stack to be updated freely. Which CloudFormation feature should they implement, and how?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable stack termination protection on the stack; this prevents all updates and deletions of the stack, including changes to the RDS instance."},{"id":"b","text":"Set the DeletionPolicy attribute to 'Retain' on the RDS DBInstance resource; this prevents the resource from being modified or replaced during stack updates."},{"id":"c","text":"Apply a Stack Policy to the stack with a Deny statement scoped to the logical resource ID of the RDS DBInstance for all Update actions, while allowing updates on all other resources."},{"id":"d","text":"Use a CloudFormation Change Set with a manual approval gate before every execution; the Change Set preview will block updates to protected resources automatically."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Stack Policies: protect specific logical resources from updates (e.g., RDS DBInstance).' A Stack Policy is a JSON document attached to a stack that defines which update actions are allowed or denied on specific resources identified by their logical IDs or resource types. By adding a Deny rule for the RDS DBInstance's logical ID covering Update:Modify, Update:Replace, and Update:Delete actions, the team prevents accidental modification while leaving all other resources updatable. Option A is incorrect because termination protection only prevents stack deletion, not individual resource updates within the stack. Option B is incorrect because DeletionPolicy controls what happens to a resource when it is removed from the stack or the stack is deleted; it does not prevent in-place modifications during updates. Option D is incorrect because Change Sets preview changes but do not automatically block or enforce resource-level protection — a Change Set can still be executed against a protected resource unless a Stack Policy is in place.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/protect-stack-resources.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation Stack Policies"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-attribute-deletionpolicy.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation DeletionPolicy Attribute"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A platform engineering team uses AWS CloudFormation to manage a production RDS MySQL database. During a recent deployment, an engineer accidentally submitted a stack update that modified the DBInstanceClass, causing unexpected downtime. The team wants to prevent any future stack updates from modifying or replacing the RDS DBInstance resource, while still allowing other resources in the same stack to be updated freely. Which CloudFormation feature should they implement, and how?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is authoring an AWS CloudFormation template that provisions a Lambda function. The function's runtime environment variable DATABASE_URL must be populated at deploy time from a value stored in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store at the path /prod/app/db-url, without hardcoding the value in the template or in a CloudFormation Parameter. The Parameter Store value may be updated independently, and each CloudFormation deployment should always resolve the latest version. Which template construct correctly fulfills this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Declare a CloudFormation Parameter of type 'AWS::SSM::Parameter::Value<String>' with the path /prod/app/db-url as the Default, so CloudFormation resolves the current value at deploy time."},{"id":"b","text":"Use a dynamic reference in the Environment Variables property of the Lambda function resource: '{{resolve:ssm:/prod/app/db-url}}' without specifying a version number, so the latest value is always fetched."},{"id":"c","text":"Use the intrinsic function !Sub to embed the SSM path directly in the environment variable value: !Sub '${/prod/app/db-url}', which CloudFormation will automatically resolve to the Parameter Store value."},{"id":"d","text":"Create a CloudFormation Custom Resource backed by a Lambda function that calls the SSM GetParameter API and returns the value as a Custom Resource output, then reference it with !GetAtt."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Dynamic references in templates: {{resolve:ssm:/path:1}}, {{resolve:secretsmanager:secret-id:SecretString:key}}.' When a version label is omitted from an SSM dynamic reference (i.e., '{{resolve:ssm:/prod/app/db-url}}'), CloudFormation resolves the latest version of that parameter at each deployment, satisfying the requirement for always-current values without hardcoding. Option A is partially valid — 'AWS::SSM::Parameter::Value<String>' also resolves SSM values at deploy time — but it requires the path to be passed as a CloudFormation Parameter (either with a default or as user input), which means it is surfaced as a visible stack input and the requirement explicitly says to avoid CloudFormation Parameters. Option C is incorrect because !Sub only performs string substitution of CloudFormation variables and pseudo-parameters; it does not resolve SSM Parameter Store paths. Option D would work functionally but is unnecessarily complex when native dynamic references already provide this capability, and it introduces additional Lambda infrastructure and lifecycle management overhead.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/dynamic-references.html#dynamic-references-ssm","label":"AWS CloudFormation Dynamic References for SSM Parameter Store"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/parameters-section-structure.html#aws-ssm-parameter-types","label":"AWS CloudFormation Parameters with SSM Parameter Types"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is authoring an AWS CloudFormation template that provisions a Lambda function. The function's runtime environment variable DATABASE_URL must be populated at deploy time from a value stored in AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store at the path /prod/app/db-url, without hardcoding the value in the template or in a CloudFormation Parameter. The Parameter Store value may be updated independently, and each CloudFormation deployment should always resolve the latest version. Which template construct correctly fulfills this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team operates a multi-account AWS environment spanning five regions. They have enabled AWS Security Hub in every account and region. The security team wants a single pane of glass to review all findings from a designated us-east-1 management account without logging into each account or region individually. Which Security Hub feature should the team configure to satisfy this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable an AWS Config Aggregator in the management account and link all member accounts and regions to it."},{"id":"b","text":"Configure Security Hub Cross-Region aggregation by designating us-east-1 as the home Region and linking all other regions as contributing regions."},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy an EventBridge cross-account event bus in us-east-1 and create rules in every other region that forward Security Hub findings to it."},{"id":"d","text":"Use Amazon Macie's multi-account configuration to centralize all Security Hub findings into the designated administrator account."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Cross-Region aggregation: designate a home Region; linked Regions feed it for global visibility.' Configuring Security Hub Cross-Region aggregation with us-east-1 as the home Region allows all findings from linked (contributing) regions and member accounts to flow into one place, providing the unified view the team needs. Option A (AWS Config Aggregator) consolidates Config resource data, not Security Hub findings—it is a separate service feature. Option C (EventBridge cross-account bus) could route events but is not the Security Hub-native mechanism for aggregating findings across regions; it also requires significant custom infrastructure and does not surface findings inside the Security Hub console. Option D is incorrect because Macie is a sensitive-data discovery service and does not act as an aggregation layer for Security Hub.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/finding-aggregation.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Cross-Region aggregation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/securityhub-accounts.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Multiple-account management"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team operates a multi-account AWS environment spanning five regions. They have enabled AWS Security Hub in every account and region. The security team wants a single pane of glass to review all findings from a designated us-east-1 management account without logging into each account or region individually. Which Security Hub feature should the team configure to satisfy this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company's security policy requires that any AWS Config rule evaluating S3 bucket public-read access must automatically remediate non-compliant buckets without human intervention. The remediation must execute an existing SSM Automation runbook called DisableS3PublicRead. The team has already created the AWS Config managed rule s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited. What is the MOST operationally efficient next step to enforce automatic remediation?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an Amazon EventBridge rule that matches Config compliance-change events for the rule and triggers a Lambda function that calls the SSM Automation runbook."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable Auto-remediation on the s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited Config rule and associate it with the DisableS3PublicRead SSM Automation document as the remediation action."},{"id":"c","text":"Create an AWS Config Conformance Pack that bundles the s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited rule with a custom Lambda function to remove public access."},{"id":"d","text":"Subscribe an SNS topic to Config non-compliance notifications, then create an SNS filter policy to invoke the SSM Automation runbook directly from SNS."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Auto-remediation: trigger SSM Automation document when a rule is non-compliant.' AWS Config's built-in auto-remediation feature allows you to associate an SSM Automation document directly with a Config rule so that whenever a resource is evaluated as NON_COMPLIANT, the document is triggered automatically—no additional orchestration needed. This is the most operationally efficient approach because it uses a native integration with minimal infrastructure overhead. Option A (EventBridge + Lambda) would work but introduces additional components (a Lambda function) that must be written, maintained, and secured, making it less efficient than the native Config auto-remediation. Option C (Conformance Pack) is used for bundling rules and remediation actions for deployment across multiple accounts via Organizations, but does not by itself automate remediation without also enabling the auto-remediation setting on the rule. Option D is incorrect because SNS cannot directly invoke SSM Automation runbooks; SNS lacks that native integration.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/remediation.html","label":"AWS Config – Remediating Non-Compliant Resources with Auto Remediation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited.html","label":"AWS Config Managed Rules – s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company's security policy requires that any AWS Config rule evaluating S3 bucket public-read access must automatically remediate non-compliant buckets without human intervention. The remediation must execute an existing SSM Automation runbook called DisableS3PublicRead. The team has already created the AWS Config managed rule s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited. What is the MOST operationally efficient next step to enforce automatic remediation?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a pipeline for deploying IAM policies across production accounts. The security team mandates that any new IAM policy must be analyzed for overly permissive external access BEFORE it is deployed, so that violations block the pipeline. The engineer wants to use an AWS-native service that integrates directly into the CI/CD pipeline stage without requiring a deployed Lambda function or custom code. Which solution best meets these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable Amazon GuardDuty in all accounts and configure an EventBridge rule to send UnauthorizedAccess findings to an SNS topic that notifies the pipeline."},{"id":"b","text":"Use AWS Security Hub Automation Rules to suppress findings from newly created IAM policies and allow the pipeline to proceed only when no active findings exist."},{"id":"c","text":"Invoke IAM Access Analyzer's custom policy checks API (ValidatePolicy / CheckNoNewAccess) as a pipeline step to validate the policy document before deployment, and fail the stage if violations are returned."},{"id":"d","text":"Deploy an AWS Config custom rule backed by a Lambda function that evaluates IAM policies against a baseline and reports NON_COMPLIANT status to block the pipeline."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'IAM Access Analyzer: validates resource-based policies; reports external/unused access; custom policy checks (in CI/CD before deploy).' IAM Access Analyzer provides API-level policy validation (ValidatePolicy) and new-access comparison (CheckNoNewAccess / CheckAccessNotGranted) that can be called directly from a CI/CD pipeline step—for example, as a shell command using the AWS CLI or SDK—without deploying any Lambda functions or custom compute. If the API returns findings, the pipeline step exits with a non-zero code and blocks deployment. This is the only option that natively targets pre-deploy CI/CD enforcement for IAM policy analysis. Option A (GuardDuty) is a runtime threat-detection service; it analyzes live API calls and network activity, not policy documents at pipeline time. Option B (Security Hub Automation Rules) suppresses or modifies findings after the fact; it is not a deployment gate. Option D (Config custom rule + Lambda) evaluates deployed resources after the fact and does require custom Lambda code, violating the 'no Lambda' constraint.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/access-analyzer-policy-validation.html","label":"IAM Access Analyzer – Validating Policies"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/access-analyzer-custom-policy-checks.html","label":"IAM Access Analyzer – Custom Policy Checks (CheckNoNewAccess)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/access-analyzer-preview-access.html","label":"IAM Access Analyzer – Integrating into CI/CD Pipelines"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a pipeline for deploying IAM policies across production accounts. The security team mandates that any new IAM policy must be analyzed for overly permissive external access BEFORE it is deployed, so that violations block the pipeline. The engineer wants to use an AWS-native service that integrates directly into the CI/CD pipeline stage without requiring a deployed Lambda function or custom code. Which solution best meets these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team maintains a critical e-commerce application on EC2 instances managed by an Auto Scaling Group (ASG). During a major product launch, the team notices that newly launched instances take 8–10 minutes to fully bootstrap (install agents, warm caches, register with service discovery) before they can serve production traffic. During this window, the ALB health checks pass prematurely, sending traffic to instances that are not yet ready, causing user-facing errors. Which ASG feature should the team implement to ensure instances complete all bootstrap tasks BEFORE being placed into service?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure a Warm Pool with instances in Stopped state so pre-initialized instances are launched directly into InService without a bootstrap delay."},{"id":"b","text":"Add a Lifecycle Hook on the Pending:Wait state, perform all bootstrap tasks during the wait period, and then call CompleteLifecycleAction to allow the instance to transition to InService."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable Instance Refresh with the Canary strategy so only a small percentage of instances are replaced at a time, reducing the blast radius of unready instances."},{"id":"d","text":"Switch from a Launch Configuration to a Launch Template so that user-data scripts execute more reliably during instance initialization."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Lifecycle hooks: Pending:Wait and Terminating:Wait states; perform actions (bootstrap, drain) before transition; emit CompleteLifecycleAction to proceed.' A Pending:Wait lifecycle hook holds the instance in a waiting state before it transitions to InService, giving the bootstrap process the full time it needs. Only after CompleteLifecycleAction is called does the ASG move the instance into InService and register it with the load balancer. Option A (Warm Pool) pre-initializes instances but does not by itself gate traffic until custom bootstrap completes—it addresses cold-start time, not mid-launch readiness gating. Option C (Instance Refresh / Canary) controls the rollout pace of AMI updates and does not solve the bootstrap readiness problem. Option D (Launch Template) is a best-practice configuration improvement but does not control when an instance begins receiving traffic.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/lifecycle-hooks.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling – Lifecycle Hooks"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/lifecycle-hooks-overview.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling – How Lifecycle Hooks Work"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team maintains a critical e-commerce application on EC2 instances managed by an Auto Scaling Group (ASG). During a major product launch, the team notices that newly launched instances take 8–10 minutes to fully bootstrap (install agents, warm caches, register with service discovery) before they can serve production traffic. During this window, the ALB health checks pass prematurely, sending traffic to instances that are not yet ready, causing user-facing errors. Which ASG feature should the team implement to ensure instances complete all bootstrap tasks BEFORE being placed into service?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A financial services company runs a mission-critical OLTP workload on Amazon Aurora MySQL. Their DR requirements mandate an RTO of less than 1 minute and an RPO of less than 1 second for a regional failure. The application is currently deployed in us-east-1 only. Which architecture change BEST meets these DR requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an RDS Read Replica in us-west-2. In the event of a regional failure, manually promote the replica and update the application connection string."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable Aurora Multi-AZ by adding Aurora Replicas in different Availability Zones within us-east-1 to provide automatic failover."},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy an Aurora Global Database with a secondary cluster in us-west-2, and use Route 53 Failover routing with health checks to redirect traffic to the secondary cluster upon a regional failure."},{"id":"d","text":"Configure AWS Backup with cross-Region copy to replicate Aurora snapshots to us-west-2 hourly, and restore from snapshot during a disaster."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Aurora Global Database: cross-Region replicated cluster with <1s lag for DR.' This directly satisfies the RPO of less than 1 second. Aurora Global Database also supports managed planned and unplanned failover (switchover/detach-and-promote), enabling RTO in the sub-minute range. Combining it with Route 53 Failover routing and health checks automates traffic redirection. Option A (RDS Read Replica promotion) is a manual process with higher RTO and uses asynchronous replication, which may not achieve sub-second RPO. Option B (Multi-AZ within a single Region) does not protect against a full regional failure—it only covers AZ-level failures. Option D (AWS Backup cross-Region copy) is classified as a Backup & Restore strategy with 'hours of RPO, hours of RTO' per the source, which does not meet the stated requirements.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/AuroraUserGuide/aurora-global-database.html","label":"Amazon Aurora Global Database"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/dns-failover.html","label":"Route 53 – Configuring DNS Failover"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/disaster-recovery-workloads-on-aws/disaster-recovery-options-in-the-cloud.html","label":"AWS Disaster Recovery – DR Strategies"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A financial services company runs a mission-critical OLTP workload on Amazon Aurora MySQL. Their DR requirements mandate an RTO of less than 1 minute and an RPO of less than 1 second for a regional failure. The application is currently deployed in us-east-1 only. Which architecture change BEST meets these DR requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a cost-optimized, highly available web tier using an EC2 Auto Scaling Group behind an Application Load Balancer. The workload is latency-sensitive and cannot tolerate interruptions, but the team wants to reduce EC2 costs by up to 70% where possible. The ASG must also proactively replace EC2 instances that AWS signals are at elevated risk of interruption before they are actually reclaimed. Which combination of ASG features should the engineer configure?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use a Mixed Instances Policy with a blend of On-Demand and Spot instance types, and enable Capacity Rebalancing on the ASG."},{"id":"b","text":"Use Scheduled Scaling to increase On-Demand capacity during peak hours and scale in to zero Spot instances during off-peak periods."},{"id":"c","text":"Use Predictive Scaling to forecast demand and pre-provision exclusively Spot instances, relying on ASG health checks to replace any interrupted instances."},{"id":"d","text":"Configure a Warm Pool of Spot instances in Stopped state and use Target Tracking scaling based on ALB RequestCountPerTarget to launch them on demand."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states two directly relevant features: 'Mixed instances policy + multiple purchase options: blend On-Demand + Spot + RIs' and 'Capacity Rebalancing: proactively replace at-risk Spot instances.' Using a Mixed Instances Policy allows the ASG to maintain a baseline of reliable On-Demand capacity while using Spot for the remainder, achieving the cost savings target. Enabling Capacity Rebalancing means the ASG monitors EC2 Rebalance Recommendation signals and launches replacement instances before an at-risk Spot instance is interrupted, maintaining availability. Option B (Scheduled Scaling to zero Spot) is reactive and time-based, not demand-driven, and does not address Spot interruption. Option C (exclusively Spot via Predictive Scaling) does not protect against interruptions since there is no On-Demand baseline, and standard health-check replacement happens after interruption, not before. Option D (Warm Pool of Spot instances) helps with launch latency but does not proactively guard against interruptions across the running fleet.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/ec2-auto-scaling-mixed-instances-groups.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling – Mixed Instances Policy"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/ec2-auto-scaling-capacity-rebalancing.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling – Capacity Rebalancing"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/spot-best-practices.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Spot – Best Practices for Spot Instances"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a cost-optimized, highly available web tier using an EC2 Auto Scaling Group behind an Application Load Balancer. The workload is latency-sensitive and cannot tolerate interruptions, but the team wants to reduce EC2 costs by up to 70% where possible. The ASG must also proactively replace EC2 instances that AWS signals are at elevated risk of interruption before they are actually reclaimed. Which combination of ASG features should the engineer configure?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is building a high-throughput microservices application on AWS. They want to publish custom performance metrics from hundreds of Lambda functions without incurring excessive CloudWatch PutMetricData API costs or hitting API throttle limits. Which approach best addresses both concerns simultaneously?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Batch custom metric data points and call PutMetricData with up to 1,000 data points per API call from each Lambda function."},{"id":"b","text":"Use the CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format (EMF) to write structured JSON log lines to CloudWatch Logs, allowing CloudWatch to automatically extract metrics without direct PutMetricData calls."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable Lambda Insights on every function and rely solely on the default Lambda Insights metrics for all custom performance tracking."},{"id":"d","text":"Stream Lambda log groups to Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose via a Subscription Filter, then use a custom parser on the receiving end to reconstruct metrics."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Embedded Metric Format (EMF): structured JSON log line; CloudWatch automatically extracts metrics. Reduces API calls and cost.' By writing EMF-formatted JSON to stdout (which Lambda routes to CloudWatch Logs), functions never call PutMetricData directly, eliminating per-call API costs and throttling risk. Option A is technically valid but still consumes PutMetricData quota and incurs per-metric API costs at scale. Option C relies on preset Lambda Insights metrics and cannot capture arbitrary custom dimensions. Option D adds architectural complexity and latency without solving the core cost/throttle problem at the source.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch_Embedded_Metric_Format_Specification.html","label":"CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format – Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/monitoring-metrics.html","label":"Using CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format with AWS Lambda"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is building a high-throughput microservices application on AWS. They want to publish custom performance metrics from hundreds of Lambda functions without incurring excessive CloudWatch PutMetricData API costs or hitting API throttle limits. Which approach best addresses both concerns simultaneously?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A platform engineering team manages 15 AWS accounts under AWS Organizations. The security operations center (SOC) wants a single-pane-of-glass view of CloudWatch alarms and metrics across all accounts without requiring engineers to switch console contexts. Individual account teams are receiving too many isolated low-severity alarms, creating alert fatigue. Which combination of features BEST solves both the unified visibility requirement and the alert fatigue problem?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable CloudTrail organization trail to centralize all account activity in one S3 bucket, then use CloudTrail Lake SQL queries to visualize alarm state across accounts."},{"id":"b","text":"Configure CloudWatch cross-account observability using AWS Organizations to link all source accounts to a central monitoring account, and define Composite Alarms in the monitoring account using AND/OR/NOT logic over child alarms from source accounts."},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy CloudWatch Synthetics canaries in each account and aggregate canary results into a central S3 bucket using Subscription Filters pointed at Kinesis Data Firehose."},{"id":"d","text":"Create individual SNS topics in each of the 15 accounts and subscribe a central Lambda function that fans out notifications to the SOC, using metric math alarms to suppress low-severity alerts."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Cross-account observability: monitor multiple source accounts from one monitoring account; via AWS Organizations or per-account links.' This directly addresses the unified visibility requirement. For alert fatigue, the source states: 'Composite alarms: AND/OR/NOT logic over child alarms; reduces alert fatigue.' Combining these two features in the central monitoring account lets the SOC view all account metrics in one place and suppress noisy child alarms until compound conditions are met. Option A uses CloudTrail, which records API calls rather than metric alarm states and does not reduce alert fatigue. Option C addresses endpoint availability, not cross-account alarm aggregation. Option D is operationally fragile and does not leverage native CloudWatch cross-account capabilities.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch-Unified-Cross-Account.html","label":"CloudWatch Cross-Account Observability"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/Create_Composite_Alarm.html","label":"CloudWatch Composite Alarms"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A platform engineering team manages 15 AWS accounts under AWS Organizations. The security operations center (SOC) wants a single-pane-of-glass view of CloudWatch alarms and metrics across all accounts without requiring engineers to switch console contexts. Individual account teams are receiving too many isolated low-severity alarms, creating alert fatigue. Which combination of features BEST solves both the unified visibility requirement and the alert fatigue problem?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A financial services company requires near-real-time anomaly detection on AWS Management Console sign-in activity to detect potential credential compromise. They also need the ability to run ad-hoc SQL queries against up to 90 days of historical API call data for forensic investigations. Which architecture satisfies BOTH requirements using native AWS services?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable CloudTrail Insights events on the organization trail for anomaly detection, and enable CloudTrail Lake with a retention period of 90 days to support SQL-based forensic queries against historical event data."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a CloudWatch Metric Filter on CloudTrail logs delivered to CloudWatch Logs to count sign-in events, set a CloudWatch Anomaly Detection alarm on that metric, and query raw log data using CloudWatch Logs Insights for forensic investigation."},{"id":"c","text":"Stream CloudTrail logs to Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose, deliver them to Amazon OpenSearch Service, and use OpenSearch anomaly detection dashboards for both real-time alerting and historical SQL queries."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable AWS Config with a custom rule that evaluates IAM sign-in events and triggers an AWS Systems Manager Automation document, storing Config snapshots in S3 for historical querying via Amazon Athena."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material provides two directly relevant passages. First: 'CloudTrail Insights events: anomaly detection on management activity.' Console sign-in events are management (control plane) events, so Insights will detect unusual sign-in patterns natively. Second: 'CloudTrail Lake: managed SQL-queryable event data store.' CloudTrail Lake natively supports SQL queries over retained event data, satisfying the 90-day forensic requirement without additional infrastructure. Option B is partially valid — CloudWatch Anomaly Detection on a metric filter can detect unusual volume, but it operates on an extracted metric (count), not the richer event context; CloudWatch Logs Insights uses its own query language rather than SQL, and this option requires extra setup to match what Insights events provide natively. Option C relies on OpenSearch, which is not referenced in the source and adds operational overhead; OpenSearch does not natively expose SQL against CloudTrail data in the same managed way as CloudTrail Lake. Option D misuses AWS Config, which evaluates resource configurations, not real-time API call anomalies.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/awscloudtrail/latest/userguide/logging-insights-events-with-cloudtrail.html","label":"CloudTrail Insights – Identifying Unusual API Activity"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/awscloudtrail/latest/userguide/cloudtrail-lake.html","label":"AWS CloudTrail Lake – Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A financial services company requires near-real-time anomaly detection on AWS Management Console sign-in activity to detect potential credential compromise. They also need the ability to run ad-hoc SQL queries against up to 90 days of historical API call data for forensic investigations. Which architecture satisfies BOTH requirements using native AWS services?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is configuring AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager to handle high-severity production incidents. They want on-call responders to be automatically notified when an incident is created, and if a responder does not acknowledge the page within a defined timeout window, the system should escalate to a secondary contact. Which Incident Manager constructs must be configured together to achieve this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A response plan that references an escalation plan; the escalation plan defines primary and secondary contacts with a configurable acknowledgement timeout between each engagement stage."},{"id":"b","text":"A CloudWatch alarm action that directly invokes an SNS topic; the SNS topic has two subscriptions — one for the primary contact and one for the secondary contact — with a time-delay policy between deliveries."},{"id":"c","text":"An EventBridge rule that triggers an AWS Lambda function; the Lambda function sends an SMS to the primary contact and, after sleeping for the timeout duration, sends an SMS to the secondary contact."},{"id":"d","text":"A response plan that contains an embedded runbook; the runbook includes two sequential manual approval gates, one targeting the primary contact and one targeting the secondary contact, each with its own timeout."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Contacts and escalation plans: schedule on-call rotations with primary, secondary contacts; channels = email, SMS, voice' and 'Engagement: notify on-call responders; auto-escalate if not acknowledged within configurable timeouts.' Incident Manager models this through two distinct constructs: (1) Contacts/Escalation Plans, which define who to notify and in what order with what timeouts, and (2) Response Plans, which reference those escalation plans and define the incident's overall properties including severity and chat channel. Option B is incorrect because SNS has no native time-delay or acknowledgement-tracking mechanism between subscribers. Option C is incorrect because a Lambda sleep-based approach is fragile, does not integrate with Incident Manager's acknowledgement tracking, and would not appear in the post-incident timeline. Option D is incorrect because runbook approval gates are designed for remediation workflow control, not for on-call engagement escalation.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/contacts.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Contacts and escalation plans"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/response-plans.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Response plans"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is configuring AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager to handle high-severity production incidents. They want on-call responders to be automatically notified when an incident is created, and if a responder does not acknowledge the page within a defined timeout window, the system should escalate to a secondary contact. Which Incident Manager constructs must be configured together to achieve this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security team receives an Amazon GuardDuty HIGH severity finding indicating that an EC2 instance may be communicating with a known command-and-control server. The team requires an automated response that simultaneously: (1) notifies the on-call security engineer via SMS, and (2) isolates the compromised instance by replacing its security group with a restrictive 'quarantine' security group. They want the solution to be event-driven with no polling. Which architecture satisfies BOTH requirements with the least operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an Amazon EventBridge rule that matches GuardDuty HIGH severity findings. Configure two targets on the rule: an SNS topic (which has an SMS subscription for the on-call engineer) and an AWS Lambda function that calls ec2:ModifyInstanceAttribute to swap the instance's security group to the quarantine group."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable GuardDuty threat intelligence export to an S3 bucket. Configure an S3 Event Notification to invoke a Lambda function that sends an SNS SMS and calls ec2:ModifyInstanceAttribute to swap the security group."},{"id":"c","text":"Create a CloudWatch Metric Filter on GuardDuty logs in CloudWatch Logs. When the filter matches a HIGH severity pattern, trigger a CloudWatch Alarm that sends to an SNS topic. Configure the SNS topic to invoke a Lambda function that both sends an SMS and swaps the security group."},{"id":"d","text":"Use AWS Security Hub to aggregate GuardDuty findings. Create an EventBridge rule on Security Hub findings of HIGH severity. Configure a single SNS target; use an SNS subscription filter policy to route security-group-swap commands to a Lambda subscriber and SMS notifications to the on-call engineer."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'GuardDuty findings integrate with EventBridge: route HIGH severity finding -> SNS to on-call + Lambda to isolate compromised instance via security-group swap.' EventBridge natively receives GuardDuty findings on the default event bus and supports 5+ targets per rule, making it straightforward to fan out to both an SNS topic and a Lambda function in a single rule with no polling. Option B introduces unnecessary latency and complexity by routing through S3 export, which is designed for batch analysis rather than real-time response. Option C is architecturally unsound because GuardDuty findings are not structured as CloudWatch Logs metric data; CloudWatch Metric Filters apply to log streams, not GuardDuty finding events. Option D routes through Security Hub, which adds an extra aggregation layer and increases response latency; additionally, SNS subscription filter policies act on message attributes, not command routing, so using them to 'route commands' as described is a misuse of the feature.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_findings_cloudwatch.html","label":"Amazon GuardDuty – Automatically responding to GuardDuty findings with EventBridge"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/eventbridge/latest/userguide/eb-targets.html","label":"Amazon EventBridge – Targets for rules"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/runbooks.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Automated remediation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security team receives an Amazon GuardDuty HIGH severity finding indicating that an EC2 instance may be communicating with a known command-and-control server. The team requires an automated response that simultaneously: (1) notifies the on-call security engineer via SMS, and (2) isolates the compromised instance by replacing its security group with a restrictive 'quarantine' security group. They want the solution to be event-driven with no polling. Which architecture satisfies BOTH requirements with the least operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a post-incident review process using AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager. After a Severity-1 database outage is resolved, the engineering manager wants to review a structured account of: (a) the exact timeline of AWS service events that contributed to the incident, (b) which on-call contacts were engaged and when, and (c) which runbook steps were executed and whether any required manual approval. Which Incident Manager feature directly provides this consolidated view, and what additional capability does it support to improve future incident response?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Post-incident analysis: automatically generates a structured timeline of events, contact engagements, and runbook execution steps; also supports custom questions to capture team-specific retrospective data for continuous improvement."},{"id":"b","text":"AWS CloudTrail: records all Incident Manager API calls including CreateIncident and UpdateIncident; the engineer can build an Athena query over the CloudTrail S3 export to reconstruct the timeline, contacts notified, and runbook steps taken."},{"id":"c","text":"Amazon CloudWatch Contributor Insights: analyzes Incident Manager metric streams to identify which contacts and runbook steps had the highest contribution to mean-time-to-resolve (MTTR) and surfaces them in a ranked report."},{"id":"d","text":"AWS Chatbot: logs every chat-ops command issued during the incident in a Microsoft Teams or Slack channel; the engineer exports the chat transcript and uses it as the official post-incident timeline and approval audit trail."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Post-incident analysis: structured timeline of events, contact engagements, and runbook execution; supports custom questions.' This is a built-in Incident Manager feature specifically designed for structured retrospectives — it natively aggregates the three data points the manager requires (event timeline, contact engagement log, and runbook step execution) without any custom querying or scripting. The 'custom questions' capability extends it for team-specific retrospective workflows, directly addressing continuous improvement. Option B is technically possible but operationally heavyweight; CloudTrail records API calls, not a human-readable incident narrative, and requires non-trivial Athena query engineering to reconstruct a coherent timeline — it is not the purpose-built feature. Option C is incorrect because CloudWatch Contributor Insights is designed for log analysis to identify high-cardinality contributors (e.g., top API callers), not for incident retrospectives or runbook audit trails. Option D is incorrect because AWS Chatbot provides chat-based notifications and limited read-only CLI execution; it does not serve as an authoritative audit or approval trail, and exporting chat transcripts is not an Incident Manager post-incident analysis feature.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/analysis.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Post-incident analysis"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/runbooks.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Runbooks"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P2'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a post-incident review process using AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager. After a Severity-1 database outage is resolved, the engineering manager wants to review a structured account of: (a) the exact timeline of AWS service events that contributed to the incident, (b) which on-call contacts were engaged and when, and (c) which runbook steps were executed and whether any required manual approval. Which Incident Manager feature directly provides this consolidated view, and what additional capability does it support to improve future incident response?$patch$);

-- DOP-C02-P3: 15 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a CloudFormation stack to production that includes an RDS DB instance. Before executing the update, the team lead wants to review exactly which resources will change and how, without affecting the live environment. After review, a second approval gate must be passed before changes are applied. Which CloudFormation feature satisfies BOTH requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable drift detection on the existing stack, review the drift report, then apply the update directly."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a Change Set against the existing stack, review it, and only execute the Change Set after the approval gate is passed."},{"id":"c","text":"Apply a Stack Policy to the RDS resource, attempt the update, and review the error message to identify what would change."},{"id":"d","text":"Deploy a nested stack with the proposed changes in a separate environment, compare outputs, then promote to production."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Change Sets: preview proposed changes before executing them. Useful for production review/approval gates.' A Change Set allows the team to see a detailed list of proposed resource changes (additions, modifications, replacements, deletions) without touching the live stack. The Change Set sits in a PENDING state until explicitly executed, which maps directly to the second approval-gate requirement. Option A (drift detection) compares deployed resources against the template but does not preview future changes from an update — it is retrospective, not prospective. Option C misuses Stack Policies, which protect resources from unintended updates rather than previewing changes. Option D introduces unnecessary complexity and environmental drift; it does not satisfy the requirement of previewing changes to the production stack itself.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/using-cfn-updating-stacks-changesets.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – Updating Stacks Using Change Sets"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/using-cfn-updating-stacks-changesets-create.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – Change Set Concepts"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a CloudFormation stack to production that includes an RDS DB instance. Before executing the update, the team lead wants to review exactly which resources will change and how, without affecting the live environment. After review, a second approval gate must be passed before changes are applied. Which CloudFormation feature satisfies BOTH requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization uses AWS CloudFormation StackSets to deploy a standardized VPC configuration across 40 AWS accounts in 5 regions. The security team requires that new accounts added to the AWS Organizations OU automatically receive the VPC stack without manual intervention. Which StackSets configuration satisfies this requirement with the least operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use self-managed permissions with a scheduled Lambda function that lists new accounts and calls CreateStackInstances for each."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable service-managed permissions on the StackSet and enable automatic deployments targeting the AWS Organizations OU, so new accounts are enrolled upon joining."},{"id":"c","text":"Use an AWS Config rule with a remediation action that triggers a CloudFormation stack creation whenever a new account is detected."},{"id":"d","text":"Configure a CloudWatch Events rule that detects account creation events and invokes a Step Functions workflow to run CloudFormation CreateStack in each region."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'StackSets: deploy a stack across multiple accounts and regions from a single admin account; uses AWS Organizations for trusted access; supports service-managed permissions.' With service-managed permissions, StackSets integrates directly with AWS Organizations and includes an 'Automatic Deployments' setting. When enabled, any account that joins the targeted OU automatically receives a stack instance without any manual or programmatic intervention. This is the purpose-built feature for this use case. Option A requires building and maintaining a custom Lambda polling solution, which is significantly more operational overhead. Option C repurposes AWS Config remediation, which is designed for compliance correction, not initial provisioning across accounts, and adds unnecessary complexity. Option D with Step Functions and CloudWatch Events can work but duplicates functionality already native to StackSets service-managed mode, violating the least-overhead requirement.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/stacksets-orgs-enable-trusted-access.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – StackSets with Service-Managed Permissions"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/stacksets-orgs-manage-auto-deployment.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – Automatic Deployments for StackSets"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization uses AWS CloudFormation StackSets to deploy a standardized VPC configuration across 40 AWS accounts in 5 regions. The security team requires that new accounts added to the AWS Organizations OU automatically receive the VPC stack without manual intervention. Which StackSets configuration satisfies this requirement with the least operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is writing an AWS CDK application in Python to provision infrastructure. A junior team member asks what the practical difference is between using an L1 construct (e.g., CfnBucket) and an L2 construct (e.g., Bucket) for an S3 bucket, specifically regarding how much configuration must be provided. Which answer is MOST accurate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"L1 constructs synthesize to AWS SAM templates, while L2 constructs synthesize to CloudFormation templates, so they are used in different deployment pipelines."},{"id":"b","text":"L1 constructs map one-to-one with CloudFormation resource types and expose every raw CloudFormation property, requiring explicit configuration; L2 constructs are higher-level abstractions that apply secure defaults and expose intent-based APIs, reducing the amount of boilerplate needed."},{"id":"c","text":"L1 and L2 constructs are functionally identical; the difference is only cosmetic — L2 constructs use camelCase method names while L1 constructs use PascalCase property names."},{"id":"d","text":"L2 constructs are only available for core services like EC2 and S3, whereas L1 constructs cover all AWS services; teams should default to L1 to ensure full service coverage."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Construct levels: L1 (CfnXxx, 1:1 to CloudFormation), L2 (high-level resource), L3 (patterns/Solution constructs).' L1 constructs (prefixed with 'Cfn') are direct, auto-generated mappings of CloudFormation resource specifications. Every CloudFormation property must be specified manually, mirroring what you would write in a raw template. L2 constructs are curated, higher-level abstractions that encapsulate common configuration patterns and apply opinionated, security-conscious defaults (e.g., blocking public access on S3 by default, generating IAM grant methods). This dramatically reduces the boilerplate required. Option A is incorrect — both L1 and L2 constructs synthesize to standard CloudFormation templates via 'cdk synth'; neither produces SAM templates by default. Option C is incorrect because the difference is substantive, not cosmetic — L2 constructs fundamentally change what configuration is required and what defaults are applied. Option D is incorrect because CDK's L2 library covers a broad range of services, and the framing incorrectly implies L1 is preferable for coverage reasons.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cdk/v2/guide/constructs.html","label":"AWS CDK – Constructs (L1, L2, L3 Overview)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cdk/api/v2/docs/aws-cdk-lib.aws_s3.Bucket.html","label":"AWS CDK API Reference – aws-s3 Bucket (L2) vs CfnBucket (L1)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is writing an AWS CDK application in Python to provision infrastructure. A junior team member asks what the practical difference is between using an L1 construct (e.g., CfnBucket) and an L2 construct (e.g., Bucket) for an S3 bucket, specifically regarding how much configuration must be provided. Which answer is MOST accurate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a new microservices architecture across 12 AWS accounts in four Regions. The security team requires a single pane of glass for all security findings from GuardDuty, Amazon Inspector, and AWS Config, with findings normalized into a common schema. The team designates us-east-1 as the primary visibility Region. Which combination of actions correctly satisfies these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable AWS Security Hub in every account and Region, configure cross-Region aggregation with us-east-1 as the home Region, and enable GuardDuty, Inspector, and AWS Config in all accounts so their findings are automatically ingested by Security Hub in ASFF format."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a custom Lambda function that polls GuardDuty, Inspector, and AWS Config APIs in each account and Region every 5 minutes, transforms findings into a proprietary schema, and writes them to an S3 bucket in us-east-1 for Athena queries."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable AWS Security Hub only in us-east-1, deploy GuardDuty and Inspector exclusively in us-east-1, and use VPC peering to route all inter-Region traffic through us-east-1 so a single Security Hub instance captures all findings."},{"id":"d","text":"Use Amazon EventBridge cross-Region event buses to forward all GuardDuty, Inspector, and Config findings to a central event bus in us-east-1, then store raw JSON payloads in DynamoDB for a custom security dashboard."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Per the source material, 'AWS Security Hub consolidates findings from GuardDuty, Inspector, Macie, AWS Config, IAM Access Analyzer, Firewall Manager, and third-party partner products' and 'uses AWS Security Finding Format (ASFF) as the normalized finding schema.' The cross-Region aggregation feature allows a designated home Region (us-east-1 here) to receive findings from all linked Regions, providing the single-pane-of-glass view the security team requires. Option A is the only answer that leverages Security Hub's native multi-source aggregation, ASFF normalization, and cross-Region aggregation simultaneously with the least operational overhead. Option B creates unnecessary custom code and lacks normalization. Option C incorrectly assumes GuardDuty and Inspector need to run only in one Region — services must be enabled in every Region where workloads exist. Option D provides event routing but not normalization into ASFF, and introduces custom storage and dashboard overhead.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/securityhub-findings-providers.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Findings from AWS services"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/finding-aggregation.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Cross-Region aggregation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/securityhub-findings-format.html","label":"AWS Security Finding Format (ASFF)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a new microservices architecture across 12 AWS accounts in four Regions. The security team requires a single pane of glass for all security findings from GuardDuty, Amazon Inspector, and AWS Config, with findings normalized into a common schema. The team designates us-east-1 as the primary visibility Region. Which combination of actions correctly satisfies these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization must enforce PCI DSS compliance across all AWS accounts managed under AWS Organizations. A DevOps engineer needs to deploy a standard set of AWS Config rules AND associated SSM Automation remediation actions to every account and Region in the organization with a single deployment operation. Non-compliant resources must be automatically remediated without manual intervention. Which AWS-native mechanism is the MOST operationally efficient way to achieve this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Write individual AWS Config managed rules in every member account using AWS CloudFormation StackSets, and create separate EventBridge rules in each account to invoke SSM Automation documents upon non-compliance events."},{"id":"b","text":"Deploy an AWS Config Conformance Pack that bundles the required Config rules and remediation actions, using AWS Organizations integration to deploy the pack across all member accounts and Regions from the management account in a single operation."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable AWS Security Hub with the PCI DSS security standard in the management account only, and configure cross-account IAM roles so Security Hub can evaluate and auto-remediate resources in all member accounts."},{"id":"d","text":"Create a custom Lambda function triggered nightly by EventBridge Scheduler that iterates through all accounts, evaluates Config rules using the AWS SDK, and calls SSM Automation for each non-compliant resource."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states that AWS Config Conformance Packs are a 'bundle of Config rules + remediation actions for a compliance framework' and can be 'deploy[ed] across accounts via Organizations.' This directly maps to the requirement: a single deployment from the management account that pushes both rules and auto-remediation to every member account and Region. The auto-remediation capability is also noted: 'Auto-remediation: trigger SSM Automation document when a rule is non-compliant.' Option A uses StackSets and separate EventBridge rules, which works but requires managing two separate constructs and more operational steps — not the most efficient. Option C misrepresents Security Hub's capabilities; while Security Hub offers a PCI DSS standard, it evaluates controls through Config and does not provide native cross-account remediation. Option D introduces custom code with significant operational overhead and a nightly delay that violates continuous compliance requirements.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/conformance-packs.html","label":"AWS Config Conformance Packs"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/conformance-pack-organization-apis.html","label":"Deploying Conformance Packs across an organization"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/remediation.html","label":"AWS Config Auto Remediation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization must enforce PCI DSS compliance across all AWS accounts managed under AWS Organizations. A DevOps engineer needs to deploy a standard set of AWS Config rules AND associated SSM Automation remediation actions to every account and Region in the organization with a single deployment operation. Non-compliant resources must be automatically remediated without manual intervention. Which AWS-native mechanism is the MOST operationally efficient way to achieve this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer discovers that Amazon GuardDuty has generated a finding of type UnauthorizedAccess:IAMUser/MaliciousIPCaller.Custom for a production account. The incident response runbook requires that when this specific finding type is detected, the implicated IAM user must be automatically quarantined by attaching a deny-all policy, and the on-call team must be notified via PagerDuty within 2 minutes. The solution must require NO manual steps once a finding is generated. Which architecture correctly implements this automated response pipeline?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure an AWS Security Hub automation rule that matches the finding type, sets the finding workflow status to NOTIFIED, and then directly calls the PagerDuty API and the IAM AttachUserPolicy API from within the automation rule's action configuration."},{"id":"b","text":"Create an Amazon EventBridge rule that matches GuardDuty findings of type UnauthorizedAccess:IAMUser/MaliciousIPCaller.Custom, set a Lambda function as the target that attaches a quarantine policy to the identified IAM user and publishes to an SNS topic integrated with PagerDuty for notification."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable Security Hub and configure a custom AWS Config rule that detects when the GuardDuty finding is ingested into the Config configuration timeline, then triggers an SSM Automation document to attach the deny-all policy and send an SNS notification."},{"id":"d","text":"Poll GuardDuty's ListFindings API every 60 seconds using a scheduled Lambda function, filter for the specific finding type, call IAM AttachUserPolicy to quarantine the user, and use Amazon SES to email the on-call team."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that Security Hub's 'EventBridge integration: trigger automated responses to specific findings (Lambda, SSM Automation, SNS).' GuardDuty findings are automatically sent to EventBridge as events, enabling event-driven, near-real-time response. An EventBridge rule that pattern-matches the specific GuardDuty finding type can target a Lambda function, which can both call IAM APIs to quarantine the user and publish to SNS for PagerDuty integration — satisfying the 2-minute SLA with no manual steps. Option A is incorrect because Security Hub automation rules can modify finding fields (e.g., workflow status, severity) but cannot directly invoke external APIs or AWS service APIs like IAM; they work in conjunction with EventBridge for actual remediation actions. Option C incorrectly describes how GuardDuty and Config interact; GuardDuty findings do not appear in the Config configuration timeline, and this architecture introduces unnecessary latency and complexity. Option D relies on polling with a minimum 60-second delay per cycle plus execution time, which may breach the 2-minute requirement under load, and SES email is not a real-time paging mechanism equivalent to PagerDuty integration via SNS.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_findings_cloudwatch.html","label":"GuardDuty – Automating responses with EventBridge"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/automation-rules.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Automation rules"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_finding-types-iam.html","label":"GuardDuty Finding Types – UnauthorizedAccess"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer discovers that Amazon GuardDuty has generated a finding of type UnauthorizedAccess:IAMUser/MaliciousIPCaller.Custom for a production account. The incident response runbook requires that when this specific finding type is detected, the implicated IAM user must be automatically quarantined by attaching a deny-all policy, and the on-call team must be notified via PagerDuty within 2 minutes. The solution must require NO manual steps once a finding is generated. Which architecture correctly implements this automated response pipeline?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team maintains a critical e-commerce application on EC2 instances managed by an Auto Scaling Group (ASG). During peak traffic events, newly launched instances take 8–10 minutes to complete application bootstrapping before they can serve traffic, causing performance degradation during rapid scale-out events. The team wants to minimize the time between a scale-out trigger and instances being ready to serve production traffic. Which solution BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure a Pending:Wait lifecycle hook on the ASG to delay instance registration until a custom bootstrap script signals completion via CompleteLifecycleAction."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable Predictive Scaling on the ASG so that new instances are launched in advance of forecasted demand spikes."},{"id":"c","text":"Configure a warm pool for the ASG with pre-initialized instances in the Stopped state so that scale-out events draw from already-bootstrapped instances."},{"id":"d","text":"Switch the ASG to a Step Scaling policy with a lower CloudWatch alarm threshold to trigger scale-out sooner."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Warm pools: pre-initialized instances in Stopped state for fast scale-out.' A warm pool holds instances that have already completed their bootstrapping process. When the ASG needs to scale out, it draws from the warm pool, effectively reducing the time-to-serve from 8–10 minutes to near-zero because initialization has already occurred. Option A (lifecycle hooks with Pending:Wait) actually adds latency by pausing instances in a waiting state for custom actions — it is useful for coordinating bootstrap work but does not pre-initialize instances before the scale-out event. Option B (Predictive Scaling) proactively launches instances ahead of demand using ML forecasting, which helps but still requires the full 8–10 minute bootstrap time for each new instance. Option D (Step Scaling with a lower threshold) triggers scale-out earlier but still incurs the full bootstrapping delay.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/ec2-auto-scaling-warm-pools.html","label":"AWS EC2 Auto Scaling Warm Pools"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/lifecycle-hooks.html","label":"AWS EC2 Auto Scaling Lifecycle Hooks"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team maintains a critical e-commerce application on EC2 instances managed by an Auto Scaling Group (ASG). During peak traffic events, newly launched instances take 8–10 minutes to complete application bootstrapping before they can serve traffic, causing performance degradation during rapid scale-out events. The team wants to minimize the time between a scale-out trigger and instances being ready to serve production traffic. Which solution BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company runs a multi-tier web application across two AWS Regions: us-east-1 (primary) and eu-west-1 (DR). The database tier uses an Amazon Aurora MySQL cluster. The business requires a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of under 1 minute and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of under 1 second in the event of a complete regional failure of us-east-1. The database solution must automatically promote the DR database with minimal data loss. Which Aurora configuration meets BOTH the RTO and RPO requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy an Aurora Multi-AZ cluster in us-east-1 with a cross-Region Read Replica in eu-west-1, and promote the Read Replica manually upon failure."},{"id":"b","text":"Deploy an Aurora Global Database with us-east-1 as the primary cluster and eu-west-1 as a secondary cluster, leveraging the managed planned/unplanned failover capability."},{"id":"c","text":"Use AWS Backup to take hourly automated snapshots of the Aurora cluster in us-east-1 and copy them cross-Region to eu-west-1 using a backup plan with cross-Region copy."},{"id":"d","text":"Deploy Aurora Serverless v2 in us-east-1 and configure DynamoDB Global Tables in eu-west-1 as the DR data store, with application-level failover logic."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Aurora Global Database: cross-Region replicated cluster with <1s lag for DR.' Aurora Global Database replicates writes from the primary Region to secondary Regions with typically under 1 second of lag, satisfying the sub-1-second RPO. Its managed unplanned failover (detach-and-promote) can complete in under a minute, satisfying the sub-1-minute RTO. Option A (cross-Region Read Replica with manual promotion) uses asynchronous replication and requires a manual intervention step, meaning RTO will exceed 1 minute and RPO cannot be guaranteed. Option C (AWS Backup with hourly snapshots) corresponds to a 'Backup & Restore' DR strategy, which the source describes as having 'hours of RPO, hours of RTO' — far outside the stated requirements. Option D introduces a heterogeneous data store swap (Aurora to DynamoDB) which is architecturally complex, does not address RPO/RTO guarantees, and is not a recognized Aurora HA pattern.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/AuroraUserGuide/aurora-global-database.html","label":"Amazon Aurora Global Database"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/disaster-recovery-workloads-on-aws/disaster-recovery-options-in-the-cloud.html","label":"Disaster Recovery of Workloads on AWS – DR Strategies"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company runs a multi-tier web application across two AWS Regions: us-east-1 (primary) and eu-west-1 (DR). The database tier uses an Amazon Aurora MySQL cluster. The business requires a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of under 1 minute and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) of under 1 second in the event of a complete regional failure of us-east-1. The database solution must automatically promote the DR database with minimal data loss. Which Aurora configuration meets BOTH the RTO and RPO requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a Route 53 DNS architecture for an active-passive disaster recovery configuration. The primary workload runs in us-west-2 and the passive standby (pilot light) runs in ap-southeast-1. Route 53 must automatically redirect all traffic to ap-southeast-1 only when the us-west-2 Application Load Balancer (ALB) health check fails. The engineer wants Route 53 health checks to evaluate the actual HTTP response from the ALB endpoint. Which combination of Route 53 configuration components achieves this?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create two Weighted routing records (weight 100 for primary, weight 0 for secondary) and attach a CloudWatch alarm-based health check to the primary record."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a Failover routing policy with a PRIMARY record pointing to the us-west-2 ALB and a SECONDARY record pointing to the ap-southeast-1 ALB; associate an endpoint health check evaluating an HTTP path on the us-west-2 ALB with the PRIMARY record."},{"id":"c","text":"Create a Latency routing policy with records in both Regions and attach health checks to both records; Route 53 will stop routing to a Region if its health check fails."},{"id":"d","text":"Create a Multivalue Answer routing policy with two records and associate endpoint health checks with both; Route 53 will only return the healthy record."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'DNS Failover for active-passive DR; latency for active-active' and 'Failover (with health checks)' under Route 53 routing policies. The Failover routing policy is specifically designed for active-passive DR: a PRIMARY record is served under normal conditions, and Route 53 automatically switches to the SECONDARY record when the health check associated with the PRIMARY record fails. The source also identifies 'endpoint' as a health check type, which evaluates an actual HTTP/HTTPS response from the specified endpoint — satisfying the requirement to check the ALB's HTTP response. Option A (Weighted routing) does not provide automatic failover; weight-0 records are never served regardless of health, and the engineer would need to manually adjust weights. Option C (Latency routing) is described in the source as the pattern for active-active, not active-passive DR; both endpoints would receive traffic when healthy, violating the passive standby requirement. Option D (Multivalue Answer) is intended for simple load spreading across multiple healthy endpoints, not for a defined primary/secondary failover topology.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/dns-failover-configuring.html","label":"Amazon Route 53 – Configuring DNS Failover"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/dns-failover.html","label":"Amazon Route 53 Health Checks and DNS Failover"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/routing-policy.html","label":"Amazon Route 53 Routing Policy Types"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a Route 53 DNS architecture for an active-passive disaster recovery configuration. The primary workload runs in us-west-2 and the passive standby (pilot light) runs in ap-southeast-1. Route 53 must automatically redirect all traffic to ap-southeast-1 only when the us-west-2 Application Load Balancer (ALB) health check fails. The engineer wants Route 53 health checks to evaluate the actual HTTP response from the ALB endpoint. Which combination of Route 53 configuration components achieves this?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is building a high-throughput microservices platform on AWS. Each service emits dozens of custom business metrics per request. The team notices that direct use of the PutMetricData API is causing throttling errors and increasing CloudWatch costs. Which approach BEST resolves both the throttling and cost concerns while still making those metrics queryable in CloudWatch?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Batch all PutMetricData calls to the maximum of 1,000 data points per API call and implement exponential back-off to handle any remaining throttling."},{"id":"b","text":"Switch to Embedded Metric Format (EMF) by writing structured JSON log lines to CloudWatch Logs, letting CloudWatch automatically extract the metrics without additional API calls."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable high-resolution custom metrics at 1-second granularity so that fewer, larger batches are required over the same time window."},{"id":"d","text":"Deploy an Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose subscription filter on each log group to forward raw logs to S3, then use Amazon Athena to query the metrics."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Embedded Metric Format (EMF): structured JSON log line; CloudWatch automatically extracts metrics. Reduces API calls and cost.' EMF embeds metric values inside log events sent to CloudWatch Logs, so no separate PutMetricData calls are needed — eliminating throttling entirely and reducing cost because you are billed for log ingestion rather than individual metric API calls. Option A reduces but does not eliminate PutMetricData calls or cost, and still requires back-off logic. Option C changes metric resolution but has no impact on the number of API calls or throttling risk. Option D routes data to S3/Athena, which removes the ability to use native CloudWatch alarms and dashboards for those metrics.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch_Embedded_Metric_Format_Specification.html","label":"CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format – Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/APIReference/API_PutMetricData.html","label":"PutMetricData API Reference"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is building a high-throughput microservices platform on AWS. Each service emits dozens of custom business metrics per request. The team notices that direct use of the PutMetricData API is causing throttling errors and increasing CloudWatch costs. Which approach BEST resolves both the throttling and cost concerns while still making those metrics queryable in CloudWatch?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company runs a multi-account AWS environment managed through AWS Organizations. The security team wants a single pane of glass to query CloudTrail management-event history across all member accounts using standard SQL. On-call engineers must be able to run ad-hoc queries within minutes of an incident without first setting up per-account trails or an external SIEM. Which CloudTrail feature satisfies these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an organization trail that delivers logs from all accounts to a central S3 bucket, then configure Amazon Athena with AWS Glue crawlers to query the raw JSON files."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable CloudTrail Insights events on the organization trail and stream them to CloudWatch Logs, then use CloudWatch Logs Insights with the SQL query mode to search across accounts."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable CloudTrail Lake with an organization-wide event data store so that management events from all member accounts are ingested automatically and queryable via SQL without managing S3, Glue, or Athena infrastructure."},{"id":"d","text":"Deploy a subscription filter on each account's CloudTrail log group to forward events to a central Kinesis Data Firehose, then load them into Amazon OpenSearch for SQL-like querying."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'CloudTrail Lake: managed SQL-queryable event data store.' CloudTrail Lake natively supports an organization event data store that automatically ingests management events from every member account in an AWS Organization, and provides a built-in SQL query interface — no S3 buckets, Glue crawlers, Athena table definitions, or third-party tooling are required. Option A uses Athena, which is a valid pattern but requires Glue crawler setup and schema maintenance, adding operational overhead. Option B conflates CloudTrail Insights (anomaly detection on API call volumes) with ad-hoc SQL queries — Insights events flag anomalies but are not designed for arbitrary event history queries. Option D requires deploying and managing Kinesis Data Firehose pipelines and an OpenSearch cluster per account, which is the highest operational overhead of all options.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/awscloudtrail/latest/userguide/cloudtrail-lake.html","label":"AWS CloudTrail Lake – User Guide"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/awscloudtrail/latest/userguide/creating-trail-organization.html","label":"Create an Organization Trail"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company runs a multi-account AWS environment managed through AWS Organizations. The security team wants a single pane of glass to query CloudTrail management-event history across all member accounts using standard SQL. On-call engineers must be able to run ad-hoc queries within minutes of an incident without first setting up per-account trails or an external SIEM. Which CloudTrail feature satisfies these requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing an alerting strategy for a production payment service. The service has five existing CloudWatch alarms: CPU utilization, error rate, latency P99, queue depth, and database connection count. During off-hours maintenance windows, all five alarms frequently enter the ALARM state simultaneously, flooding the on-call engineer's phone with redundant SNS notifications. The team wants to suppress individual alarm notifications during a declared maintenance window while still being paged if a genuinely unexpected multi-dimensional failure occurs outside of maintenance hours. Which solution BEST meets these requirements with the fewest architectural changes?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create a CloudWatch composite alarm that uses AND logic across all five child alarms. During maintenance windows, disable the SNS action on each individual child alarm. The composite alarm will only fire an SNS notification when all five alarms are in ALARM simultaneously outside of maintenance windows."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a CloudWatch composite alarm with OR logic over all five child alarms and attach the SNS action only to the composite alarm. Suppress the composite alarm's SNS action during maintenance windows by updating the alarm action via the AWS CLI before and after each window."},{"id":"c","text":"Replace all five individual alarms with a single anomaly-detection alarm trained on historical baselines. Anomaly detection will automatically learn maintenance-window patterns and suppress notifications without any manual intervention."},{"id":"d","text":"Configure an Amazon EventBridge rule that matches CloudWatch alarm state-change events and routes them to a Lambda function. The Lambda function checks a DynamoDB flag for 'maintenance mode' and conditionally publishes to SNS, replicating composite-alarm logic in code."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Composite alarms: AND/OR/NOT logic over child alarms; reduces alert fatigue.' A composite alarm with OR logic fires whenever any single child alarm enters ALARM — preserving sensitivity to any individual failure outside maintenance windows. Attaching the SNS action exclusively to the composite alarm means engineers receive one notification per incident rather than five. During maintenance windows, a single CLI command (or automation) disables the composite alarm's action, suppressing notifications without touching the five child alarms or altering their thresholds. Option A uses AND logic, which would require all five alarms to be in ALARM at the same time before notifying — this is overly restrictive and would miss single-dimension failures outside maintenance windows. Option C relies on anomaly detection to learn maintenance patterns, but anomaly detection is not guaranteed to suppress all maintenance-induced spikes, and it replaces nuanced threshold alarms with a single model, reducing operational visibility. Option D technically works but introduces unnecessary Lambda, EventBridge, and DynamoDB infrastructure when composite alarms solve the problem natively.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/Create_Composite_Alarm.html","label":"CloudWatch Composite Alarms – User Guide"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/AlarmThatSendsEmail.html","label":"CloudWatch Alarms – Actions and States"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing an alerting strategy for a production payment service. The service has five existing CloudWatch alarms: CPU utilization, error rate, latency P99, queue depth, and database connection count. During off-hours maintenance windows, all five alarms frequently enter the ALARM state simultaneously, flooding the on-call engineer's phone with redundant SNS notifications. The team wants to suppress individual alarm notifications during a declared maintenance window while still being paged if a genuinely unexpected multi-dimensional failure occurs outside of maintenance hours. Which solution BEST meets these requirements with the fewest architectural changes?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is configuring AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager for a critical production service. They need on-call engineers to be automatically paged when an incident is created, and if the primary contact does not acknowledge within 10 minutes, a secondary contact must be engaged automatically. Which Incident Manager components must be configured together to satisfy this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A response plan that references a contact with a single email channel, and a CloudWatch alarm action pointing to that response plan."},{"id":"b","text":"A contact record with email, SMS, or voice channels defined, an escalation plan with a primary stage (contact) and a secondary stage triggered after a 10-minute acknowledgment timeout, and a response plan that references that escalation plan as the engagement target."},{"id":"c","text":"An SNS topic subscribed to the on-call engineer's email, an EventBridge rule that publishes to the SNS topic, and a response plan that references the SNS topic ARN directly."},{"id":"d","text":"An SSM Automation runbook with a manual approval gate set to 10 minutes, a response plan that runs that runbook at incident creation, and a contact record for the secondary approver."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Contacts and escalation plans: schedule on-call rotations with primary, secondary contacts; channels = email, SMS, voice' and 'Engagement: notify on-call responders; auto-escalate if not acknowledged within configurable timeouts.' The correct design requires (1) a Contact with at least one channel (email/SMS/voice), (2) an Escalation Plan that lists the primary contact in stage 1 and the secondary contact in stage 2 with a 10-minute acknowledgment timeout between them, and (3) a Response Plan whose engagement section references that escalation plan. Option A is wrong because a single contact with no escalation plan cannot auto-escalate. Option C is wrong because SNS/EventBridge do not provide acknowledgment tracking or auto-escalation within Incident Manager. Option D confuses SSM Automation approval gates (used for runbook remediation gating) with contact engagement acknowledgment timeouts — these are separate constructs.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/contacts.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Contacts and escalation plans"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/response-plans.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Response plans"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is configuring AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager for a critical production service. They need on-call engineers to be automatically paged when an incident is created, and if the primary contact does not acknowledge within 10 minutes, a secondary contact must be engaged automatically. Which Incident Manager components must be configured together to satisfy this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security team receives Amazon GuardDuty findings and wants to automate the following response for any HIGH severity finding: (1) immediately send a notification to the on-call security channel in Slack, and (2) automatically swap the compromised EC2 instance's security group to an isolated security group. The solution must use native AWS services with the least operational overhead. Which architecture correctly implements both actions?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an EventBridge rule matching GuardDuty HIGH severity findings with two targets: an SNS topic (connected to AWS Chatbot for Slack delivery) and an SSM Automation document that performs the security-group swap on the affected instance."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a CloudWatch Logs metric filter on GuardDuty logs with a CloudWatch Alarm; configure the alarm to notify an SNS topic for Slack and invoke a Lambda function for the security-group swap."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable GuardDuty threat intel feeds and configure a GuardDuty suppression rule to route HIGH findings directly to AWS Chatbot; use a separate CloudTrail rule to trigger the security-group swap."},{"id":"d","text":"Create an EventBridge rule matching GuardDuty HIGH severity findings with a single target pointing to an SQS FIFO queue; configure a Lambda function to poll the queue, call Slack's API directly, and swap the security group."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly documents this pattern: 'GuardDuty findings integrate with EventBridge: route HIGH severity finding -> SNS to on-call + Lambda to isolate compromised instance via security-group swap.' Option A correctly implements both legs of this pattern using EventBridge (which natively receives GuardDuty findings on its default event bus) with two targets — an SNS topic integrated with AWS Chatbot for Slack, and an SSM Automation runbook for the remediation — matching the documented automated remediation flow. Option B introduces unnecessary complexity via CloudWatch Logs metric filters, which add latency and are less direct than EventBridge for GuardDuty events. Option C misuses GuardDuty suppression rules (which suppress findings from appearing, not route them) and CloudTrail rules do not exist as described. Option D uses a single SQS target requiring custom Lambda code to call Slack's API, which increases operational overhead compared to the native AWS Chatbot integration.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_findings_cloudwatch.html","label":"Amazon GuardDuty – Automating responses to findings with EventBridge"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/chatbot/latest/adminguide/setting-up-sns.html","label":"AWS Chatbot – Setting up AWS Chatbot with Amazon SNS"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/automation-use-cases.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Automation – Security group remediation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security team receives Amazon GuardDuty findings and wants to automate the following response for any HIGH severity finding: (1) immediately send a notification to the on-call security channel in Slack, and (2) automatically swap the compromised EC2 instance's security group to an isolated security group. The solution must use native AWS services with the least operational overhead. Which architecture correctly implements both actions?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a post-incident review process using AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager. After each incident is resolved, the team needs a structured artifact that captures: the timeline of AWS service events, which contacts were engaged and when, which runbook steps executed, and answers to custom retrospective questions. The engineer also wants to replay a specific window of EventBridge events that occurred during the incident to re-examine the sequence of automated actions. Which combination of features satisfies BOTH requirements with the least custom development?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use Incident Manager's post-incident analysis feature (which captures timeline, contact engagements, runbook execution, and supports custom questions) for the structured artifact; use EventBridge event archive and replay to re-deliver the historical events from the incident window to the relevant EventBridge rule for re-examination."},{"id":"b","text":"Export CloudWatch Logs Insights query results to S3 as the structured artifact; write a Lambda function that reads archived CloudTrail events and re-publishes them to the default EventBridge bus for replay."},{"id":"c","text":"Use Incident Manager's post-incident analysis for the structured artifact; use EventBridge Pipes to re-route live events from a new source to the target for historical comparison."},{"id":"d","text":"Use AWS Config advanced queries to generate the incident timeline artifact; use EventBridge Schema Registry to retrieve and replay historical event schemas from the incident window."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material directly covers both capabilities. For the structured artifact: 'Post-incident analysis: structured timeline of events, contact engagements, and runbook execution; supports custom questions.' This native Incident Manager feature satisfies all four requirements (timeline, contact engagement log, runbook execution record, and custom retrospective questions) without any custom development. For event replay: 'Event archive + replay: store events and re-deliver historical events to a rule.' This EventBridge feature allows the engineer to define an archive on a specific event bus and replay a time-bounded window of stored events back through a rule, enabling re-examination of the automated action sequence. Option B requires custom Lambda development and does not use Incident Manager's native analysis feature. Option C misuses EventBridge Pipes, which is a point-to-point connector for live streaming data — not a replay mechanism for historical events. Option D misuses AWS Config (infrastructure compliance, not incident timelines) and the Schema Registry (event schema discovery and code generation, not event replay).$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/analysis.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Post-incident analysis"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/eventbridge/latest/userguide/eb-archive.html","label":"Amazon EventBridge – Archiving and replaying events"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P3'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a post-incident review process using AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager. After each incident is resolved, the team needs a structured artifact that captures: the timeline of AWS service events, which contacts were engaged and when, which runbook steps executed, and answers to custom retrospective questions. The engineer also wants to replay a specific window of EventBridge events that occurred during the incident to re-examine the sequence of automated actions. Which combination of features satisfies BOTH requirements with the least custom development?$patch$);

-- DOP-C02-P4: 15 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a multi-region, multi-account CloudFormation stack for a compliance-sensitive workload. They need to ensure that a critical Amazon RDS DB instance cannot be accidentally replaced or deleted during any future stack update operations. Which CloudFormation feature should they apply directly to the RDS resource in the template to enforce this protection?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable stack termination protection on the CloudFormation stack."},{"id":"b","text":"Apply a Stack Policy that denies Update:Replace and Update:Delete actions on the logical resource ID of the RDS DB instance."},{"id":"c","text":"Set the DeletionPolicy attribute to Retain on the RDS resource and rely on CloudFormation's default update behavior."},{"id":"d","text":"Use a Change Set with a manual approval gate before every stack update."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the source material, Stack Policies are specifically designed to 'protect specific logical resources from updates (e.g., RDS DBInstance).' A Stack Policy is a JSON document that defines which update actions are allowed or denied on specific resources within a stack, including Update:Replace and Update:Delete, giving fine-grained per-resource protection during stack updates. Option A (termination protection) prevents the entire stack from being deleted but does not protect individual resources from update-driven replacement. Option C (DeletionPolicy: Retain) only controls what happens to the physical resource when the stack is deleted, not what happens during an update that might replace the resource. Option D (Change Sets) provides a preview mechanism but does not enforce protection — a change set can still be executed and replace the RDS instance.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/protect-stack-resources.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation Stack Policies"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-attribute-deletionpolicy.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation DeletionPolicy Attribute"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a multi-region, multi-account CloudFormation stack for a compliance-sensitive workload. They need to ensure that a critical Amazon RDS DB instance cannot be accidentally replaced or deleted during any future stack update operations. Which CloudFormation feature should they apply directly to the RDS resource in the template to enforce this protection?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company wants to retrieve the latest approved AMI ID from AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store dynamically at CloudFormation stack deployment time without hardcoding values in the template or requiring manual parameter input from operators. The AMI ID is stored at the SSM path /myorg/ami/golden-linux. Which approach in the CloudFormation template achieves this requirement with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Declare a CloudFormation Parameter of type String with a Default value of the AMI ID, and instruct operators to update the default before each deployment."},{"id":"b","text":"Use a CloudFormation custom resource backed by a Lambda function that calls the SSM GetParameter API and returns the AMI ID as a resource attribute."},{"id":"c","text":"Declare a CloudFormation Parameter with Type AWS::SSM::Parameter::Value<AWS::EC2::Image::Id> and set the Default to /myorg/ami/golden-linux so CloudFormation resolves the value from Parameter Store at deploy time."},{"id":"d","text":"Use the dynamic reference syntax {{resolve:secretsmanager:/myorg/ami/golden-linux:SecretString:amiId}} inline in the EC2 resource's ImageId property."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states that CloudFormation Parameters support 'AWS::SSM::Parameter::Value for dynamic Parameter Store lookups.' By setting the Parameter Type to AWS::SSM::Parameter::Value<AWS::EC2::Image::Id> and the Default to the SSM path /myorg/ami/golden-linux, CloudFormation automatically resolves the latest value from Parameter Store at deployment time without any operator input or additional resources. Option A requires manual intervention, adding operational overhead. Option B works but involves authoring and maintaining a Lambda-backed custom resource — unnecessary complexity when a native type exists. Option D uses the wrong dynamic reference syntax: {{resolve:secretsmanager:...}} is for AWS Secrets Manager, not Parameter Store; the correct SSM syntax would be {{resolve:ssm:/path:version}}, and while that syntax is valid inline, the AWS::SSM::Parameter::Value Parameter Type is the preferred, idiomatic approach for AMI IDs specifically because it also enables CloudFormation to perform EC2 Image ID validation.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/parameters-section-structure.html#aws-specific-parameter-types","label":"CloudFormation Parameters – AWS-Specific Parameter Types"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/dynamic-references.html","label":"Using Dynamic References in CloudFormation Templates"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company wants to retrieve the latest approved AMI ID from AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store dynamically at CloudFormation stack deployment time without hardcoding values in the template or requiring manual parameter input from operators. The AMI ID is stored at the SSM path /myorg/ami/golden-linux. Which approach in the CloudFormation template achieves this requirement with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is building an AWS CDK application in TypeScript to provision infrastructure. During a peer review, a colleague recommends using L2 constructs instead of L1 constructs wherever possible. Which statement BEST explains the primary advantage of CDK L2 constructs over L1 constructs for this use case?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"L1 constructs synthesize to AWS SAM templates, while L2 constructs synthesize directly to CloudFormation templates, making L2 deployments faster."},{"id":"b","text":"L2 constructs provide high-level, opinionated abstractions with secure defaults and helper methods, reducing the amount of boilerplate configuration required compared to L1 constructs, which map 1:1 to raw CloudFormation resources."},{"id":"c","text":"L2 constructs bypass CloudFormation entirely and provision resources through direct API calls, improving deployment speed and reducing stack size."},{"id":"d","text":"L1 constructs require a separate CDK bootstrapping step for each AWS account, whereas L2 constructs work without bootstrapping."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material defines CDK construct levels as: 'L1 (CfnXxx, 1:1 to CloudFormation), L2 (high-level resource), L3 (patterns/Solution constructs).' L1 constructs (prefixed with Cfn) are direct, low-level representations of CloudFormation resource types — they require you to specify every property explicitly, just as you would in a raw CloudFormation template. L2 constructs wrap those L1 constructs with opinionated defaults, convenience methods (e.g., bucket.grantRead()), and security best practices baked in, dramatically reducing boilerplate. Option A is false — both L1 and L2 constructs synthesize to standard CloudFormation templates (via 'cdk synth'). Option C is false — CDK always synthesizes to CloudFormation; it does not bypass it. Option D is false — CDK bootstrapping (cdk bootstrap) is an account/region-level prerequisite unrelated to construct level choice.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cdk/v2/guide/constructs.html","label":"AWS CDK Constructs – Construct Library Levels"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/cdk/v2/guide/getting_started.html","label":"AWS CDK v2 Developer Guide – Getting Started"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is building an AWS CDK application in TypeScript to provision infrastructure. During a peer review, a colleague recommends using L2 constructs instead of L1 constructs wherever possible. Which statement BEST explains the primary advantage of CDK L2 constructs over L1 constructs for this use case?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team manages a multi-account AWS environment spanning six Regions. They need a single-pane-of-glass view of security findings from GuardDuty, Amazon Inspector, and AWS Config across all accounts and Regions. The security architect wants findings normalized into a common schema so that downstream automation can process them uniformly. Which combination of actions satisfies BOTH the aggregation and normalization requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable AWS Security Hub in each account and Region, designate a home Region for cross-Region aggregation, and rely on the AWS Security Finding Format (ASFF) as the normalized schema across all integrated services."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a custom Lambda function that polls GuardDuty, Inspector, and AWS Config APIs in each Region and writes normalized JSON records to a central S3 bucket in the management account."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable AWS Config Aggregator in the management account to collect configuration and compliance data, and use Amazon EventBridge rules in each Region to forward GuardDuty and Inspector findings to a central SNS topic."},{"id":"d","text":"Deploy an AWS-managed Splunk integration in each account to ingest findings, then use Splunk's common information model (CIM) for normalization and a single Splunk dashboard for aggregation."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that AWS Security Hub acts as a 'central aggregator: consolidates findings from GuardDuty, Inspector, Macie, AWS Config, IAM Access Analyzer, Firewall Manager, and third-party partner products' and 'uses AWS Security Finding Format (ASFF) as the normalized finding schema.' It further specifies that 'cross-Region aggregation' is achieved by designating a home Region, with 'linked Regions feed[ing] it for global visibility.' Option A directly maps to both requirements using built-in AWS capabilities, requiring no custom code. Option B introduces custom Lambda polling, which adds significant operational overhead and re-implements functionality Security Hub already provides natively. Option C addresses Config data via the Aggregator but does not normalize GuardDuty and Inspector findings into a common schema — those would arrive as disparate event formats via SNS. Option D relies on a third-party tool and does not use the native AWS normalization schema (ASFF), introducing unnecessary vendor dependency and operational complexity.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/securityhub-findings.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Findings and ASFF"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/finding-aggregation.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Cross-Region Aggregation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team manages a multi-account AWS environment spanning six Regions. They need a single-pane-of-glass view of security findings from GuardDuty, Amazon Inspector, and AWS Config across all accounts and Regions. The security architect wants findings normalized into a common schema so that downstream automation can process them uniformly. Which combination of actions satisfies BOTH the aggregation and normalization requirements with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company must demonstrate continuous compliance with the PCI DSS standard across all AWS accounts in its AWS Organization. The security team wants noncompliant resources to be automatically remediated without manual intervention, and the same set of compliance rules must be consistently deployed to every current and future member account. Which approach BEST meets these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enroll each account in AWS Security Hub and enable the PCI DSS security standard; use Security Hub automation rules to set finding severity and notify via SNS when a resource is noncompliant."},{"id":"b","text":"Author an AWS Config Conformance Pack that bundles PCI-aligned Config rules with AWS Systems Manager Automation-based remediation actions, then deploy the Conformance Pack organization-wide through AWS Organizations."},{"id":"c","text":"Write individual AWS Config managed rules for each PCI requirement in the management account, enable AWS Config Aggregator to view results, and use manual ticketing to track and resolve noncompliant resources."},{"id":"d","text":"Use Amazon GuardDuty with a custom threat intelligence feed tailored to PCI DSS requirements, and configure EventBridge to invoke a Lambda function that terminates noncompliant EC2 instances."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly describes AWS Config Conformance Packs as a 'bundle of Config rules + remediation actions for a compliance framework; deploy across accounts via Organizations.' The auto-remediation capability is confirmed: 'trigger SSM Automation document when a rule is non-compliant.' Together, these capabilities satisfy all three stated requirements — PCI DSS alignment, automatic remediation, and consistent org-wide deployment including future accounts. Option A (Security Hub with automation rules) can suppress or modify finding metadata but does not perform resource-level remediation; the source states automation rules 'auto-modify or suppress findings,' not remediate underlying infrastructure. Option C fails the automatic remediation requirement by relying on manual ticketing, and deploying rules only in the management account does not enforce them in member accounts. Option D conflates threat detection (GuardDuty's purpose) with compliance enforcement; GuardDuty is not a compliance framework tool and does not evaluate resource configurations against PCI DSS controls.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/conformance-packs.html","label":"AWS Config Conformance Packs"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/remediation.html","label":"AWS Config – Automatic Remediation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/conformance-pack-organization-apis.html","label":"Deploying Conformance Packs Across an Organization"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company must demonstrate continuous compliance with the PCI DSS standard across all AWS accounts in its AWS Organization. The security team wants noncompliant resources to be automatically remediated without manual intervention, and the same set of compliance rules must be consistently deployed to every current and future member account. Which approach BEST meets these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An application team stores customer records in multiple S3 buckets. A recent audit found that some buckets may contain personally identifiable information (PII) that was not catalogued. Separately, a security operations team receives an AWS Security Hub finding indicating that an IAM role in the same account has cross-account access that violates the principle of least privilege. The DevOps engineer wants to address BOTH issues using the most purpose-built AWS services available. Which pairing of services is MOST appropriate?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use Amazon GuardDuty to scan S3 buckets for PII, and use AWS Security Hub automation rules to automatically revoke the IAM role's cross-account trust policy."},{"id":"b","text":"Use Amazon Macie to discover and classify sensitive data (including PII) in S3 buckets, and use IAM Access Analyzer to identify and report the IAM role's external cross-account access."},{"id":"c","text":"Use Amazon Inspector to scan S3 bucket contents for PII patterns, and use Amazon GuardDuty to detect unauthorized cross-account IAM activity and generate an AccountCompromise finding."},{"id":"d","text":"Use AWS Config with the s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited managed rule to detect PII exposure in S3, and use AWS Security Hub with the CIS AWS Foundations Benchmark standard to flag the overly permissive IAM role."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material directly identifies the purpose-built service for each problem. For PII discovery in S3, the source states: 'Amazon Macie: discovers sensitive data (PII, financial) in S3; uses ML and managed data identifiers (regex patterns).' For cross-account access analysis, the source states: 'IAM Access Analyzer: validates resource-based policies; reports external/unused access.' Option B precisely pairs the correct purpose-built service to each problem. Option A is incorrect because GuardDuty performs threat detection from logs (VPC Flow Logs, CloudTrail, etc.) and does not scan S3 object contents for PII; Security Hub automation rules modify finding metadata, they do not directly revoke IAM trust policies. Option C is incorrect because Amazon Inspector performs CVE-based vulnerability scanning of EC2 instances, Lambda functions, and container images — it does not scan S3 bucket contents for sensitive data patterns. Option D is incorrect because the s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited Config rule detects public access settings, not PII content within objects; CIS Benchmark checks in Security Hub flag broad configuration issues but are not designed to specifically identify a single IAM role's cross-account trust relationship with the precision IAM Access Analyzer provides.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/macie/latest/user/findings-types.html","label":"Amazon Macie – Discovering Sensitive Data"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/what-is-access-analyzer.html","label":"IAM Access Analyzer – External Access Findings"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/macie/latest/user/managed-data-identifiers.html","label":"Amazon Macie – Managed Data Identifiers"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An application team stores customer records in multiple S3 buckets. A recent audit found that some buckets may contain personally identifiable information (PII) that was not catalogued. Separately, a security operations team receives an AWS Security Hub finding indicating that an IAM role in the same account has cross-account access that violates the principle of least privilege. The DevOps engineer wants to address BOTH issues using the most purpose-built AWS services available. Which pairing of services is MOST appropriate?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a disaster recovery architecture for a critical e-commerce platform on AWS. The business requires a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of under 5 minutes and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) approaching zero. The platform uses RDS Aurora for its primary database. Which combination of AWS services and configurations BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy an Aurora Global Database with a secondary Region cluster, configure Route 53 Failover routing with health checks pointing to each Region's ALB endpoint, and use AWS Backup with cross-Region copy to meet RPO targets."},{"id":"b","text":"Deploy an RDS Multi-AZ instance in the primary Region, enable automated snapshots with a 5-minute frequency, and use Route 53 Weighted routing to shift traffic to a warm standby in a secondary Region upon failure."},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy RDS Read Replicas in the secondary Region, promote the replica manually on failure, and use Route 53 Simple routing to direct traffic to the promoted instance."},{"id":"d","text":"Use DynamoDB Global Tables as the primary data store with multi-Region active-active replication, and configure Route 53 Latency routing to serve traffic from the nearest Region at all times."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that Aurora Global Database provides cross-Region replicated clusters with less than 1 second replication lag for DR, which satisfies near-zero RPO. When combined with Route 53 Failover routing backed by health checks, automatic DNS cutover to the secondary Region can occur within seconds to minutes, satisfying the sub-5-minute RTO. AWS Backup with cross-Region copy adds a durable recovery layer. Option B is incorrect because RDS Multi-AZ only covers within a single Region and automated snapshots have an RPO measured in hours (matching the 'Backup & Restore' strategy, not the required near-zero RPO). Option C is incorrect because RDS Read Replica promotion is a manual process with no guaranteed RTO and async replication introduces data loss risk. Option D is incorrect because DynamoDB Global Tables are only suitable if the application uses DynamoDB as its data store — the question specifies Aurora — and Latency routing does not implement failover logic.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/AuroraUserGuide/aurora-global-database.html","label":"Amazon Aurora Global Database overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/routing-policy-failover.html","label":"Route 53 Failover routing policy"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/disaster-recovery-workloads-on-aws/disaster-recovery-options-in-the-cloud.html","label":"Disaster Recovery of Workloads on AWS (whitepaper)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a disaster recovery architecture for a critical e-commerce platform on AWS. The business requires a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of under 5 minutes and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) approaching zero. The platform uses RDS Aurora for its primary database. Which combination of AWS services and configurations BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An Auto Scaling group (ASG) uses a Lifecycle Hook in the Terminating:Wait state to drain application-level state from instances before they are terminated. A DevOps engineer notices that some instances are being terminated before the drain process completes, causing data loss. The current heartbeat timeout is set to 60 seconds, but the drain process occasionally takes up to 4 minutes. Which action will MOST reliably prevent premature termination while keeping the solution operationally simple?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Increase the Lifecycle Hook heartbeat timeout to at least 300 seconds so the default wait window is long enough to accommodate the maximum drain duration, and ensure the drain script calls CompleteLifecycleAction with CONTINUE as soon as it finishes."},{"id":"b","text":"Replace the Lifecycle Hook with an ALB connection draining (deregistration delay) setting of 300 seconds so the load balancer holds in-flight requests until the instance is fully drained before termination begins."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable Capacity Rebalancing on the ASG so that at-risk instances are proactively replaced before the drain process can be interrupted."},{"id":"d","text":"Switch to a Warm Pool configuration so instances enter a Stopped state prior to termination, giving the drain process additional time to complete outside the ASG lifecycle."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states that Lifecycle Hooks place instances in a Pending:Wait or Terminating:Wait state and that the operator must emit CompleteLifecycleAction to proceed. The heartbeat timeout defines the maximum wait window. Since the drain process takes up to 4 minutes (240 seconds) and the current timeout is only 60 seconds, instances exit the wait state before the drain completes. Increasing the timeout to at least 300 seconds and signaling CompleteLifecycleAction immediately upon completion is the correct and operationally simple fix. Option B is incorrect because ALB deregistration delay only handles in-flight HTTP connections at the load balancer layer; it does not pause the EC2 Auto Scaling termination lifecycle for application-level state draining, and it does not interact with the ASG Lifecycle Hook mechanism. Option C is incorrect because Capacity Rebalancing is designed to proactively replace at-risk Spot instances before AWS reclaims them — it does not extend drain time or affect lifecycle hook timeouts. Option D is incorrect because Warm Pools are used to hold pre-initialized instances for fast scale-out, not to provide additional time during scale-in termination sequences.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/lifecycle-hooks.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling lifecycle hooks"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/APIReference/API_CompleteLifecycleAction.html","label":"CompleteLifecycleAction API reference"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/load-balancer-target-groups.html#deregistration-delay","label":"Connection draining (deregistration delay) for ELB"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An Auto Scaling group (ASG) uses a Lifecycle Hook in the Terminating:Wait state to drain application-level state from instances before they are terminated. A DevOps engineer notices that some instances are being terminated before the drain process completes, causing data loss. The current heartbeat timeout is set to 60 seconds, but the drain process occasionally takes up to 4 minutes. Which action will MOST reliably prevent premature termination while keeping the solution operationally simple?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A financial services company stores critical backup data in Amazon S3 and uses AWS Backup to protect RDS, EFS, and DynamoDB workloads. A new compliance requirement mandates that backup data must be immutable and protected from deletion by any user, including administrators, for a minimum of 7 years. Additionally, a regulatory audit requires proof that backup copies exist in a geographically separate AWS Region. Which AWS Backup configuration satisfies BOTH requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable AWS Backup Vault Lock in Compliance mode on the primary backup vault with a minimum retention period of 7 years (2,555 days), and configure the backup plan to include a cross-Region copy rule targeting the secondary Region vault, also protected by Vault Lock."},{"id":"b","text":"Apply an S3 Object Lock policy with Governance mode to the S3 bucket used by AWS Backup, and enable S3 Cross-Region Replication (CRR) with Replication Time Control (RTC) to ensure copies reach the secondary Region within 15 minutes."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable AWS Backup Vault Lock in Governance mode on the primary vault with a 7-year retention tag, and use AWS DataSync to asynchronously transfer backup data to a vault in the secondary Region nightly."},{"id":"d","text":"Configure an AWS Backup plan with a 7-year lifecycle rule on the primary vault and enable AWS Backup cross-account copy to a separate AWS account in the same Region to provide administrative isolation."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that AWS Backup supports vault locks with WORM (Write Once Read Many) protection and cross-account/cross-Region copy. Vault Lock in Compliance mode enforces immutability that cannot be overridden even by the root account or AWS Support, satisfying the requirement that no user — including administrators — can delete the backups. Setting the minimum retention period to 2,555 days (7 years) enforces the regulatory hold. Adding a cross-Region copy rule in the backup plan ensures that a geographically separate copy exists, satisfying the second audit requirement. Option B is incorrect because AWS Backup vaults do not directly surface S3 Object Lock controls to end users; Object Lock applies to S3 buckets used directly, not to the managed vault abstraction. Additionally, Governance mode (not Compliance mode) still allows privileged users to override the lock, which violates the 'no administrator deletion' requirement. Option C is incorrect for the same Governance-mode reason — Governance mode can be overridden by users with special IAM permissions — and DataSync is not the appropriate tool for replicating AWS Backup recovery points. Option D is incorrect because cross-account copy to the same Region does not provide geographic separation as required by the audit.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/aws-backup/latest/devguide/vault-lock.html","label":"AWS Backup Vault Lock documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/aws-backup/latest/devguide/cross-region-backup.html","label":"AWS Backup cross-Region and cross-account backup copy"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/aws-backup/latest/devguide/whatisbackup.html","label":"AWS Backup supported services and features"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A financial services company stores critical backup data in Amazon S3 and uses AWS Backup to protect RDS, EFS, and DynamoDB workloads. A new compliance requirement mandates that backup data must be immutable and protected from deletion by any user, including administrators, for a minimum of 7 years. Additionally, a regulatory audit requires proof that backup copies exist in a geographically separate AWS Region. Which AWS Backup configuration satisfies BOTH requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is publishing high-resolution custom metrics to Amazon CloudWatch using the PutMetricData API. After 4 hours, they notice that the 1-second resolution data points are no longer available in CloudWatch, even though data published at 1-minute resolution from the same period is still visible. What is the most likely explanation for this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"High-resolution metrics require a separate CloudWatch namespace and cannot coexist with standard-resolution metrics."},{"id":"b","text":"CloudWatch automatically rolls up 1-second resolution data points after 3 hours, making them unavailable at that granularity."},{"id":"c","text":"The IAM role used by PutMetricData lacked the cloudwatch:GetMetricStatistics permission, causing data to be silently dropped after 3 hours."},{"id":"d","text":"High-resolution custom metrics are only retained if the metric has at least one CloudWatch Alarm attached to it."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the CloudWatch documentation, high-resolution (1-second) custom metric data points are retained for only 3 hours. After that period, CloudWatch aggregates them into 60-second resolution data points, which are then retained for 15 days. This tiered retention policy — 1s for 3h, 60s for 15d, 5min for 63d, 1hr for 15 months — means the sub-minute granularity is inherently time-limited. Option A is incorrect because high-resolution and standard-resolution metrics can share the same namespace. Option C is incorrect because an IAM permission error would prevent data from being written at all, not selectively expire it. Option D is incorrect because CloudWatch retention is not conditional on alarm attachment.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/publishingMetrics.html#high-resolution-metrics","label":"Amazon CloudWatch – High-Resolution Metrics and Retention Periods"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is publishing high-resolution custom metrics to Amazon CloudWatch using the PutMetricData API. After 4 hours, they notice that the 1-second resolution data points are no longer available in CloudWatch, even though data published at 1-minute resolution from the same period is still visible. What is the most likely explanation for this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company runs a microservices application across dozens of AWS accounts managed under AWS Organizations. The operations team needs to consolidate CloudWatch metrics, logs, and traces from all accounts into a single pane of glass without deploying aggregation pipelines in each account. Which CloudWatch capability MOST directly satisfies this requirement with the least operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure a CloudWatch Subscription Filter in every source account to forward log events to a central Kinesis Data Firehose, then deliver them to Amazon OpenSearch in the monitoring account."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable CloudWatch cross-account observability using AWS Organizations so that a designated monitoring account can natively view metrics, logs, and traces from all source accounts."},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy an X-Ray daemon on a central EC2 instance in each account and configure all services to send trace segments to that instance via UDP."},{"id":"d","text":"Use AWS CloudTrail Lake with an organization trail to query API activity across all accounts from a single event data store."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Cross-account observability: monitor multiple source accounts from one monitoring account; via AWS Organizations or per-account links.' This native CloudWatch feature allows a monitoring account to search, visualize, and alert on metrics, logs, and X-Ray traces from linked source accounts without any custom aggregation pipelines, making it the lowest-overhead solution. Option A involves meaningful per-account setup of Subscription Filters and Firehose, adding operational complexity. Option C is an X-Ray-only approach and still requires per-account daemon infrastructure. Option D addresses CloudTrail API audit logs only, not CloudWatch metrics or application logs, so it does not satisfy the full requirement.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch-Unified-Cross-Account.html","label":"Amazon CloudWatch – Cross-Account Observability"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company runs a microservices application across dozens of AWS accounts managed under AWS Organizations. The operations team needs to consolidate CloudWatch metrics, logs, and traces from all accounts into a single pane of glass without deploying aggregation pipelines in each account. Which CloudWatch capability MOST directly satisfies this requirement with the least operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An engineering team is experiencing alert fatigue because dozens of individual CloudWatch Alarms fire simultaneously whenever a shared upstream dependency degrades. They want a single notification that fires only when the overall system is truly impacted, using AND logic across a subset of child alarms. They also want to suppress notifications when a related maintenance alarm is in the ALARM state. Which CloudWatch feature and configuration approach satisfies BOTH requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create a CloudWatch Metric Math alarm expression that sums all child metric values and thresholds the aggregated result; use an SNS filter policy to suppress maintenance-window notifications."},{"id":"b","text":"Use a Composite Alarm with an alarm rule that combines AND logic for the impacted child alarms and NOT logic to exclude the maintenance alarm, then attach a single SNS action to the Composite Alarm."},{"id":"c","text":"Configure an Amazon EventBridge rule that matches all child alarm state-change events and invokes a Lambda function to apply AND/NOT logic before publishing to SNS."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable CloudWatch Anomaly Detection on each child metric and set a single threshold alarm on the anomaly band's upper bound, suppressing alarms by setting the evaluation period to zero during maintenance."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Composite alarms: AND/OR/NOT logic over child alarms; reduces alert fatigue.' A Composite Alarm alarm rule can express: ALARM(child-alarm-1) AND ALARM(child-alarm-2) AND NOT ALARM(maintenance-alarm). This natively satisfies both requirements — AND logic for real impact and NOT logic for maintenance suppression — with no custom code. A single SNS action on the Composite Alarm replaces the flood of individual notifications. Option A uses Metric Math, which can aggregate values but does not support the NOT logic referencing a maintenance alarm state nor can it suppress based on another alarm's state. Option C achieves the logic via Lambda but introduces additional infrastructure and operational overhead that is unnecessary given native Composite Alarms. Option D addresses anomaly detection thresholds but does not support the AND/NOT alarm-state logic required here.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/Create_Composite_Alarm.html","label":"Amazon CloudWatch – Composite Alarms"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An engineering team is experiencing alert fatigue because dozens of individual CloudWatch Alarms fire simultaneously whenever a shared upstream dependency degrades. They want a single notification that fires only when the overall system is truly impacted, using AND logic across a subset of child alarms. They also want to suppress notifications when a related maintenance alarm is in the ALARM state. Which CloudWatch feature and configuration approach satisfies BOTH requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is configuring AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager for a production workload. They want to ensure that if the primary on-call engineer does not acknowledge a page within 10 minutes, a secondary engineer is automatically notified. Which Incident Manager feature should they configure to achieve this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A response plan with a linked SSM Automation runbook that polls for acknowledgment and invokes SNS after a timeout."},{"id":"b","text":"An escalation plan that defines primary and secondary contacts with a configurable acknowledgment timeout between escalation stages."},{"id":"c","text":"A CloudWatch alarm action that publishes to an SNS FIFO topic with message deduplication targeting both engineers simultaneously."},{"id":"d","text":"An EventBridge rule on the incident-created event that invokes a Lambda function to page the secondary contact after a delay."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Contacts and escalation plans: schedule on-call rotations with primary, secondary contacts; channels = email, SMS, voice. Engagement: notify on-call responders; auto-escalate if not acknowledged within configurable timeouts.' This is precisely the escalation plan feature in Incident Manager — you define an ordered set of stages, each stage targeting one or more contacts, with a per-stage timeout after which Incident Manager automatically advances to the next stage if the current contact has not acknowledged. Option A misuses SSM Automation for a polling loop that is not designed for this purpose and adds unnecessary complexity. Option C uses SNS with simultaneous delivery rather than escalation, meaning both engineers are paged at once with no conditional escalation logic. Option D relies on a custom Lambda delay mechanism, which duplicates functionality native to escalation plans and introduces operational overhead.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/escalation.html","label":"AWS Incident Manager – Escalation plans"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/contacts.html","label":"AWS Incident Manager – Contacts"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is configuring AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager for a production workload. They want to ensure that if the primary on-call engineer does not acknowledge a page within 10 minutes, a secondary engineer is automatically notified. Which Incident Manager feature should they configure to achieve this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security team receives a high-severity Amazon GuardDuty finding indicating that an EC2 instance may be compromised. The team wants an automated response that: (1) notifies the on-call security engineer immediately, and (2) isolates the compromised instance by replacing its security group with a restricted 'quarantine' security group — all without manual intervention. Which architecture correctly implements this using the services described in the AWS documentation?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an EventBridge rule that matches HIGH severity GuardDuty findings. Set two targets on the rule: an SNS topic (to notify the engineer) and an AWS Lambda function (to swap the instance's security group to the quarantine group)."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable GuardDuty threat intelligence export to S3, trigger an S3 event notification to Lambda, and have Lambda publish to SNS and modify the security group."},{"id":"c","text":"Create a CloudWatch Logs metric filter on GuardDuty exported logs, trigger a CloudWatch alarm, and use the alarm's SNS action to invoke Lambda for security group remediation."},{"id":"d","text":"Use AWS Config rules to detect the GuardDuty finding, trigger an SSM Automation runbook via a Config remediation action, and configure the runbook to send an SNS notification and update the security group."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly documents this pattern: 'GuardDuty findings integrate with EventBridge: route HIGH severity finding -> SNS to on-call + Lambda to isolate compromised instance via security-group swap.' EventBridge natively receives GuardDuty findings as events on the default event bus, and a single rule can fan out to multiple targets simultaneously — in this case, an SNS topic for human notification and a Lambda function for automated remediation. The source also confirms that EventBridge supports 5+ targets per rule and that Lambda and SNS are valid target types. Option B introduces unnecessary latency and complexity by routing through S3 exports instead of using the direct EventBridge integration. Option C relies on log-based metric filters, which add delay and are not the recommended integration path for GuardDuty findings. Option D uses AWS Config, which is designed for configuration compliance evaluation rather than real-time event-driven incident response, and introduces additional setup overhead without benefit.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_findings_cloudwatch.html","label":"Amazon GuardDuty – Integrating with EventBridge"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/eventbridge/latest/userguide/eb-targets.html","label":"Amazon EventBridge – Targets"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/lambda/latest/dg/services-cloudwatch-events.html","label":"AWS Lambda – Using Lambda with Amazon EventBridge"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security team receives a high-severity Amazon GuardDuty finding indicating that an EC2 instance may be compromised. The team wants an automated response that: (1) notifies the on-call security engineer immediately, and (2) isolates the compromised instance by replacing its security group with a restricted 'quarantine' security group — all without manual intervention. Which architecture correctly implements this using the services described in the AWS documentation?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After resolving a major production incident, a DevOps team wants to conduct a structured post-incident review. They need to capture a chronological sequence of key events that occurred during the incident, document which on-call contacts were engaged and when, record the steps executed by automated runbooks, and answer custom retrospective questions. Which AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager capability directly supports all of these requirements in a single workflow?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"An SSM OpsItem with enriched operational data, which stores all incident artifacts and allows custom notes in its detail section."},{"id":"b","text":"The Incident Manager post-incident analysis feature, which provides a structured timeline of events, contact engagements, runbook execution history, and supports custom retrospective questions."},{"id":"c","text":"An AWS Chatbot conversation transcript exported from the incident's Slack channel, which is archived in S3 and indexed by Athena for review."},{"id":"d","text":"A CloudWatch dashboard combining metric widgets, log insights queries, and annotation markers that the team manually populates after the incident."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material directly documents this capability: 'Post-incident analysis: structured timeline of events, contact engagements, and runbook execution; supports custom questions.' Incident Manager's post-incident analysis is purpose-built to fulfill all four stated requirements in a unified interface — it automatically captures the event timeline from the incident record, logs which contacts were paged and acknowledged, records each runbook step that was executed, and allows the team to answer custom retrospective questions (such as 'What was the root cause?' or 'How can we prevent recurrence?'). Option A describes OpsItems, which are used to track operational work items but are not designed to provide a structured post-incident analysis with custom retrospective questions or automatic timeline generation from incident data. Option C relies on a manually archived chat transcript, which is neither automated nor structured and requires significant additional tooling. Option D describes a CloudWatch dashboard, which is a monitoring tool requiring manual population and does not natively integrate contact engagement records or runbook execution history in a post-incident analysis workflow.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/analysis.html","label":"AWS Incident Manager – Post-incident analysis"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/what-is-incident-manager.html","label":"AWS Incident Manager – What is Incident Manager?"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P4'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After resolving a major production incident, a DevOps team wants to conduct a structured post-incident review. They need to capture a chronological sequence of key events that occurred during the incident, document which on-call contacts were engaged and when, record the steps executed by automated runbooks, and answer custom retrospective questions. Which AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager capability directly supports all of these requirements in a single workflow?$patch$);

-- DOP-C02-P5: 15 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is preparing to update a production CloudFormation stack that includes a critical Amazon RDS DB instance. Before applying any changes, they want to allow senior engineers to review exactly which resources will be added, modified, or replaced — without making any live changes to the environment. Which CloudFormation feature should they use to satisfy this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable drift detection on the stack to compare the live environment against the template."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a Change Set against the stack and have engineers review it before executing."},{"id":"c","text":"Apply a Stack Policy to the RDS resource to block updates until approval is granted."},{"id":"d","text":"Use the 'cdk diff' command to preview changes and share the output with senior engineers."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Change Sets: preview proposed changes before executing them. Useful for production review/approval gates.' A Change Set lets engineers see exactly which resources will be added, modified, or replaced (including replacement warnings for stateful resources like RDS) before any live change occurs. Option A (drift detection) compares an already-deployed stack against its template to find out-of-band changes — it does not preview future template updates. Option C (Stack Policy) restricts which resources can be updated but does not provide a preview mechanism; it would block the update rather than preview it. Option D ('cdk diff') is a CDK-specific command that synthesizes a new CloudFormation template and diffs it locally, but it operates outside the CloudFormation service and does not create a reviewable, service-side artifact tied to the production stack.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/using-cfn-updating-stacks-changesets.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – Using Change Sets"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/protect-stack-resources.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – Stack Policies"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is preparing to update a production CloudFormation stack that includes a critical Amazon RDS DB instance. Before applying any changes, they want to allow senior engineers to review exactly which resources will be added, modified, or replaced — without making any live changes to the environment. Which CloudFormation feature should they use to satisfy this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company manages 150 AWS accounts organized under AWS Organizations. A platform engineering team needs to deploy a standardized VPC configuration stack to every account in three specific organizational units (OUs) and across four AWS Regions — including any new accounts added to those OUs in the future. Which CloudFormation capability meets ALL of these requirements with the least operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create a master CloudFormation template with nested stacks and manually execute it in each account-region combination."},{"id":"b","text":"Use CloudFormation StackSets with service-managed permissions targeting the three OUs, and enable automatic deployment for new accounts."},{"id":"c","text":"Use cross-stack references with Fn::ImportValue to share VPC outputs across all accounts and regions."},{"id":"d","text":"Package the VPC pattern as an AWS CDK L3 construct and run 'cdk deploy --all' from a CI/CD pipeline against each account."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'StackSets: deploy a stack across multiple accounts and regions from a single admin account; uses AWS Organizations for trusted access; supports service-managed permissions.' With service-managed permissions, StackSets integrates directly with AWS Organizations so that stacks are automatically deployed to new accounts added to the targeted OUs — satisfying the future-account requirement with no manual intervention. Option A (nested stacks) addresses template reuse within a single account/region and requires manual execution per account, which is impractical at scale. Option C (cross-stack references / Fn::ImportValue) is designed for sharing outputs between stacks in the same account/region and does not provision resources across accounts or regions. Option D (CDK deploy --all) can target multiple accounts but requires per-account credential configuration and pipeline orchestration, resulting in significantly more operational overhead than StackSets with Organizations integration.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/stacksets-concepts.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – StackSets Concepts"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/stacksets-orgs-activate-trusted-access.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – Service-Managed StackSets with AWS Organizations"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company manages 150 AWS accounts organized under AWS Organizations. A platform engineering team needs to deploy a standardized VPC configuration stack to every account in three specific organizational units (OUs) and across four AWS Regions — including any new accounts added to those OUs in the future. Which CloudFormation capability meets ALL of these requirements with the least operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is authoring a CloudFormation template that provisions an Amazon EC2 instance. The instance's AMI ID must be sourced dynamically from AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store at deploy time so that it always reflects the latest approved golden AMI — without requiring the template to be modified each time the AMI is rotated. The parameter is stored at the path '/golden-ami/amazon-linux-2/latest'. Which template snippet correctly implements this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Declare a CloudFormation Parameter of Type 'AWS::SSM::Parameter::Value<AWS::EC2::Image::Id>' with Default '/golden-ami/amazon-linux-2/latest', and reference it with !Ref in the ImageId property."},{"id":"b","text":"Hardcode the AMI ID string in the ImageId property and update the template manually each time the AMI changes."},{"id":"c","text":"Use the dynamic reference '{{resolve:secretsmanager:/golden-ami/amazon-linux-2/latest:SecretString:amiId}}' in the ImageId property."},{"id":"d","text":"Use a CloudFormation Mapping that maps each region to a static AMI ID and retrieve the value with !FindInMap at deploy time."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states two mechanisms for Parameter Store integration: 'Parameters: input values; supports … AWS::SSM::Parameter::Value for dynamic Parameter Store lookups' and 'Dynamic references in templates: {{resolve:ssm:/path:1}}'. Using a CloudFormation Parameter of type 'AWS::SSM::Parameter::Value<AWS::EC2::Image::Id>' causes CloudFormation to resolve the SSM parameter at deploy time automatically; when the golden AMI is rotated and the SSM parameter value is updated, the next stack deployment (or update) picks up the new AMI ID without any template change. Option B requires manual template edits on every AMI rotation, which defeats the purpose of automation. Option C uses a Secrets Manager dynamic reference, which is appropriate for secrets — the source material notes '{{resolve:secretsmanager:secret-id:SecretString:key}}' for Secrets Manager — but an AMI ID in Parameter Store is not a secret, making this the wrong service and resolver. Option D (Mappings with !FindInMap) is a static lookup table as described in the source material ('Mappings: static lookup tables (e.g., region -> AMI)'); it still requires the template to be updated when AMI IDs change, offering no dynamic resolution.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/parameters-section-structure.html#aws-ssm-parameter-types","label":"AWS CloudFormation – Using AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store as CloudFormation Parameter Types"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/dynamic-references.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – Dynamic References to Specify Template Values"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is authoring a CloudFormation template that provisions an Amazon EC2 instance. The instance's AMI ID must be sourced dynamically from AWS Systems Manager Parameter Store at deploy time so that it always reflects the latest approved golden AMI — without requiring the template to be modified each time the AMI is rotated. The parameter is stored at the path '/golden-ami/amazon-linux-2/latest'. Which template snippet correctly implements this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is building a centralized security operations workflow across 12 AWS accounts in three Regions. They want a single pane of glass that normalizes findings from GuardDuty, Amazon Inspector, Amazon Macie, and AWS Config into one consistent schema so that downstream Lambda-based remediation functions can parse findings without per-service branching logic. Which AWS feature DIRECTLY satisfies this normalization requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"AWS Security Hub with AWS Security Finding Format (ASFF) as the unified finding schema"},{"id":"b","text":"Amazon EventBridge with a custom event schema registry that maps each service's native finding format"},{"id":"c","text":"AWS Config Aggregator with a conformance pack that collects rule evaluations from all accounts and Regions"},{"id":"d","text":"Amazon CloudWatch Logs Insights with a unified log group that ingests findings from all security services"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states that AWS Security Hub acts as a 'central aggregator' that 'consolidates findings from GuardDuty, Inspector, Macie, AWS Config, IAM Access Analyzer, Firewall Manager, and third-party partner products' and 'uses AWS Security Finding Format (ASFF) as the normalized finding schema.' ASFF is the single schema that all integrated services translate their findings into, meaning downstream consumers such as Lambda functions can process any finding with a uniform data structure — no per-service conditional parsing needed. Option B (EventBridge schema registry) only maps schemas; it does not normalize findings from multiple services into one format. Option C (Config Aggregator) consolidates configuration compliance data only — it does not ingest GuardDuty or Macie findings. Option D (CloudWatch Logs Insights) is a log query service with no finding normalization capability.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/securityhub-findings-format.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Findings and ASFF"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/securityhub-internal-providers.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Integrating with other AWS services"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is building a centralized security operations workflow across 12 AWS accounts in three Regions. They want a single pane of glass that normalizes findings from GuardDuty, Amazon Inspector, Amazon Macie, and AWS Config into one consistent schema so that downstream Lambda-based remediation functions can parse findings without per-service branching logic. Which AWS feature DIRECTLY satisfies this normalization requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company must ensure that all S3 buckets across every account in its AWS Organization remain compliant with a rule prohibiting public read access. When a bucket is found non-compliant, an SSM Automation document must remediate it automatically within minutes — without manual intervention. The solution must also be deployable consistently across all member accounts from a single control point. Which combination of AWS Config features fulfills ALL of these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy the s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited managed Config rule with auto-remediation via an SSM Automation document, packaged inside a Conformance Pack deployed through AWS Organizations"},{"id":"b","text":"Deploy the s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited managed Config rule in each account individually, and configure a CloudWatch Events rule to invoke a Lambda function that calls the SSM Automation document"},{"id":"c","text":"Enable AWS Security Hub FSBP standard in every account; Security Hub will automatically remediate non-compliant S3 buckets without additional configuration"},{"id":"d","text":"Use AWS Config Aggregator to collect compliance data and manually review non-compliant resources in the aggregator dashboard, then trigger SSM Automation on demand"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material describes two distinct AWS Config capabilities that together satisfy all requirements. First, 'Conformance Packs: bundle of Config rules + remediation actions for a compliance framework; deploy across accounts via Organizations' — this provides the single-control-point, organization-wide deployment. Second, 'Auto-remediation: trigger SSM Automation document when a rule is non-compliant' — this provides the automatic, near-real-time remediation without manual steps. The managed rule s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited is explicitly cited in the source as an example managed rule. Combining these two features inside a Conformance Pack deployed via Organizations is the fully automated, scalable solution. Option B satisfies remediation but requires per-account manual deployment and adds unnecessary Lambda complexity. Option C is incorrect because Security Hub does not auto-remediate by default — it surfaces findings and can trigger EventBridge, but remediation requires explicit automation wiring. Option D explicitly involves manual review and is therefore not fully automated.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/conformance-packs.html","label":"AWS Config – Conformance Packs"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/remediation.html","label":"AWS Config – Automatic Remediation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited.html","label":"AWS Config Managed Rule – s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company must ensure that all S3 buckets across every account in its AWS Organization remain compliant with a rule prohibiting public read access. When a bucket is found non-compliant, an SSM Automation document must remediate it automatically within minutes — without manual intervention. The solution must also be deployable consistently across all member accounts from a single control point. Which combination of AWS Config features fulfills ALL of these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer discovers that a symmetric AWS KMS Customer Managed Key (CMK) has not been rotated for over 14 months. The engineer wants to immediately rotate the key material. The engineer's colleague suggests enabling KMS automatic key rotation. Which statement CORRECTLY describes the behavior and limitation the engineer must understand before choosing between automatic and manual rotation for this CMK?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enabling automatic key rotation immediately triggers a rotation; KMS will rotate the key material on demand and update all existing ciphertext to use the new key material automatically"},{"id":"b","text":"Automatic key rotation operates on an annual cycle for symmetric CMKs and does NOT immediately rotate the key; manual rotation requires creating a new CMK and re-encrypting data encrypted under the old CMK"},{"id":"c","text":"Automatic key rotation rotates the key material every 90 days for symmetric CMKs and automatically re-encrypts all data keys stored in AWS services"},{"id":"d","text":"Manual rotation can be performed in-place by calling the kms:RotateKeyOnDemand API, which replaces the backing key material of the existing CMK without requiring creation of a new CMK or re-encryption"}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'KMS automatic key rotation (annual for symmetric CMKs); manual rotation requires creating a new key and re-encrypting.' This directly supports option B on both counts: (1) automatic rotation is annual — not immediate, not 90 days — so enabling it will NOT immediately resolve the 14-month gap; and (2) manual rotation is a more involved process requiring a brand-new CMK and explicit re-encryption of data. Option A is wrong because enabling automatic rotation does not trigger an immediate rotation — it schedules the next rotation to occur one year from the last rotation. Option C is incorrect because the rotation period is annual, not 90 days, and KMS does NOT automatically re-encrypt data keys stored in downstream services; existing ciphertext remains decryptable via the retained old backing key material, but new encryptions use the new material. Option D misrepresents the KMS API; while AWS did introduce on-demand rotation (kms:RotateKeyOnDemand) for certain key types, manual rotation as described in the source material still fundamentally means creating a new CMK and updating references, which is the behavior the exam blueprint and source material ground this question in.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/kms/latest/developerguide/rotate-keys.html","label":"AWS KMS – Rotating AWS KMS keys"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/kms/latest/developerguide/rotate-keys.html#rotate-keys-how-it-works","label":"AWS KMS – How automatic key rotation works"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer discovers that a symmetric AWS KMS Customer Managed Key (CMK) has not been rotated for over 14 months. The engineer wants to immediately rotate the key material. The engineer's colleague suggests enabling KMS automatic key rotation. Which statement CORRECTLY describes the behavior and limitation the engineer must understand before choosing between automatic and manual rotation for this CMK?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is running a critical e-commerce application on EC2 instances managed by an Auto Scaling Group (ASG). During peak sales events, new instances are launched but they take several minutes to bootstrap application dependencies, causing them to receive traffic before they are fully ready. Which ASG feature should the team implement to ensure new instances are fully initialized before serving production traffic?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure a Lifecycle Hook on the Pending:Wait state to run the bootstrap script, then call CompleteLifecycleAction when initialization is complete."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable Predictive Scaling so that the ASG launches instances hours in advance of the anticipated demand spike."},{"id":"c","text":"Switch from a Launch Template to a Launch Configuration and embed the full bootstrap script in the UserData field."},{"id":"d","text":"Increase the ALB target group deregistration delay to 600 seconds so instances have more time to finish startup."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Lifecycle hooks: Pending:Wait and Terminating:Wait states; perform actions (bootstrap, drain) before transition; emit CompleteLifecycleAction to proceed.' A Pending:Wait lifecycle hook pauses the instance in a waiting state before it is placed InService. The bootstrap script runs during this pause, and once complete the team calls CompleteLifecycleAction to allow the ASG to move the instance to InService and register it with the load balancer. Predictive Scaling (option B) addresses when instances are launched relative to demand but does not prevent unready instances from receiving traffic. Switching to a Launch Configuration (option C) is discouraged — Launch Templates are preferred — and UserData still does not gate traffic until the script finishes unless a lifecycle hook is also used. Deregistration delay (option D) controls how long a *deregistering* target continues to receive in-flight requests; it has no effect on the startup path.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/lifecycle-hooks.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling Lifecycle Hooks"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/APIReference/API_CompleteLifecycleAction.html","label":"CompleteLifecycleAction API Reference"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is running a critical e-commerce application on EC2 instances managed by an Auto Scaling Group (ASG). During peak sales events, new instances are launched but they take several minutes to bootstrap application dependencies, causing them to receive traffic before they are fully ready. Which ASG feature should the team implement to ensure new instances are fully initialized before serving production traffic?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An organization operates a globally distributed SaaS platform with users across North America and Europe. The primary workload runs in us-east-1, and a disaster recovery environment exists in eu-west-1. The business requires an RTO of under 15 minutes and an RPO of under 5 minutes for their Aurora MySQL database. The DR environment must be capable of accepting full production traffic within minutes of a regional failure. Which combination of Aurora and Route 53 capabilities BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy an Aurora Global Database spanning us-east-1 and eu-west-1, and configure a Route 53 Failover routing policy with health checks on the primary endpoint; promote the secondary cluster during a failure."},{"id":"b","text":"Create an RDS Read Replica in eu-west-1 using asynchronous cross-Region replication, and update Route 53 weighted records to shift traffic to eu-west-1 after a failure."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable Aurora Serverless v2 in us-east-1 so the cluster auto-scales ACUs, then use an S3 cross-Region replication job to copy daily snapshots to eu-west-1 as the DR copy."},{"id":"d","text":"Configure a Multi-AZ Aurora deployment within us-east-1 and rely on automatic AZ failover to meet both the RPO and RTO targets in the event of a regional outage."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Aurora Global Database: cross-Region replicated cluster with <1s lag for DR.' A Global Database replicates with sub-second lag, which easily satisfies the 5-minute RPO. During a regional failure, the secondary cluster in eu-west-1 can be promoted to a standalone writer — a managed operation that completes in under a minute — meeting the 15-minute RTO. Route 53 Failover routing with health checks automates DNS cutover when the primary endpoint becomes unhealthy, as described: 'DNS Failover for active-passive DR.' This combination maps directly to the Warm Standby or better DR strategy. Option B uses asynchronous RDS Read Replicas; while cross-Region replication is supported, RDS Read Replica lag and the manual promotion process are less predictable than Aurora Global Database and do not guarantee sub-5-minute RPO. Option C couples Aurora Serverless v2 (a scaling feature, not a DR feature) with S3 snapshot replication, which would yield hours-level RPO/RTO — consistent only with Backup & Restore strategy. Option D uses Multi-AZ within a single Region; it protects against AZ failures but offers no resilience against a full Regional outage.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/AuroraUserGuide/aurora-global-database.html","label":"Aurora Global Database – Amazon Aurora"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/dns-failover.html","label":"Route 53 DNS Failover"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/disaster-recovery-workloads-on-aws/disaster-recovery-options-in-the-cloud.html","label":"Disaster Recovery Options in the Cloud (AWS Whitepaper)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An organization operates a globally distributed SaaS platform with users across North America and Europe. The primary workload runs in us-east-1, and a disaster recovery environment exists in eu-west-1. The business requires an RTO of under 15 minutes and an RPO of under 5 minutes for their Aurora MySQL database. The DR environment must be capable of accepting full production traffic within minutes of a regional failure. Which combination of Aurora and Route 53 capabilities BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps Engineer is updating the base AMI for an Auto Scaling Group that serves a high-traffic REST API behind an Application Load Balancer. Leadership requires that the rollout minimize user impact and allow the team to detect any regression before all instances are replaced. The ASG has 40 instances spread across three Availability Zones. Which ASG feature and configuration BEST meets these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Trigger an Instance Refresh with a Canary strategy, setting a small percentage of instances to be replaced first and defining a health check grace period; monitor for errors before the rollout continues to remaining instances."},{"id":"b","text":"Use a Scheduled Scaling policy to reduce the ASG to zero instances during off-peak hours, then update the Launch Template and set the desired capacity back to 40 so all new instances use the updated AMI."},{"id":"c","text":"Manually terminate instances one by one and allow the ASG to replace them using the updated Launch Template, relying on ALB connection draining to protect in-flight requests."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable a Warm Pool with pre-initialized instances running the new AMI, then double the desired capacity to bring all new instances into service simultaneously and terminate the old ones."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Instance Refresh: rolling replacement on AMI/launch-template update; supports Canary.' The Canary strategy replaces a small subset of instances first (a 'canary' batch), then pauses so operators can evaluate application health metrics or error rates before proceeding with the rest of the fleet. A health check grace period ensures the ALB's health checks have time to validate the new instances before the refresh advances. This provides a gated, low-risk rollout with the ability to cancel mid-flight if regressions are detected. Option B terminates all 40 instances simultaneously (by setting desired to 0) causing a complete outage, which directly contradicts the requirement to minimize user impact. Option C performs manual terminations, which is operationally error-prone at scale, not automated, and does not provide the structured regression-detection gate that Instance Refresh offers. Option D uses a Warm Pool — described in the source as 'pre-initialized instances in Stopped state for fast scale-out' — but doubling capacity and simultaneously cutting over all instances does not provide a canary validation gate and temporarily doubles cost without a safe rollback mechanism.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/asg-instance-refresh.html","label":"Replace Auto Scaling Instances Using Instance Refresh"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/asg-instance-refresh-overview.html#instance-refresh-strategies","label":"Instance Refresh Strategies (Canary)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/elasticloadbalancing/latest/application/load-balancer-target-groups.html#deregistration-delay","label":"ALB Connection Draining (Deregistration Delay)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps Engineer is updating the base AMI for an Auto Scaling Group that serves a high-traffic REST API behind an Application Load Balancer. Leadership requires that the rollout minimize user impact and allow the team to detect any regression before all instances are replaced. The ASG has 40 instances spread across three Availability Zones. Which ASG feature and configuration BEST meets these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is building a high-throughput microservices platform on AWS. They need to publish custom application metrics to Amazon CloudWatch at the highest possible resolution without incurring excessive API costs. The metrics are already being written to Amazon CloudWatch Logs as part of structured application logs. Which approach BEST meets both the high-resolution and cost-efficiency requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Call PutMetricData with StorageResolution set to 1 for every metric data point generated by the application."},{"id":"b","text":"Use the Embedded Metric Format (EMF) to write structured JSON log lines to CloudWatch Logs; CloudWatch will automatically extract high-resolution metrics from those log lines."},{"id":"c","text":"Create a CloudWatch Metric Filter on the existing log group with a custom metric resolution of 1 second."},{"id":"d","text":"Configure a CloudWatch Subscription Filter to stream logs to a Lambda function that calls PutMetricData for each log event."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Embedded Metric Format (EMF): structured JSON log line; CloudWatch automatically extracts metrics. Reduces API calls and cost.' EMF is the purpose-built solution when metrics are already flowing through CloudWatch Logs — it avoids the overhead of separate PutMetricData API calls (limited to 1,000 data points per call) and is therefore both higher-throughput and more cost-efficient. Option A is functionally possible but costly and rate-limited. Option C is incorrect because Metric Filters do not support 1-second (high-resolution) custom metrics — they produce standard-resolution metrics. Option D introduces unnecessary architectural complexity and Lambda invocation costs when EMF achieves the same outcome natively.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch_Embedded_Metric_Format_Specification.html","label":"CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format – AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/APIReference/API_PutMetricData.html","label":"PutMetricData API Reference – AWS Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is building a high-throughput microservices platform on AWS. They need to publish custom application metrics to Amazon CloudWatch at the highest possible resolution without incurring excessive API costs. The metrics are already being written to Amazon CloudWatch Logs as part of structured application logs. Which approach BEST meets both the high-resolution and cost-efficiency requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company operates workloads across 25 AWS accounts managed under AWS Organizations. The central platform engineering team needs a single consolidated view of CloudWatch alarms, metrics, and logs across all accounts without building and maintaining custom cross-account IAM role assumption logic in their dashboards. They also want anomaly-detection alarms from child accounts to surface in the central account. Which CloudWatch capability DIRECTLY satisfies this requirement with the least operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy a CloudWatch Synthetics canary in each member account and aggregate canary run results in a central S3 bucket."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a CloudWatch Subscription Filter in each member account to stream all metrics and alarms to a central Kinesis Data Firehose, then visualize them in Amazon OpenSearch Service."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable CloudWatch cross-account observability using AWS Organizations to link all source accounts to a designated monitoring account, allowing the central team to view metrics, alarms, and logs natively in the monitoring account's CloudWatch console."},{"id":"d","text":"Configure an AWS CloudTrail organization trail and integrate it with CloudWatch Logs in a central account to ingest all account activity as a unified log stream."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Cross-account observability: monitor multiple source accounts from one monitoring account; via AWS Organizations or per-account links.' This feature is purpose-built for exactly this scenario — a single monitoring account can natively query, visualize, and alarm on metrics, logs, and alarms from linked source accounts through the standard CloudWatch console, eliminating the need for custom IAM role assumption code. Option A (Synthetics canaries) only monitors endpoint availability, not existing application metrics and alarms. Option B (Subscription Filter → Firehose → OpenSearch) is a valid near-real-time analytics pattern for logs but does not provide native CloudWatch alarm visibility and requires significant operational plumbing. Option D (CloudTrail organization trail) captures API activity (control-plane events), not application metrics or CloudWatch alarm states.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch-Unified-Cross-Account.html","label":"CloudWatch Cross-Account Observability – AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/organizations/latest/userguide/orgs_introduction.html","label":"AWS Organizations – AWS Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company operates workloads across 25 AWS accounts managed under AWS Organizations. The central platform engineering team needs a single consolidated view of CloudWatch alarms, metrics, and logs across all accounts without building and maintaining custom cross-account IAM role assumption logic in their dashboards. They also want anomaly-detection alarms from child accounts to surface in the central account. Which CloudWatch capability DIRECTLY satisfies this requirement with the least operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is troubleshooting intermittent latency spikes in a distributed application running on AWS Lambda, Amazon ECS, and Amazon DynamoDB. The team has AWS X-Ray tracing enabled. They notice that the default X-Ray sampling configuration is causing most high-latency requests — which occur at irregular, low frequency — to be dropped before a trace is recorded. Which X-Ray configuration change will MOST reliably ensure high-latency outlier requests are captured while keeping overall trace volume and cost manageable?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Increase the default reservoir rate to 100 requests per second and set the fixed rate to 100% to capture all traffic."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a custom X-Ray sampling rule targeting the specific service names and URL paths associated with the slow operations, setting a higher fixed rate for those rules while leaving the default rule unchanged for other traffic."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable X-Ray Active Tracing on all Lambda functions and set the Lambda reserved concurrency to 1 to serialize invocations and reduce trace volume."},{"id":"d","text":"Switch from X-Ray daemon-based tracing to CloudWatch ServiceLens, which automatically captures 100% of requests without any sampling configuration."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material notes: 'Sampling rules: default 1 req/sec + 5% of additional traffic; custom rules per service/URL/method.' Custom sampling rules allow the team to increase the capture rate specifically for the services and endpoints exhibiting latency issues (e.g., higher fixed-rate percentage for the DynamoDB subsegment path) without inflating trace volume and cost for all other traffic. This is the canonical approach for surfacing low-frequency outlier requests. Option A sets a blanket 100% sampling rate which would capture outliers but at the cost of tracing every request across all services — expensive and operationally impractical at scale. Option C conflates Active Tracing (a Lambda-specific enablement mechanism) with sampling configuration and introduces a harmful architectural anti-pattern (concurrency = 1). Option D is incorrect; CloudWatch ServiceLens is described in the source as an overlay that 'overlays CloudWatch with X-Ray traces' — it does not bypass X-Ray sampling, nor does it automatically capture 100% of requests.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/xray/latest/devguide/xray-console-sampling.html","label":"X-Ray Sampling Rules – AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/xray/latest/devguide/xray-concepts.html","label":"AWS X-Ray Concepts: Segments and Sampling – AWS Documentation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/ServiceLens.html","label":"CloudWatch ServiceLens – AWS Documentation"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is troubleshooting intermittent latency spikes in a distributed application running on AWS Lambda, Amazon ECS, and Amazon DynamoDB. The team has AWS X-Ray tracing enabled. They notice that the default X-Ray sampling configuration is causing most high-latency requests — which occur at irregular, low frequency — to be dropped before a trace is recorded. Which X-Ray configuration change will MOST reliably ensure high-latency outlier requests are captured while keeping overall trace volume and cost manageable?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is configuring AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager to handle production incidents. They need on-call responders to be automatically paged when an incident is created, and if a responder does not acknowledge within 10 minutes, a secondary contact must be engaged automatically. Which Incident Manager constructs together satisfy this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A response plan with a chat channel configured to post to Slack via AWS Chatbot, combined with a CloudWatch alarm action that sends an SNS notification to the secondary contact directly."},{"id":"b","text":"A contact record with primary and secondary channels, an escalation plan that promotes to the secondary contact after a configurable acknowledgment timeout, and a response plan that references that escalation plan as the engagement target."},{"id":"c","text":"An EventBridge rule that matches the incident creation event and invokes two separate Lambda functions — one to notify the primary contact and one to notify the secondary contact simultaneously."},{"id":"d","text":"An SSM Automation runbook attached to the response plan that contains a manual approval gate; the approval notification is sent to the primary contact, and on timeout the runbook proceeds to notify the secondary contact."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Contacts and escalation plans: schedule on-call rotations with primary, secondary contacts; channels = email, SMS, voice' and 'Engagement: notify on-call responders; auto-escalate if not acknowledged within configurable timeouts.' The correct architecture is to define a Contact with primary and secondary notification channels, then build an Escalation Plan that specifies the acknowledgment timeout before promoting to the next contact stage, and finally reference that escalation plan inside the Response Plan's engagement section. Option A incorrectly relies on SNS/Chatbot for escalation logic, which has no built-in acknowledgment timeout. Option C uses EventBridge + Lambda but bypasses Incident Manager's native escalation mechanism entirely, providing no acknowledgment-based gating. Option D misuses SSM Automation manual approval gates, which are designed for runbook flow control, not on-call escalation with acknowledgment timeouts.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/contacts.html","label":"AWS Incident Manager – Contacts and escalation plans"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/response-plans.html","label":"AWS Incident Manager – Response plans"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is configuring AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager to handle production incidents. They need on-call responders to be automatically paged when an incident is created, and if a responder does not acknowledge within 10 minutes, a secondary contact must be engaged automatically. Which Incident Manager constructs together satisfy this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An AWS GuardDuty finding of HIGH severity is detected in a production account. The security team requires that: (1) on-call engineers are notified immediately via SMS, and (2) the compromised EC2 instance is automatically isolated by replacing its security group with a restricted one — all without manual intervention. Which architecture best satisfies both requirements using the source material guidance?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an EventBridge rule that matches GuardDuty HIGH severity findings and configure two targets: an SNS topic (subscribed to by the on-call team via SMS) and a Lambda function that swaps the instance's security group to a restricted one."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable GuardDuty threat intelligence export to an S3 bucket, configure an S3 Event Notification to trigger a Lambda function for isolation, and separately configure a CloudWatch Metric Alarm on GuardDuty findings to publish to an SNS SMS topic."},{"id":"c","text":"Create an EventBridge rule that matches GuardDuty HIGH severity findings with a single target: an SNS FIFO topic that fans out to both an SMS subscription for the engineers and an SQS queue polled by a Lambda function for isolation."},{"id":"d","text":"Configure AWS Security Hub to aggregate GuardDuty findings, create a Security Hub custom action, and manually trigger an SSM Automation runbook from the Security Hub console whenever a HIGH severity finding appears."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly describes this pattern: 'GuardDuty findings integrate with EventBridge: route HIGH severity finding -> SNS to on-call + Lambda to isolate compromised instance via security-group swap.' EventBridge supports multiple targets per rule (the source states '5+ targets per rule'), making it straightforward to fan out to both SNS (for SMS notification) and Lambda (for automated isolation) from a single rule. Option B is overly complex, relies on S3 event indirection not described for this use case, and CloudWatch Metric Alarms on GuardDuty findings are a non-standard path compared to the native EventBridge integration. Option C is flawed because SNS FIFO topics do not support SMS subscriptions — FIFO topics only support SQS FIFO queues as subscribers — making the SMS notification path invalid. Option D requires manual intervention ('manually trigger'), which violates the 'without manual intervention' requirement.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_findings_cloudwatch.html","label":"Amazon GuardDuty – EventBridge integration for automated responses"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/eventbridge/latest/userguide/eb-targets.html","label":"Amazon EventBridge – Targets for rules"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/sns/latest/dg/sns-fifo-topics.html","label":"Amazon SNS – FIFO topics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An AWS GuardDuty finding of HIGH severity is detected in a production account. The security team requires that: (1) on-call engineers are notified immediately via SMS, and (2) the compromised EC2 instance is automatically isolated by replacing its security group with a restricted one — all without manual intervention. Which architecture best satisfies both requirements using the source material guidance?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company runs a critical payment-processing service on AWS. After a major incident, leadership mandates that the team conduct a structured post-incident analysis capturing: a timeline of all events, which contacts were engaged and when, which runbook steps executed, and custom lessons-learned answers. The DevOps engineer is told to use native AWS tooling only. Which service and feature directly fulfills this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"AWS CloudTrail Lake, by running SQL queries against management and data events recorded during the incident window to reconstruct a timeline and export results to an S3 report."},{"id":"b","text":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager post-incident analysis, which provides a structured timeline of events, contact engagement records, runbook execution history, and supports custom questions for lessons learned."},{"id":"c","text":"Amazon CloudWatch Application Insights, by configuring a custom dashboard that correlates alarm history, Lambda invocation logs, and SNS delivery logs into a unified incident timeline with annotation support."},{"id":"d","text":"AWS Config with a conformance pack that evaluates resource configuration changes during the incident and generates a compliance report mapping each change to a responsible IAM principal."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states directly: 'Post-incident analysis: structured timeline of events, contact engagements, and runbook execution; supports custom questions.' AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager's post-incident analysis feature is purpose-built for exactly this use case — it automatically captures the incident timeline, logs which contacts were engaged and at what time, records each runbook step that was executed, and allows teams to answer custom questions (e.g., 'What was the root cause?', 'What can we improve?') as part of a formal lessons-learned process. Option A (CloudTrail Lake) can reconstruct API-level events but does not natively correlate contact engagements, runbook steps, or provide a structured lessons-learned template. Option C (CloudWatch Application Insights) focuses on application anomaly detection and dashboards, not structured post-incident reviews. Option D (AWS Config) tracks configuration compliance and drift, not incident timelines or on-call engagement records.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/analysis.html","label":"AWS Incident Manager – Post-incident analysis"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/what-is-incident-manager.html","label":"AWS Incident Manager – What is AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager?"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P5'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company runs a critical payment-processing service on AWS. After a major incident, leadership mandates that the team conduct a structured post-incident analysis capturing: a timeline of all events, which contacts were engaged and when, which runbook steps executed, and custom lessons-learned answers. The DevOps engineer is told to use native AWS tooling only. Which service and feature directly fulfills this requirement?$patch$);

-- DOP-C02-P6: 15 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a CloudFormation stack that provisions a production RDS database instance and several surrounding Lambda functions. Leadership requires that the database resource can never be accidentally modified or replaced during future stack updates, while all other resources remain freely updatable. Which CloudFormation feature should the engineer configure to enforce this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable stack termination protection on the entire stack."},{"id":"b","text":"Set the DeletionPolicy attribute to Retain on the RDS resource."},{"id":"c","text":"Apply a Stack Policy that explicitly denies Update actions on the RDS DBInstance logical resource."},{"id":"d","text":"Use a Change Set to review changes before each deployment."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Stack Policies, as described in the source material, protect specific logical resources from updates. By authoring a Stack Policy that includes a Deny statement targeting the Update action on the RDS DBInstance logical resource, any attempt to modify that resource during a stack update will be blocked. (A) Stack termination protection only prevents the entire stack from being deleted — it does not prevent individual resource updates. (B) DeletionPolicy: Retain prevents the physical resource from being deleted when the stack or resource is removed, but it does not block update or replacement operations during a stack update. (D) Change Sets allow engineers to preview proposed changes but do not enforce a preventive control; a Change Set can still be executed and the resource changed.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/protect-stack-resources.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – Stack Policies"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a CloudFormation stack that provisions a production RDS database instance and several surrounding Lambda functions. Leadership requires that the database resource can never be accidentally modified or replaced during future stack updates, while all other resources remain freely updatable. Which CloudFormation feature should the engineer configure to enforce this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A platform engineering team manages infrastructure for 40 AWS accounts organized under AWS Organizations. They need to deploy a standardized VPC architecture — including subnets, route tables, and security groups — to every account in a specific Organizational Unit (OU), including any new accounts that join the OU in the future. The solution must minimize operational overhead. Which CloudFormation capability best satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create a CloudFormation nested stack in the management account and reference it from each child account using cross-stack Fn::ImportValue references."},{"id":"b","text":"Use CloudFormation StackSets with service-managed permissions and target the specific Organizational Unit, enabling automatic deployment to accounts."},{"id":"c","text":"Store the VPC template in S3 and trigger a CloudFormation stack creation via a Lambda function invoked by an EventBridge scheduled rule in each account."},{"id":"d","text":"Use AWS CDK with a pipeline that iterates over a hard-coded list of account IDs and runs cdk deploy for each account."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'StackSets: deploy a stack across multiple accounts and regions from a single admin account; uses AWS Organizations for trusted access; supports service-managed permissions.' Service-managed permissions allow StackSets to automatically deploy to all accounts in a targeted OU and to any new accounts added to that OU in the future, directly addressing the zero-touch requirement. (A) Nested stacks and Fn::ImportValue are for reusing and sharing values within a single account/region context — they cannot deploy resources into other accounts. (C) A Lambda + EventBridge approach could work but requires significant custom orchestration and does not natively integrate with Organizations OUs for automatic coverage of new accounts. (D) A CDK pipeline with a hard-coded account list requires manual updates whenever accounts are added, introducing operational overhead.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/stacksets-orgs-enable-trusted-access.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – StackSets with AWS Organizations"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/stacksets-concepts.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – StackSets Concepts"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A platform engineering team manages infrastructure for 40 AWS accounts organized under AWS Organizations. They need to deploy a standardized VPC architecture — including subnets, route tables, and security groups — to every account in a specific Organizational Unit (OU), including any new accounts that join the OU in the future. The solution must minimize operational overhead. Which CloudFormation capability best satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is authoring a CloudFormation template that provisions an EC2 Auto Scaling group running a custom application. The stack must not report CREATE_COMPLETE until at least three instances have signaled that the application tier is fully initialized and healthy. The instances run a user-data script that installs and starts the application. Which combination of CloudFormation mechanisms should the engineer implement to meet this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Add a DependsOn attribute on the Auto Scaling group pointing to an Application Load Balancer resource, and configure health checks on the ALB target group."},{"id":"b","text":"Configure a CreationPolicy on the Auto Scaling group resource with a ResourceSignal count of 3 and a timeout, then invoke cfn-signal at the end of the user-data script on each instance."},{"id":"c","text":"Use an UpdatePolicy with AutoScalingRollingUpdate on the Auto Scaling group and set MinSuccessfulInstancesPercent to 75."},{"id":"d","text":"Create a CloudFormation custom resource backed by a Lambda function that polls the Auto Scaling group activity history and returns SUCCESS when three InService instances are detected."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'CreationPolicy with cfn-signal: wait for application startup before reporting CREATE_COMPLETE.' A CreationPolicy with ResourceSignal.Count set to 3 instructs CloudFormation to wait until exactly 3 success signals are received before transitioning the stack to CREATE_COMPLETE. The cfn-signal helper utility is invoked at the end of the user-data script on each instance to send that signal once the application has fully started. (A) DependsOn only controls the ordering of resource creation within the stack; it does not wait for application-level readiness signals from within the instance. (C) UpdatePolicy with AutoScalingRollingUpdate controls behavior during stack updates, not initial stack creation, and does not gate the CREATE_COMPLETE transition. (D) A custom Lambda-backed resource could theoretically poll Auto Scaling, but it is a complex, non-idiomatic solution for a problem that CreationPolicy + cfn-signal solves natively and precisely.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-attribute-creationpolicy.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – CreationPolicy Attribute"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/cfn-signal.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – cfn-signal Helper Script"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is authoring a CloudFormation template that provisions an EC2 Auto Scaling group running a custom application. The stack must not report CREATE_COMPLETE until at least three instances have signaled that the application tier is fully initialized and healthy. The instances run a user-data script that installs and starts the application. Which combination of CloudFormation mechanisms should the engineer implement to meet this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is building a multi-account AWS environment spanning five AWS Regions. The security team requires a single pane of glass for all security findings generated by GuardDuty, Amazon Inspector, and Amazon Macie across every account and Region. They also need findings normalized into a common schema so that downstream Lambda-based remediation functions do not have to handle product-specific formats. Which combination of actions BEST satisfies both requirements with the least operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable AWS Security Hub in each account and Region individually, designate one Region as the home Region for cross-Region aggregation, and use AWS Organizations integration to auto-enable member accounts. Rely on the AWS Security Finding Format (ASFF) as the normalized schema for all ingested findings."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a custom Lambda function that polls the GuardDuty, Inspector, and Macie APIs in each Region every five minutes, transforms findings into a proprietary JSON schema, and writes them to a central DynamoDB table in the management account."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable AWS Config Aggregator across all accounts and Regions and use Config conformance packs to collect and normalize findings from GuardDuty, Inspector, and Macie."},{"id":"d","text":"Configure Amazon EventBridge event buses in each Region to forward all security-service events to a central account's event bus, then use a single Lambda to manually normalize each event payload into a common format."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that AWS Security Hub is a 'central aggregator: consolidates findings from GuardDuty, Inspector, Macie, AWS Config, IAM Access Analyzer, Firewall Manager, and third-party partner products' and that it 'uses AWS Security Finding Format (ASFF) as the normalized finding schema.' It further states that 'cross-Region aggregation: designate a home Region; linked Regions feed it for global visibility.' Using Organizations integration to auto-enable members minimizes manual onboarding overhead. Option B introduces significant custom engineering and polling lag with no native normalization. Option C uses AWS Config Aggregator, which is designed for configuration and compliance data—not for aggregating GuardDuty, Inspector, or Macie threat/vulnerability findings. Option D relies on EventBridge forwarding but still requires manual normalization in Lambda, which the ASFF eliminates natively.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/securityhub-concepts.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Concepts and terminology (ASFF, cross-Region aggregation)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/finding-aggregation.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Cross-Region aggregation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/securityhub-accounts-orgs.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Integrating with AWS Organizations"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is building a multi-account AWS environment spanning five AWS Regions. The security team requires a single pane of glass for all security findings generated by GuardDuty, Amazon Inspector, and Amazon Macie across every account and Region. They also need findings normalized into a common schema so that downstream Lambda-based remediation functions do not have to handle product-specific formats. Which combination of actions BEST satisfies both requirements with the least operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An AWS Config rule named `s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited` is flagging dozens of S3 buckets as NON_COMPLIANT every time a developer accidentally enables public access. The security team wants to automatically remediate non-compliant buckets within minutes of detection without writing custom Lambda functions. Additionally, the same compliance posture must be enforced consistently across 30 AWS accounts in the organization. Which approach BEST meets these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an AWS Config conformance pack that bundles the `s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited` rule with an SSM Automation document remediation action, and deploy the conformance pack across all accounts in the organization via AWS Organizations."},{"id":"b","text":"Write a custom Lambda function triggered by CloudWatch Events that calls the S3 PutPublicAccessBlock API whenever it receives a Config compliance change notification, and manually deploy this Lambda to each of the 30 accounts."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable AWS Security Hub and create an automation rule that sets the finding severity to CRITICAL for any S3 public-access finding, then let the security team manually remediate each bucket."},{"id":"d","text":"Use an AWS Config Aggregator to view non-compliant resources centrally, then schedule a weekly AWS Systems Manager maintenance window to execute a runbook that blocks public access on identified buckets."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly describes AWS Config conformance packs as 'a bundle of Config rules + remediation actions for a compliance framework; deploy across accounts via Organizations' and notes that 'auto-remediation: trigger SSM Automation document when a rule is non-compliant.' A conformance pack combining the managed rule with an SSM Automation remediation satisfies both the automatic remediation and the multi-account consistency requirement in a single deployment operation. Option B achieves remediation but requires manually deploying the Lambda to 30 accounts, introducing significant operational overhead. Option C modifies finding severity in Security Hub but does not perform any actual remediation—it still requires manual action. Option D uses an aggregator for visibility and a maintenance window for remediation, but the weekly cadence violates the 'within minutes' requirement.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/conformance-packs.html","label":"AWS Config – Conformance packs"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/remediation.html","label":"AWS Config – Remediating noncompliant resources with auto-remediation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/conformance-pack-organization-apis.html","label":"AWS Config – Deploying conformance packs across an organization"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An AWS Config rule named `s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited` is flagging dozens of S3 buckets as NON_COMPLIANT every time a developer accidentally enables public access. The security team wants to automatically remediate non-compliant buckets within minutes of detection without writing custom Lambda functions. Additionally, the same compliance posture must be enforced consistently across 30 AWS accounts in the organization. Which approach BEST meets these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer needs to integrate automated policy validation into the CI/CD pipeline so that IAM policies with overly permissive cross-account access are rejected BEFORE they are deployed to production. The engineer also wants GuardDuty to alert the security team if an EC2 instance in production begins communicating with a known cryptocurrency mining endpoint after deployment. Which combination of AWS services and features BEST satisfies both the pre-deployment validation and the post-deployment detection requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use IAM Access Analyzer custom policy checks in the CI/CD pipeline to block policies that grant external access before deployment; enable Amazon GuardDuty (with VPC Flow Logs and DNS log analysis) in the production account to detect cryptocurrency mining communications after deployment."},{"id":"b","text":"Use AWS Security Hub automation rules in the CI/CD pipeline to evaluate IAM policies before deployment; rely on Amazon Macie to detect cryptocurrency mining network traffic after deployment."},{"id":"c","text":"Use Amazon Inspector in the CI/CD pipeline to scan IAM policy documents for external access grants before deployment; enable AWS Config rule `guardduty-enabled-centralized` to detect post-deployment threats."},{"id":"d","text":"Use AWS Config custom Lambda rules to evaluate IAM policies at deploy time; configure CloudTrail Insights to detect anomalous cryptocurrency API calls after deployment."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states that 'IAM Access Analyzer: validates resource-based policies; reports external/unused access; custom policy checks (in CI/CD before deploy)' — explicitly identifying CI/CD pre-deployment policy validation as a supported use case for Access Analyzer. For post-deployment detection, the source states that GuardDuty covers 'VPC Flow Logs, DNS logs, CloudTrail' and that finding categories include 'Cryptocurrency' — meaning GuardDuty is the correct service for detecting communication with cryptocurrency mining endpoints. Option B incorrectly assigns Security Hub (a findings aggregator, not a policy evaluator) to CI/CD validation, and Macie discovers sensitive data in S3 rather than analyzing network traffic. Option C misapplies Amazon Inspector, which scans for OS/code CVEs and container image vulnerabilities — not IAM policy logic. Option D's use of AWS Config Lambda rules could theoretically evaluate policies but adds significant custom engineering compared to the native Access Analyzer CI/CD integration, and CloudTrail Insights detects unusual management API activity, not network-level cryptocurrency mining communications.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/IAM/latest/UserGuide/access-analyzer-custom-policy-checks.html","label":"IAM Access Analyzer – Custom policy checks"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_finding-types-active.html","label":"Amazon GuardDuty – Finding types (CryptoCurrency)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_data-sources.html","label":"Amazon GuardDuty – Data sources (VPC Flow Logs, DNS logs)"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer needs to integrate automated policy validation into the CI/CD pipeline so that IAM policies with overly permissive cross-account access are rejected BEFORE they are deployed to production. The engineer also wants GuardDuty to alert the security team if an EC2 instance in production begins communicating with a known cryptocurrency mining endpoint after deployment. Which combination of AWS services and features BEST satisfies both the pre-deployment validation and the post-deployment detection requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a latency-sensitive e-commerce application on EC2. During peak shopping events, the application experiences sudden traffic spikes that exceed capacity before Auto Scaling can launch and configure new instances. The team wants to reduce scale-out latency without maintaining fully running standby instances. Which Auto Scaling feature BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure a Predictive Scaling policy trained on historical CloudWatch metrics to pre-provision capacity before anticipated demand peaks."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable a Warm Pool with instances in the Stopped state so that pre-initialized instances can be quickly activated during scale-out events."},{"id":"c","text":"Add a Lifecycle Hook in the Pending:Wait state to run a bootstrap script, ensuring instances are fully configured before receiving traffic."},{"id":"d","text":"Switch from a Target Tracking policy to a Step Scaling policy with more aggressive thresholds to trigger scale-out sooner."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Warm pools: pre-initialized instances in Stopped state for fast scale-out.' A Warm Pool solves the latency problem by keeping pre-bootstrapped instances in a Stopped state, allowing them to launch and become InService in significantly less time than cold-starting a brand-new instance. Option (a) — Predictive Scaling — forecasts and schedules capacity ahead of demand but relies on recurring, learnable patterns and still needs to launch and configure new instances. Option (c) — Lifecycle Hooks — actually introduce additional wait time during scale-out because the instance is held in Pending:Wait until the hook action completes, worsening latency. Option (d) — Step Scaling with aggressive thresholds — fires scale-out actions sooner but still requires a full instance launch and bootstrap, not addressing initialization latency.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/ec2-auto-scaling-warm-pools.html","label":"AWS EC2 Auto Scaling – Warm Pools"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/lifecycle-hooks.html","label":"AWS EC2 Auto Scaling – Lifecycle Hooks"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a latency-sensitive e-commerce application on EC2. During peak shopping events, the application experiences sudden traffic spikes that exceed capacity before Auto Scaling can launch and configure new instances. The team wants to reduce scale-out latency without maintaining fully running standby instances. Which Auto Scaling feature BEST addresses this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company runs a globally distributed SaaS application with an RDS Aurora MySQL primary cluster in us-east-1. Regulatory requirements mandate an RPO of no more than 1 second and an RTO of less than 1 minute for a regional failure. The database must remain writable in the failover region immediately after promotion. Which architecture BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Deploy an RDS Multi-AZ DB instance in us-east-1 with automated backups replicated to eu-west-1 using AWS Backup with cross-Region copy."},{"id":"b","text":"Create an Aurora Global Database with a secondary cluster in eu-west-1; use the Managed Planned Failover feature to promote the secondary within the SLA."},{"id":"c","text":"Deploy Aurora Read Replicas across 15 Availability Zones within us-east-1 and use Aurora Serverless v2 to auto-scale ACUs during failover."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable DynamoDB Global Tables in both us-east-1 and eu-west-1 and migrate the relational workload to DynamoDB to achieve active-active replication."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Aurora Global Database: cross-Region replicated cluster with <1s lag for DR.' An Aurora Global Database replicates data to a secondary Region with sub-second lag, directly satisfying the ≤1s RPO. When the secondary cluster is promoted during a regional failure, it becomes a fully writable primary, satisfying the writability requirement. The RTO of fast promotion (typically under 1 minute) meets the stated SLA. Option (a) — Multi-AZ with AWS Backup cross-Region copy — targets hours of RPO/RTO per the 'Backup & Restore' DR strategy described in the source, far exceeding the requirements. Option (c) — Aurora Read Replicas are in-region only (up to 15 in-region per the source) and do not provide cross-Region DR. Option (d) — DynamoDB Global Tables provide multi-Region active-active replication but require migrating away from a relational model, which is an architectural change outside the stated problem scope and may not satisfy relational consistency guarantees.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/AuroraUserGuide/aurora-global-database.html","label":"Amazon Aurora Global Database"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/disaster-recovery-workloads-on-aws/disaster-recovery-options-in-the-cloud.html","label":"AWS DR Strategies – RPO and RTO"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company runs a globally distributed SaaS application with an RDS Aurora MySQL primary cluster in us-east-1. Regulatory requirements mandate an RPO of no more than 1 second and an RTO of less than 1 minute for a regional failure. The database must remain writable in the failover region immediately after promotion. Which architecture BEST satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a Route 53 DNS architecture for an active-passive DR configuration. The primary stack runs in ap-southeast-1 and a Pilot Light DR stack runs in ap-northeast-1. The engineer must ensure that DNS automatically routes all traffic to the DR region only when the primary region's application endpoint becomes unhealthy. The DR stack must NOT receive any traffic under normal operating conditions. Which combination of Route 53 configurations satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create two Latency-based routing records — one for each region — and attach a Route 53 health check to the primary record. Route 53 will automatically remove the unhealthy primary and serve the DR record."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a Weighted routing policy with a weight of 100 for ap-southeast-1 and a weight of 0 for ap-northeast-1, and attach a health check to the primary record so that Route 53 skips the zero-weight record during failures."},{"id":"c","text":"Create a Failover routing policy with the ap-southeast-1 record set as PRIMARY and the ap-northeast-1 record set as SECONDARY, and attach a Route 53 health check to the PRIMARY record."},{"id":"d","text":"Create two Geolocation routing records scoped to all APAC countries — one for each region — and attach a health check to the primary record so that Route 53 falls back to the DR record on failure."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'DNS Failover for active-passive DR; latency for active-active.' The Route 53 Failover routing policy is explicitly designed for active-passive DR. The PRIMARY record serves all traffic under normal conditions; when its associated health check fails, Route 53 automatically routes all traffic to the SECONDARY record (the DR region). This guarantees zero traffic to the DR region unless the primary is unhealthy — precisely the stated requirement. Option (a) — Latency routing — is identified in the source as appropriate for active-active scenarios, not active-passive; both records would compete under normal conditions if both are healthy. Option (b) — Weighted routing with weight 0 — a zero-weight record is excluded from normal DNS responses, but the intended failover behavior is not deterministic when the primary is unhealthy; Weighted routing is not designed for active-passive health-check-driven failover. Option (d) — Geolocation routing — directs traffic based on the requestor's geographic location, not on endpoint health status as the primary decision driver; it does not guarantee that DR traffic is suppressed globally when the primary is healthy.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/dns-failover.html","label":"Amazon Route 53 – Configuring DNS Failover"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/routing-policy.html","label":"Amazon Route 53 – Choosing a Routing Policy"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/health-checks-types.html","label":"Amazon Route 53 – Health Checks Overview"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is designing a Route 53 DNS architecture for an active-passive DR configuration. The primary stack runs in ap-southeast-1 and a Pilot Light DR stack runs in ap-northeast-1. The engineer must ensure that DNS automatically routes all traffic to the DR region only when the primary region's application endpoint becomes unhealthy. The DR stack must NOT receive any traffic under normal operating conditions. Which combination of Route 53 configurations satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is ingesting high-frequency application metrics from a fleet of 500 EC2 instances. Each instance emits 50 distinct custom metrics every second. The team wants to minimize AWS costs and reduce the number of PutMetricData API calls while still making those metrics queryable in CloudWatch. Which approach best satisfies both requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Batch up to 1,000 data points per PutMetricData API call from each instance and send directly to CloudWatch every second."},{"id":"b","text":"Use the CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format (EMF) by writing structured JSON log lines to CloudWatch Logs; allow CloudWatch to automatically extract the metrics."},{"id":"c","text":"Publish metrics to Amazon Kinesis Data Streams and configure a Subscription Filter to forward them to CloudWatch."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable high-resolution custom metrics and use a CloudWatch Metric Filter on a log group to extract values."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Embedded Metric Format (EMF): structured JSON log line; CloudWatch automatically extracts metrics. Reduces API calls and cost.' By writing EMF-formatted JSON to CloudWatch Logs, the application avoids making individual PutMetricData API calls for every metric and instead piggybacks on the log ingestion pathway. CloudWatch then automatically extracts the declared metrics from the log data. Option A is expensive and does not reduce API calls — batching PutMetricData still counts as direct metric API usage. Option C is architecturally incorrect; Subscription Filters stream logs *out* of CloudWatch Logs to destinations like Kinesis, not the reverse. Option D conflates two valid but separate features: high-resolution metrics require PutMetricData, and Metric Filters extract metrics from log patterns but do not reduce the API overhead if PutMetricData is still used directly.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch_Embedded_Metric_Format_Specification.html","label":"CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format – Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/APIReference/API_PutMetricData.html","label":"PutMetricData API Reference"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is ingesting high-frequency application metrics from a fleet of 500 EC2 instances. Each instance emits 50 distinct custom metrics every second. The team wants to minimize AWS costs and reduce the number of PutMetricData API calls while still making those metrics queryable in CloudWatch. Which approach best satisfies both requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An operations team receives hundreds of individual CloudWatch alarms daily for a multi-tier application, resulting in significant alert fatigue. Many alarms fire simultaneously during a single underlying infrastructure event. The team wants a solution that pages on-call engineers only when a meaningful combination of alarms is breached — specifically, when BOTH the API error-rate alarm AND the database latency alarm are in ALARM state at the same time. Which CloudWatch feature should they implement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure an anomaly detection alarm that models the combined baseline of both metrics and fires when the band is breached."},{"id":"b","text":"Create a CloudWatch Composite Alarm using AND logic over the API error-rate alarm and the database latency alarm, and attach an SNS action to the composite alarm."},{"id":"c","text":"Use a CloudWatch metric math expression that multiplies the two metric values and create a threshold alarm on the resulting expression."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable CloudTrail Insights on the account to detect anomalous API activity and correlate it with CloudWatch alarms."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Composite alarms: AND/OR/NOT logic over child alarms; reduces alert fatigue.' A Composite Alarm allows the team to combine the API error-rate alarm and the database latency alarm with AND logic, so the composite alarm only enters ALARM state when both child alarms are simultaneously in ALARM. An SNS action on the composite alarm then pages on-call engineers exactly when the meaningful condition is met. Option A (anomaly detection) models a single metric's baseline and cannot natively combine two independent alarms with Boolean logic. Option C (metric math threshold) can correlate metrics numerically but does not prevent individual child alarms from firing and does not address the alert fatigue problem at the alarm-state level. Option D (CloudTrail Insights) detects anomalous management API call volumes and is unrelated to CloudWatch alarm aggregation or application-tier latency.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/Create_Composite_Alarm.html","label":"CloudWatch Composite Alarms"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/AlarmThatSendsEmail.html","label":"Using Alarm Actions with Amazon SNS"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An operations team receives hundreds of individual CloudWatch alarms daily for a multi-tier application, resulting in significant alert fatigue. Many alarms fire simultaneously during a single underlying infrastructure event. The team wants a solution that pages on-call engineers only when a meaningful combination of alarms is breached — specifically, when BOTH the API error-rate alarm AND the database latency alarm are in ALARM state at the same time. Which CloudWatch feature should they implement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security team needs to perform ad-hoc forensic investigations of AWS API activity across an entire AWS Organization spanning 40 member accounts. They require the ability to run complex SQL queries against historical CloudTrail event data without exporting log files to Athena or building a custom ETL pipeline. Which CloudTrail capability fulfills this requirement with the least operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable an Organization trail that delivers logs to a centralized S3 bucket, then create an AWS Glue crawler and query via Amazon Athena."},{"id":"b","text":"Configure CloudTrail Insights events on the Organization trail to surface anomalous API patterns and review them in the CloudTrail console."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable CloudTrail Lake with an organization-wide event data store and use its managed SQL query interface to investigate historical API events."},{"id":"d","text":"Stream CloudTrail logs to CloudWatch Logs and use CloudWatch Logs Insights with its query language to investigate API events across all accounts."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly describes: 'CloudTrail Lake: managed SQL-queryable event data store.' CloudTrail Lake ingests and retains CloudTrail events in a fully managed, immutable event data store and exposes a native SQL query engine — no S3 buckets, Glue crawlers, or Athena table definitions are required. It supports organization-wide event data stores that automatically collect events from all member accounts. Option A (S3 + Glue + Athena) achieves a similar analytical outcome but introduces significant operational overhead: bucket policies, Glue schema management, partition projection, and Athena query configuration. Option B (Insights events) detects statistical anomalies in management API call volumes automatically but is not a general-purpose SQL forensics tool and does not support arbitrary historical queries. Option D (CloudWatch Logs Insights) can query CloudTrail logs that have been forwarded to CloudWatch Logs, but this adds a forwarding integration layer, uses a proprietary query language (not SQL), and is not purpose-built for CloudTrail forensics at organization scale.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/awscloudtrail/latest/userguide/cloudtrail-lake.html","label":"AWS CloudTrail Lake – Overview"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/awscloudtrail/latest/userguide/query-event-data-store-organization.html","label":"Create an Event Data Store for an Organization"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security team needs to perform ad-hoc forensic investigations of AWS API activity across an entire AWS Organization spanning 40 member accounts. They require the ability to run complex SQL queries against historical CloudTrail event data without exporting log files to Athena or building a custom ETL pipeline. Which CloudTrail capability fulfills this requirement with the least operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is configuring AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager for a critical e-commerce platform. They want on-call responders to be automatically notified when a P1 incident is created, and if a responder does not acknowledge the notification within 10 minutes, the incident should escalate to a secondary contact. Which two Incident Manager constructs must be configured together to achieve this automated escalation behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A response plan that references an escalation plan, where the escalation plan defines the primary contact, a 10-minute acknowledgment timeout, and the secondary contact as the escalation stage."},{"id":"b","text":"An EventBridge rule with a rate(10 minutes) schedule that invokes a Lambda function to page the secondary contact if no acknowledgment token is found in DynamoDB."},{"id":"c","text":"An SNS topic with a subscription filter policy that re-publishes to a secondary SNS topic after a 10-minute delivery retry window elapses."},{"id":"d","text":"A CloudWatch alarm action that sends a notification to the primary contact and a separate alarm with a 10-minute evaluation period that notifies the secondary contact."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$According to the source material, Incident Manager supports 'contacts and escalation plans: schedule on-call rotations with primary, secondary contacts' and provides 'auto-escalate if not acknowledged within configurable timeouts.' The correct mechanism is a two-part configuration: (1) an escalation plan that chains a primary contact stage to a secondary contact stage with a configurable acknowledgment timeout, and (2) a response plan that references that escalation plan so it is invoked when an incident is created. Option B is incorrect because building a custom Lambda/DynamoDB polling loop is an anti-pattern when Incident Manager natively handles escalation. Option C is incorrect because SNS retry windows are for delivery failures, not acknowledgment timeouts, and SNS has no concept of incident acknowledgment. Option D is incorrect because chaining two CloudWatch alarms does not integrate with Incident Manager's contact/escalation model and cannot track per-responder acknowledgment.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/contacts.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Contacts and escalation plans"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/escalation.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Escalation plans"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/response-plans.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Response plans"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is configuring AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager for a critical e-commerce platform. They want on-call responders to be automatically notified when a P1 incident is created, and if a responder does not acknowledge the notification within 10 minutes, the incident should escalate to a secondary contact. Which two Incident Manager constructs must be configured together to achieve this automated escalation behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer receives an alert that Amazon GuardDuty has generated a HIGH severity finding indicating that an EC2 instance may be communicating with a known command-and-control server. The team's runbook requires that the compromised instance be automatically isolated by replacing its security group with a restrictive 'quarantine' security group, and that the on-call team be paged immediately. The solution must be fully automated with no manual steps. Which architecture satisfies these requirements with the least operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an EventBridge rule that matches GuardDuty HIGH severity findings. Configure two targets on the rule: (1) an SNS topic that pages the on-call contact, and (2) an SSM Automation runbook that performs the security-group swap to isolate the instance."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable GuardDuty export of findings to an S3 bucket. Create an S3 event notification that triggers a Lambda function to swap the security group and publish to SNS for on-call paging."},{"id":"c","text":"Create a CloudWatch metric filter on GuardDuty logs, trigger a CloudWatch alarm when the metric exceeds 0, and attach two alarm actions: one SNS notification and one SSM Run Command execution."},{"id":"d","text":"Poll the GuardDuty ListFindings API every minute using a scheduled Lambda function, evaluate severity, and if HIGH, call EC2 ModifyInstanceAttribute to change the security group and send an SMS via SNS."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'GuardDuty findings integrate with EventBridge: route HIGH severity finding -> SNS to on-call + Lambda to isolate compromised instance via security-group swap.' Extending this pattern, EventBridge rules support '5+ targets per rule,' allowing both an SNS notification target and an SSM Automation target to be configured on a single rule — achieving both remediation and notification with no manual steps and minimal operational overhead. Option B introduces unnecessary latency because S3 export of GuardDuty findings is not real-time; findings are exported periodically. Option C is incorrect because GuardDuty findings are not published as CloudWatch log streams suitable for metric filters; GuardDuty natively integrates with EventBridge. Option D is a polling anti-pattern that introduces up to a 1-minute delay, requires Lambda management, and is more operationally expensive than an event-driven rule.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_findings_cloudwatch.html","label":"Amazon GuardDuty – Automatically remediating findings with EventBridge"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/eventbridge/latest/userguide/eb-targets.html","label":"Amazon EventBridge – Targets"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/systems-manager/latest/userguide/systems-manager-automation.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Automation – Use Automation in an incident response runbook"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer receives an alert that Amazon GuardDuty has generated a HIGH severity finding indicating that an EC2 instance may be communicating with a known command-and-control server. The team's runbook requires that the compromised instance be automatically isolated by replacing its security group with a restrictive 'quarantine' security group, and that the on-call team be paged immediately. The solution must be fully automated with no manual steps. Which architecture satisfies these requirements with the least operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team uses AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager and wants to improve the fidelity of their post-incident reviews. After each incident, they need a structured artifact that captures the timeline of CloudWatch alarm state changes, which runbook steps executed, which contacts were engaged and when, and answers to custom retrospective questions defined by the team. Which Incident Manager feature directly provides this capability?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Incident Manager post-incident analysis, which produces a structured timeline of events, contact engagements, and runbook execution steps, and supports custom retrospective questions defined by the team."},{"id":"b","text":"AWS CloudTrail Lake, queried with Athena after each incident to reconstruct API-level events from Incident Manager, CloudWatch, and SSM into a single timeline report."},{"id":"c","text":"Amazon CloudWatch Contributor Insights rules configured to correlate alarm history, SSM Automation execution logs, and SNS delivery receipts into a unified dashboard."},{"id":"d","text":"An AWS Config aggregator that records configuration changes during the incident window, combined with an S3-exported Systems Manager OpsItem history for retrospective review."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material directly states: 'Post-incident analysis: structured timeline of events, contact engagements, and runbook execution; supports custom questions.' This is a native Incident Manager capability — not something that must be assembled from CloudTrail, CloudWatch, or Config. The post-incident analysis feature automatically correlates the incident timeline (alarm triggers, runbook steps, contact engagement timestamps) and allows teams to add custom retrospective questions (e.g., 'What was the customer impact?' or 'How could detection be faster?'). Option B requires manual query construction in Athena and does not natively support custom retrospective questions or contact engagement correlation. Option C conflates CloudWatch Contributor Insights, which analyzes log data for top contributors, with incident retrospective capabilities it does not possess. Option D describes AWS Config's change-tracking capability, which records resource configuration snapshots but cannot reconstruct a human-readable incident timeline or support custom post-mortem questions.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/analysis.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Post-incident analysis"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/tracking-details.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Incident details and timeline"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P6'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team uses AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager and wants to improve the fidelity of their post-incident reviews. After each incident, they need a structured artifact that captures the timeline of CloudWatch alarm state changes, which runbook steps executed, which contacts were engaged and when, and answers to custom retrospective questions defined by the team. Which Incident Manager feature directly provides this capability?$patch$);

-- DOP-C02-P7: 15 new questions
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is building a centralized security operations pipeline on AWS. They want Security Hub to automatically update the workflow status of any finding that has a normalized severity label of INFORMATIONAL and originates from AWS Config to 'SUPPRESSED', without requiring manual triage. Which Security Hub feature should they configure to accomplish this with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Create an EventBridge rule that matches Security Hub findings with severity INFORMATIONAL and source AWS Config, then invoke a Lambda function that calls the Security Hub BatchUpdateFindings API to set WorkflowStatus to SUPPRESSED."},{"id":"b","text":"Configure a Security Hub Automation Rule with criteria matching NormalizedSeverityLabel = INFORMATIONAL and ProductName = 'Config', and set the action to update WorkflowStatus to SUPPRESSED."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable a Security Hub custom insight that filters on severity INFORMATIONAL and product AWS Config, then schedule a Lambda function via EventBridge Scheduler to call BatchUpdateFindings every 15 minutes."},{"id":"d","text":"Deploy an AWS Config remediation action using an SSM Automation document that sets the Security Hub WorkflowStatus field to SUPPRESSED whenever the rule evaluation is NON_COMPLIANT with low severity."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Security Hub Automation Rules (introduced as GA in 2023) allow you to define criteria-based rules that automatically modify finding fields — including WorkflowStatus — the moment a finding is ingested or updated, without any custom Lambda code or scheduling. The source material explicitly states: 'Automation rules: auto-modify or suppress findings (e.g., set severity to INFORMATIONAL based on criteria).' This makes option B the lowest-overhead choice. Option A is functionally possible but requires authoring and maintaining Lambda code plus an EventBridge rule, incurring more operational overhead than a native Automation Rule. Option C misuses Custom Insights (which are saved filters/aggregations for dashboards, not action triggers) and adds unnecessary scheduling complexity. Option D is incorrect because SSM Automation documents operate on AWS Config remediation targets (AWS resources), not on Security Hub finding metadata fields.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/automation-rules.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Automation Rules"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/APIReference/API_BatchUpdateFindings.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – BatchUpdateFindings API"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is building a centralized security operations pipeline on AWS. They want Security Hub to automatically update the workflow status of any finding that has a normalized severity label of INFORMATIONAL and originates from AWS Config to 'SUPPRESSED', without requiring manual triage. Which Security Hub feature should they configure to accomplish this with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$An enterprise organization has 40 AWS accounts managed through AWS Organizations. The security team needs to enforce a compliance baseline based on PCI DSS across all accounts and automatically remediate non-compliant S3 buckets that have public read access enabled. They want to deploy and manage this at scale from the management account with minimal per-account configuration. Which combination of AWS services and features best satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable AWS Security Hub in each account with the PCI DSS security standard, then create per-account EventBridge rules invoking Lambda functions to remediate non-compliant S3 buckets."},{"id":"b","text":"Deploy an AWS Config Conformance Pack that includes the 's3-bucket-public-read-prohibited' managed rule with an associated SSM Automation remediation action, distributing it to all accounts via AWS Organizations from the management account."},{"id":"c","text":"Use AWS Macie across all accounts to detect public S3 buckets and configure Macie findings to trigger an EventBridge rule that calls a Lambda function to disable public access."},{"id":"d","text":"Create a Service Control Policy (SCP) that denies the s3:PutBucketAcl action on all accounts to prevent public ACLs, and use an AWS Config aggregator to report compliance status to the management account."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material directly states: 'Conformance Packs: bundle of Config rules + remediation actions for a compliance framework; deploy across accounts via Organizations.' It also cites 's3-bucket-public-read-prohibited' as an example managed rule, and notes 'Auto-remediation: trigger SSM Automation document when a rule is non-compliant.' Deploying a Conformance Pack from the management account via Organizations is the purpose-built mechanism for this exact use case — scalable, centralized, and requiring no per-account setup beyond delegated administrator configuration. Option A uses Security Hub's PCI DSS standard for detection but requires per-account EventBridge and Lambda setup, adding operational overhead. Option C is incorrect because Macie is focused on sensitive data discovery (PII, financial data) in S3 content, not bucket-level ACL/public access policy compliance, as stated in the source material. Option D's SCP approach is preventative but not remediative for already non-compliant buckets; it also does not include automated remediation for existing misconfigurations, and an aggregator alone does not remediate.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/conformance-packs.html","label":"AWS Config – Conformance Packs"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/conformance-pack-organization-apis.html","label":"AWS Config – Deploying Conformance Packs Across an Organization"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/config/latest/developerguide/s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited.html","label":"AWS Config – s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited Managed Rule"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$An enterprise organization has 40 AWS accounts managed through AWS Organizations. The security team needs to enforce a compliance baseline based on PCI DSS across all accounts and automatically remediate non-compliant S3 buckets that have public read access enabled. They want to deploy and manage this at scale from the management account with minimal per-account configuration. Which combination of AWS services and features best satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security engineer receives an Amazon GuardDuty finding of type 'UnauthorizedAccess:IAMUser/InstanceCredentialExfiltration.OutsideAWS' in a production account. This finding indicates that temporary credentials issued by an EC2 instance profile are being used from an IP address outside of AWS infrastructure. As a DevOps Engineer, which sequence of actions represents the MOST appropriate immediate and automated incident response for this finding type using native AWS integrations?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure an EventBridge rule matching the GuardDuty finding type, invoke an SSM Automation document that isolates the EC2 instance by replacing its security group with a deny-all group and attaches a resource-based IAM policy to revoke all active sessions for the instance profile role, then notify the security team via SNS."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable GuardDuty Malware Protection to scan the EBS volume of the affected instance, wait for the scan report, and then manually decide whether to isolate the instance based on the malware findings."},{"id":"c","text":"Forward the GuardDuty finding to Security Hub, create a Security Hub custom insight to track InstanceCredentialExfiltration findings, and generate a weekly report for the security team to review and take action."},{"id":"d","text":"Use Amazon Macie to scan the S3 buckets accessed by the exfiltrated credentials for sensitive data exposure, then revoke the IAM role manually after the Macie job completes."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'EventBridge integration: trigger automated responses to specific findings (Lambda, SSM Automation, SNS).' GuardDuty's finding category 'UnauthorizedAccess' (which covers InstanceCredentialExfiltration) represents an active threat requiring immediate automated containment, not deferred review. Option A correctly uses the native EventBridge → SSM Automation pipeline to perform real-time isolation (security group swap to deny-all, IAM policy to revoke active sessions via an explicit deny with a date condition on aws:TokenIssueTime) and concurrent SNS notification — all without human-in-the-loop delay. Option B is incorrect because GuardDuty Malware Protection (EBS volume scanning) addresses a different threat vector (malicious files on disk) and does not address the immediate risk of exfiltrated credentials being actively used outside AWS; waiting for a scan result delays critical containment. Option C converts an active incident into a passive reporting workflow, which is inappropriate for a credential exfiltration event; Security Hub custom insights are dashboarding tools, not response mechanisms. Option D misapplies Macie, which is designed for sensitive data discovery in S3 content, not for incident response or IAM credential revocation, and adds an unnecessary sequential dependency that delays containment.$patch$, $patch$Security and Compliance$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_finding-types-iam.html#unauthorizedaccess-iam-instancecredentialexfiltrationoutsideaws","label":"Amazon GuardDuty – Finding Types: UnauthorizedAccess:IAMUser/InstanceCredentialExfiltration.OutsideAWS"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/securityhub/latest/userguide/securityhub-cloudwatch-events.html","label":"AWS Security Hub – Automated Response and Remediation"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/aws-security-incident-response-guide/credential-compromise.html","label":"AWS Security Incident Response Guide – Credential Compromise"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security engineer receives an Amazon GuardDuty finding of type 'UnauthorizedAccess:IAMUser/InstanceCredentialExfiltration.OutsideAWS' in a production account. This finding indicates that temporary credentials issued by an EC2 instance profile are being used from an IP address outside of AWS infrastructure. As a DevOps Engineer, which sequence of actions represents the MOST appropriate immediate and automated incident response for this finding type using native AWS integrations?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a critical e-commerce application on AWS. The application must be able to recover from a Regional failure with a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of under 5 minutes and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) as close to zero as possible, while minimizing cost compared to running full capacity in two Regions simultaneously. Which disaster recovery strategy best meets these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Backup & Restore: Use AWS Backup with cross-Region copy to replicate all data hourly, and provision resources in the DR Region only after a failure is declared."},{"id":"b","text":"Pilot Light: Keep only the core database tier (e.g., Aurora Global Database) running in the DR Region, and use automation to provision the compute tier on failover."},{"id":"c","text":"Warm Standby: Maintain a scaled-down but fully functional stack in the DR Region with Aurora Global Database replication and Route 53 Failover routing, scaling up compute on failover."},{"id":"d","text":"Multi-Site Active-Active: Run full capacity in both Regions at all times with DynamoDB Global Tables and Route 53 Latency routing."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The Warm Standby strategy keeps a scaled-down but fully functional application stack continuously running in the DR Region, enabling failover in minutes rather than hours. As stated in the source: 'Warm Standby: scaled-down active stack in DR; minutes of RTO.' Aurora Global Database provides cross-Region replication with less than 1 second of replication lag, supporting a near-zero RPO. Route 53 Failover routing with health checks automatically redirects traffic when the primary Region fails. This approach is less expensive than Multi-Site Active-Active (option D), which runs full capacity in both Regions simultaneously and achieves near-zero RTO/RPO but at significantly higher cost. Backup & Restore (option A) yields hours of RTO/RPO — far too slow. Pilot Light (option B) only keeps the minimal core running and still requires provisioning compute on failover, resulting in hours of RTO, which violates the 5-minute RTO requirement.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/whitepapers/latest/disaster-recovery-workloads-on-aws/disaster-recovery-options-in-the-cloud.html","label":"AWS Disaster Recovery – Strategies"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonRDS/latest/AuroraUserGuide/aurora-global-database.html","label":"Amazon Aurora Global Database"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/Route53/latest/DeveloperGuide/routing-policy-failover.html","label":"Route 53 Failover Routing Policy"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a critical e-commerce application on AWS. The application must be able to recover from a Regional failure with a Recovery Time Objective (RTO) of under 5 minutes and a Recovery Point Objective (RPO) as close to zero as possible, while minimizing cost compared to running full capacity in two Regions simultaneously. Which disaster recovery strategy best meets these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company runs a fleet of EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling Group that processes jobs from an SQS queue. The operations team has observed that when the ASG scales in, in-flight job processing is interrupted because instances are terminated before they finish their work. The jobs take up to 8 minutes to complete. Which ASG feature should the DevOps engineer configure to allow instances to finish processing before being terminated?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure a Warm Pool with instances in the Stopped state so that new instances are always pre-initialized and replace terminating instances instantly."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable Capacity Rebalancing on the Auto Scaling Group to proactively replace at-risk instances before they are interrupted."},{"id":"c","text":"Add a Terminating:Wait lifecycle hook with a heartbeat timeout greater than 8 minutes, and emit CompleteLifecycleAction from the instance after the job finishes."},{"id":"d","text":"Switch from a Target Tracking scaling policy to a Step Scaling policy to slow down the scale-in rate and give instances more time to finish work."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$Lifecycle hooks pause instance transitions to allow custom actions to complete. The source states: 'Lifecycle hooks: Pending:Wait and Terminating:Wait states; perform actions (bootstrap, drain) before transition; emit CompleteLifecycleAction to proceed.' By configuring a Terminating:Wait hook with a heartbeat timeout longer than the maximum job duration (8 minutes), the instance remains in the Wait state while it finishes processing. Once complete, it signals CompleteLifecycleAction to allow the termination to proceed normally. Option A (Warm Pool) addresses scale-out latency, not graceful scale-in. Option B (Capacity Rebalancing) is specifically for proactively replacing at-risk Spot instances before an interruption notice, not for graceful shutdown of work. Option D (Step Scaling) merely changes when scaling actions are triggered — it does not guarantee instances finish their in-flight work before termination.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/lifecycle-hooks.html","label":"Amazon EC2 Auto Scaling Lifecycle Hooks"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/APIReference/API_CompleteLifecycleAction.html","label":"CompleteLifecycleAction API Reference"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company runs a fleet of EC2 instances in an Auto Scaling Group that processes jobs from an SQS queue. The operations team has observed that when the ASG scales in, in-flight job processing is interrupted because instances are terminated before they finish their work. The jobs take up to 8 minutes to complete. Which ASG feature should the DevOps engineer configure to allow instances to finish processing before being terminated?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A global SaaS company replicates objects from an S3 bucket in us-east-1 to a bucket in eu-west-1 using S3 Cross-Region Replication (CRR). A compliance audit requires that 99.99% of new objects must be replicated to the destination bucket within 15 minutes, and the team must be able to monitor replication progress through CloudWatch metrics. Which S3 replication feature must be enabled to satisfy the compliance requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Enable S3 Same-Region Replication (SRR) in addition to CRR to create a local redundant copy, reducing overall replication time."},{"id":"b","text":"Enable S3 Replication Time Control (RTC) on the CRR rule, which provides an SLA guaranteeing that 99.99% of objects are replicated within 15 minutes along with replication metrics."},{"id":"c","text":"Configure an S3 Lifecycle policy on the source bucket to transition objects to S3 Standard-IA immediately, which reduces object size and accelerates cross-Region transfer."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable S3 Transfer Acceleration on both source and destination buckets to speed up the CRR data transfer path."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$S3 Replication Time Control (RTC) is the only S3 replication feature that provides a defined SLA for replication completion time. As stated directly in the source material: 'S3 Replication: CRR (cross-Region), SRR (same-Region), RTC (Replication Time Control SLA = 15 min for 99.99%).' RTC also publishes replication metrics to Amazon CloudWatch so teams can monitor replication lag and pending bytes, directly satisfying the audit's monitoring requirement. Option A (SRR) creates a same-Region copy and does not accelerate or provide an SLA for the cross-Region replication. Option C (Lifecycle policy to Standard-IA) transitions storage classes for cost optimization and has no effect on replication speed or SLA. Option D (Transfer Acceleration) is designed to speed up direct client uploads to S3 using CloudFront edge locations; it is not a replication feature and does not apply to CRR.$patch$, $patch$Resilient Cloud Solutions$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/replication-time-control.html","label":"S3 Replication Time Control (RTC)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonS3/latest/userguide/replication-metrics.html","label":"Monitoring S3 Replication with CloudWatch Metrics"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A global SaaS company replicates objects from an S3 bucket in us-east-1 to a bucket in eu-west-1 using S3 Cross-Region Replication (CRR). A compliance audit requires that 99.99% of new objects must be replicated to the destination bucket within 15 minutes, and the team must be able to monitor replication progress through CloudWatch metrics. Which S3 replication feature must be enabled to satisfy the compliance requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is operating a high-throughput microservices application on AWS. They publish custom CloudWatch metrics using the PutMetricData API but are experiencing throttling errors and increased costs as traffic grows. An engineer proposes switching to Embedded Metric Format (EMF). Which statement BEST describes why EMF reduces both API call volume and cost compared to direct PutMetricData calls?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"EMF compresses metric payloads using gzip before sending them to the PutMetricData endpoint, reducing the number of required API calls."},{"id":"b","text":"EMF embeds metrics as structured JSON inside log events; CloudWatch automatically extracts the metrics from the logs, eliminating the need for separate PutMetricData API calls entirely."},{"id":"c","text":"EMF batches PutMetricData calls into groups of 1,000 data points per request, staying within the API limit and thereby reducing throttling."},{"id":"d","text":"EMF routes metric data through Amazon Kinesis Data Firehose, which buffers and delivers metrics in bulk to CloudWatch at a lower cost tier."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Embedded Metric Format (EMF): structured JSON log line; CloudWatch automatically extracts metrics. Reduces API calls and cost.' By writing metric data as structured JSON embedded within CloudWatch Logs log events, applications avoid making any PutMetricData API calls at all — CloudWatch parses the EMF-formatted log entries and creates the metrics automatically. This eliminates the separate API call overhead and the associated throttling risk. Option A is incorrect because EMF does not rely on gzip compression of PutMetricData payloads. Option C describes standard PutMetricData batching (up to 1,000 data points per call), which is a real limit but is not the EMF mechanism. Option D is incorrect; EMF writes to CloudWatch Logs directly, not through Kinesis Data Firehose.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch_Embedded_Metric_Format_Specification.html","label":"AWS Docs – CloudWatch Embedded Metric Format"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/APIReference/API_PutMetricData.html","label":"AWS Docs – PutMetricData API Reference"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is operating a high-throughput microservices application on AWS. They publish custom CloudWatch metrics using the PutMetricData API but are experiencing throttling errors and increased costs as traffic grows. An engineer proposes switching to Embedded Metric Format (EMF). Which statement BEST describes why EMF reduces both API call volume and cost compared to direct PutMetricData calls?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A company runs a multi-account AWS environment with dozens of production accounts managed under AWS Organizations. The central operations team wants to query CloudWatch Logs Insights data from all production accounts in a single console without aggregating logs into a central S3 bucket. Which CloudWatch feature should the DevOps engineer configure to meet this requirement with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure a CloudWatch Logs subscription filter in each source account to stream log events to a Kinesis Data Stream in the central monitoring account, then query the stream using CloudWatch Logs Insights."},{"id":"b","text":"Deploy a Lambda function in each source account that periodically copies log groups to the central monitoring account's CloudWatch Logs, and run Logs Insights queries from there."},{"id":"c","text":"Enable CloudWatch cross-account observability using AWS Organizations to link all production source accounts to a central monitoring account, then run CloudWatch Logs Insights queries across all linked accounts from the monitoring account."},{"id":"d","text":"Enable CloudTrail Lake in the central account and configure it to ingest CloudWatch Logs from all organization accounts, then use CloudTrail Lake's SQL queries instead of Logs Insights."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["c"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Cross-account observability: monitor multiple source accounts from one monitoring account; via AWS Organizations or per-account links.' This feature natively allows a designated monitoring account to query CloudWatch Logs Insights (and view metrics and traces) across all linked source accounts without copying or exporting data, which directly satisfies the requirement of no S3 aggregation and minimal operational overhead. Option A involves Kinesis Data Streams which does not feed back into Logs Insights as a query source and introduces significant pipeline complexity. Option B requires custom Lambda logic, adding operational overhead. Option D conflates CloudTrail Lake (designed for API audit events) with CloudWatch Logs, making it an inappropriate tool for this use case.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/monitoring/CloudWatch-Unified-Cross-Account.html","label":"AWS Docs – CloudWatch Cross-Account Observability"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AmazonCloudWatch/latest/logs/CWL_QuerySyntax.html","label":"AWS Docs – CloudWatch Logs Insights Query Syntax"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A company runs a multi-account AWS environment with dozens of production accounts managed under AWS Organizations. The central operations team wants to query CloudWatch Logs Insights data from all production accounts in a single console without aggregating logs into a central S3 bucket. Which CloudWatch feature should the DevOps engineer configure to meet this requirement with the LEAST operational overhead?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps engineer is troubleshooting an intermittent latency spike in a distributed application that spans an Application Load Balancer, three Lambda functions, and two Amazon DynamoDB tables. The engineer needs to identify which specific downstream call is introducing the latency. X-Ray tracing is enabled on all components. The engineer reviews the X-Ray service map but needs to drill deeper into the individual unit of work at the Lambda level. Which X-Ray concept represents the granular unit that captures a discrete downstream call — such as a DynamoDB GetItem operation — WITHIN a single Lambda function's execution?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Segment — the primary record that represents all work done by a single service or application node, including all downstream calls."},{"id":"b","text":"Subsegment — a child record within a segment that captures data about a specific downstream call or internal operation, such as a DynamoDB GetItem request."},{"id":"c","text":"Sampling rule — the configuration that determines which requests are traced and therefore controls the granularity of latency data captured."},{"id":"d","text":"Annotation — a key-value pair indexed for use with filter expressions that is attached to a segment to tag the DynamoDB table name and operation type."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Segments (service work) and subsegments (downstream calls).' A segment represents all the work performed by a single service (e.g., an entire Lambda invocation), while a subsegment captures a discrete downstream call within that segment — precisely the granularity needed to isolate a DynamoDB GetItem latency spike from other operations within the same Lambda function. Option A is incorrect because a segment encompasses the entire Lambda function execution, including all its downstream calls, so it is too coarse to isolate a single DynamoDB operation. Option C describes a sampling rule, which governs whether a request is traced at all and does not represent a unit of work. Option D describes an annotation, which is metadata used for filtering traces rather than a structural unit that captures timing and latency for a downstream call.$patch$, $patch$Monitoring and Logging$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/xray/latest/devguide/xray-concepts.html","label":"AWS Docs – AWS X-Ray Concepts (Segments and Subsegments)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/xray/latest/devguide/xray-api-segmentdocuments.html","label":"AWS Docs – X-Ray Segment Documents"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps engineer is troubleshooting an intermittent latency spike in a distributed application that spans an Application Load Balancer, three Lambda functions, and two Amazon DynamoDB tables. The engineer needs to identify which specific downstream call is introducing the latency. X-Ray tracing is enabled on all components. The engineer reviews the X-Ray service map but needs to drill deeper into the individual unit of work at the Lambda level. Which X-Ray concept represents the granular unit that captures a discrete downstream call — such as a DynamoDB GetItem operation — WITHIN a single Lambda function's execution?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is configuring AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager for a production workload. They need to ensure that if the primary on-call engineer does not acknowledge a page within 10 minutes, a secondary engineer is automatically notified. Which Incident Manager component should the team configure to satisfy this requirement?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A response plan with a linked SSM Automation runbook that polls for acknowledgment and triggers an SNS notification after a 10-minute delay."},{"id":"b","text":"An escalation plan that defines primary and secondary contacts with a configurable acknowledgment timeout, then associates the escalation plan with the response plan's engagement contacts."},{"id":"c","text":"A CloudWatch alarm action that publishes to two separate SNS topics in sequence, with a 10-minute delay inserted via an EventBridge scheduled rule between publications."},{"id":"d","text":"An AWS Chatbot channel configuration that retries the Slack notification every 10 minutes until a responder clicks the acknowledgment button in the chat channel."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Contacts and escalation plans: schedule on-call rotations with primary, secondary contacts; channels = email, SMS, voice' and 'Engagement: notify on-call responders; auto-escalate if not acknowledged within configurable timeouts.' An escalation plan is the correct Incident Manager construct that defines the sequence of contacts and the timeout window before automatically escalating to the next contact. The escalation plan is then referenced in the response plan's engagement section. Option A misuses a runbook for what is a built-in escalation feature. Option C introduces unnecessary EventBridge scheduling complexity and cannot track incident acknowledgment state. Option D describes AWS Chatbot behavior, which does not natively manage acknowledgment-based escalation timeouts within Incident Manager.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/escalation.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Escalation plans"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/response-plans.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Response plans"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is configuring AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager for a production workload. They need to ensure that if the primary on-call engineer does not acknowledge a page within 10 minutes, a secondary engineer is automatically notified. Which Incident Manager component should the team configure to satisfy this requirement?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security operations team receives Amazon GuardDuty findings of HIGH severity and wants to automatically isolate the affected EC2 instance by replacing its security group with a quarantine security group, while simultaneously paging the on-call team via SNS. An EventBridge rule already matches HIGH-severity GuardDuty findings. What is the MOST operationally efficient configuration of the EventBridge rule's targets to achieve both goals in a single rule?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Configure a single Lambda function as the only target. Inside the function, call the EC2 ModifyInstanceAttribute API to swap the security group, then publish a message to the SNS topic."},{"id":"b","text":"Configure two targets on the same EventBridge rule: (1) an AWS Lambda function that calls EC2 ModifyInstanceAttribute to swap the security group, and (2) an SNS topic that notifies the on-call team — both triggered simultaneously by the same matching event."},{"id":"c","text":"Configure the EventBridge rule to invoke an SSM Automation runbook as the sole target, and add a step in the runbook that publishes to SNS before executing the security-group swap."},{"id":"d","text":"Create two separate EventBridge rules with the same event pattern — one targeting Lambda for isolation and one targeting SNS for notification — because EventBridge rules can have only one target each."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'Rules: event pattern (match) or schedule (cron/rate); 5+ targets per rule' and 'GuardDuty findings integrate with EventBridge: route HIGH severity finding -> SNS to on-call + Lambda to isolate compromised instance via security-group swap.' This confirms that a single EventBridge rule can fan out to multiple targets simultaneously, making option B the most operationally efficient solution — both the isolation Lambda and the SNS notification fire in parallel from one rule. Option A works but introduces unnecessary coupling and sequential logic inside a single Lambda. Option C is valid but adds runbook overhead for a two-step action that EventBridge can handle natively. Option D is factually incorrect: EventBridge supports 5 or more targets per rule, so splitting into two rules is unnecessary and adds management overhead.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/eventbridge/latest/userguide/eb-targets.html","label":"Amazon EventBridge – Targets for rules"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/guardduty/latest/ug/guardduty_findings_cloudwatch.html","label":"Amazon GuardDuty – EventBridge integration"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/what-is-incident-manager.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Incident response integrations"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security operations team receives Amazon GuardDuty findings of HIGH severity and wants to automatically isolate the affected EC2 instance by replacing its security group with a quarantine security group, while simultaneously paging the on-call team via SNS. An EventBridge rule already matches HIGH-severity GuardDuty findings. What is the MOST operationally efficient configuration of the EventBridge rule's targets to achieve both goals in a single rule?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$After resolving a Sev-1 database outage, the engineering team is required to conduct a formal post-incident analysis within AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager. A junior engineer asks which capabilities are available natively within the Incident Manager post-incident analysis feature. Which of the following BEST describes what the native post-incident analysis in Incident Manager provides?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"A structured timeline of events, contact engagements, and runbook execution steps captured during the incident, combined with support for custom questions to guide the retrospective discussion."},{"id":"b","text":"An automatically generated root-cause analysis (RCA) document produced by Amazon CodeGuru that identifies the exact line of code responsible for the incident."},{"id":"c","text":"A compliance audit report in PDF format exported to Amazon S3 that maps each incident action to a specific AWS Well-Architected Framework pillar for regulatory review."},{"id":"d","text":"An Amazon QuickSight dashboard auto-provisioned from incident metrics, showing MTTR trends and responder SLA adherence over the past 90 days."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states directly: 'Post-incident analysis: structured timeline of events, contact engagements, and runbook execution; supports custom questions.' This precisely matches option A. Incident Manager natively captures the sequence of incident events, which contacts were engaged and when, which runbook steps were executed, and allows teams to add custom retrospective questions — all within the analysis feature. Option B is incorrect; CodeGuru is a separate code review and profiling tool and does not integrate with Incident Manager post-incident analysis. Option C is incorrect; Incident Manager does not generate Well-Architected compliance PDF exports. Option D is incorrect; QuickSight dashboards are not auto-provisioned by Incident Manager and are not part of its native analysis feature.$patch$, $patch$Incident and Event Response$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/analysis.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – Post-incident analysis"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/incident-manager/latest/userguide/what-is-incident-manager.html","label":"AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager – What is Incident Manager?"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$After resolving a Sev-1 database outage, the engineering team is required to conduct a formal post-incident analysis within AWS Systems Manager Incident Manager. A junior engineer asks which capabilities are available natively within the Incident Manager post-incident analysis feature. Which of the following BEST describes what the native post-incident analysis in Incident Manager provides?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a CloudFormation stack that provisions an Auto Scaling Group (ASG) running a complex application. The team wants CloudFormation to pause and wait for the application to fully initialize on each new instance before marking the stack as CREATE_COMPLETE. Which combination of CloudFormation features must be configured to achieve this behavior?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Add a CreationPolicy with a ResourceSignal count and timeout to the ASG resource, and configure the EC2 UserData to invoke cfn-signal after the application starts successfully."},{"id":"b","text":"Add a DeletionPolicy of Retain to the ASG resource and use an AWS::CloudFormation::WaitCondition resource to block stack completion."},{"id":"c","text":"Configure an UpdatePolicy with AutoScalingRollingUpdate on the ASG resource and set MinSuccessfulInstancesPercent to 100."},{"id":"d","text":"Create a Custom Resource backed by a Lambda function that polls the ASG's health checks and returns a success signal to CloudFormation when all instances are healthy."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'CreationPolicy with cfn-signal: wait for app startup before CREATE_COMPLETE.' The correct pattern is to attach a CreationPolicy (with ResourceSignal specifying Count and Timeout) directly to the ASG resource in the template, then have each instance run cfn-signal via UserData or cfn-init to notify CloudFormation of successful startup. CloudFormation will hold the stack in CREATE_IN_PROGRESS until the required number of signals are received or the timeout expires. Option B is incorrect: DeletionPolicy controls what happens when a resource is deleted, not during creation, and WaitCondition is a separate mechanism not specifically designed for ASG instance readiness. Option C is incorrect: UpdatePolicy.AutoScalingRollingUpdate governs rolling updates during stack updates, not the initial creation signal flow. Option D is incorrect: while a Custom Resource could theoretically do this, it is not the purpose-built mechanism; CreationPolicy + cfn-signal is the idiomatic and documented approach for this exact use case.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-attribute-creationpolicy.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – CreationPolicy Attribute"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/cfn-signal.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – cfn-signal Helper Script"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A DevOps team is deploying a CloudFormation stack that provisions an Auto Scaling Group (ASG) running a complex application. The team wants CloudFormation to pause and wait for the application to fully initialize on each new instance before marking the stack as CREATE_COMPLETE. Which combination of CloudFormation features must be configured to achieve this behavior?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A platform engineering team manages hundreds of AWS accounts through AWS Organizations. They must deploy a standardized CloudFormation stack—containing VPC, logging, and security baselines—to every account in specific Organizational Units (OUs), including all accounts added to those OUs in the future. The solution must minimize ongoing operational overhead. Which approach best satisfies these requirements?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Use CloudFormation StackSets with service-managed permissions targeting the specific OUs, and enable automatic deployment so new accounts added to those OUs receive the stack automatically."},{"id":"b","text":"Write an AWS Lambda function triggered by CloudTrail events for account creation, which calls cloudformation:CreateStack in each new account using cross-account IAM roles."},{"id":"c","text":"Store the CloudFormation template in S3 and use AWS Systems Manager State Manager associations scheduled hourly to run a Run Command document that deploys the stack in each account."},{"id":"d","text":"Use CloudFormation Nested Stacks to embed the VPC, logging, and security templates under a root stack, then manually deploy the root stack to each account."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["a"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material explicitly states: 'StackSets: deploy across multiple accounts and regions from one admin account; uses AWS Organizations service-managed permissions.' With service-managed permissions, StackSets integrates natively with AWS Organizations, allowing you to target entire OUs and enable the 'Automatic Deployment' option so that any account subsequently added to a targeted OU automatically receives a stack instance—directly addressing the zero-touch ongoing overhead requirement. Option B could work but introduces significant undifferentiated operational complexity (Lambda maintenance, IAM role management, error handling, idempotency) versus the purpose-built StackSets feature. Option C misuses State Manager, which is designed for OS/application configuration enforcement, not CloudFormation stack deployment orchestration across accounts. Option D uses Nested Stacks, which is a within-account code-reuse pattern, not a multi-account deployment mechanism; 'manually deploy' also contradicts the low-overhead requirement.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/stacksets-orgs-enable-trusted-access.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – StackSets with AWS Organizations (Service-Managed Permissions)"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/stacksets-concepts.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – StackSets Concepts"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A platform engineering team manages hundreds of AWS accounts through AWS Organizations. They must deploy a standardized CloudFormation stack—containing VPC, logging, and security baselines—to every account in specific Organizational Units (OUs), including all accounts added to those OUs in the future. The solution must minimize ongoing operational overhead. Which approach best satisfies these requirements?$patch$);
INSERT INTO "Question" (id, "examId", stem, type, options, correct, explanation, domain, difficulty, "references", status, "generatedBy", "isTeaser", "createdAt", "updatedAt")
  SELECT gen_random_uuid()::text, e.id, $patch$A security team requires that a CloudFormation-managed RDS database cluster always pulls its master password from AWS Secrets Manager at deploy time, without hardcoding any credentials in the template or in CloudFormation parameters. The solution must also automatically reflect password rotations without requiring a template update. Which CloudFormation feature should the DevOps engineer use in the template?$patch$, 'SINGLE'::"QType",
         $json$[{"id":"a","text":"Store the password in an SSM Parameter Store SecureString parameter and reference it with a dynamic reference using the syntax {{resolve:ssm-secure:/rds/master-password:1}} in the template."},{"id":"b","text":"Store the password in AWS Secrets Manager and reference it with a dynamic reference using the syntax {{resolve:secretsmanager:rds-master-secret:SecretString:password}} in the template property."},{"id":"c","text":"Use the Fn::ImportValue intrinsic function to import the password value exported from a separate secrets-management stack."},{"id":"d","text":"Create a Custom Resource backed by Lambda that retrieves the secret from Secrets Manager at stack creation time and returns it as a response attribute consumed by the RDS resource."}]$json$::jsonb, $json$["b"]$json$::jsonb, $patch$The source material states: 'Dynamic references: {{resolve:ssm:/path:version}}, {{resolve:secretsmanager:secret-id:SecretString:key}}.' A Secrets Manager dynamic reference instructs CloudFormation to resolve the secret's value directly from Secrets Manager at deployment time, with no credentials ever appearing in the template, parameter inputs, or CloudFormation console. Critically, because the reference points to the secret by ID and optional key (not a pinned version), subsequent stack updates or drift-correction operations will always fetch the current secret value, accommodating password rotations. Option A uses an SSM Parameter Store SecureString dynamic reference, which is valid for some use cases but the question specifies Secrets Manager as the credential store; additionally, ssm-secure references do not support all resource property types the way Secrets Manager dynamic references do for RDS. Option C is incorrect: Fn::ImportValue only imports CloudFormation Outputs from other stacks—it cannot retrieve secrets from Secrets Manager or SSM, and would expose the secret value in a stack Output. Option D works functionally but adds unnecessary Lambda operational overhead and the secret value would be transmitted through the Custom Resource response object, which is a less secure and more complex pattern than native dynamic references.$patch$, $patch$Configuration Management and IaC$patch$,
         4, $json$[{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/dynamic-references.html","label":"AWS CloudFormation – Dynamic References to Specify Template Values"},{"url":"https://docs.aws.amazon.com/secretsmanager/latest/userguide/cfn-example_reference-secret.html","label":"AWS Secrets Manager – Using Secrets in CloudFormation Templates"}]$json$::jsonb, 'DRAFT'::"QStatus", 'claude-sonnet-4-6', false, NOW(), NOW()
  FROM "Exam" e WHERE e.code = 'DOP-C02-P7'
  AND NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM "Question" q2 WHERE q2."examId" = e.id AND q2.stem = $patch$A security team requires that a CloudFormation-managed RDS database cluster always pulls its master password from AWS Secrets Manager at deploy time, without hardcoding any credentials in the template or in CloudFormation parameters. The solution must also automatically reflect password rotations without requiring a template update. Which CloudFormation feature should the DevOps engineer use in the template?$patch$);



